    - name: '4: The Four Living Creatures'
      title: The Four Living Creatures
      number: 4
      content: "As I looked into the spirit realm, [[COMMENT(0)]] I saw a fierce
        whirlwind and a massive cloud coming toward me from the north. <smallcaps>.
        The fact that the stormy wind came from the north means that it came from
        God. This intense wind is a picture of the Spirit of God (see</smallcaps>
        Within the approaching cloud I saw raging flames of fire\u2014flames enfolding
        themselves in flames! <smallcaps>. The wind, glory cloud, and fire were all
        manifestations of the God of Pentecost.</smallcaps> And outlining the glory
        cloud was a radiant light.  And in the center of the flashing fire, I saw
        a substance of blinding brilliance with the appearance  of electrum. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  There is no doubt that Ezekiel\u2019s ecstatic vision was a glimpse
          into the eternal realm and is not meant to be interpreted only literally.     
          In Hebraic thought, the north is the dwelling place of    ). God was in
          the stormy wind. The Hebrew word for \u201Cnorth\u201D is  , which comes
          from the verb meaning \u201Cto hide.\u201D See  ;  ;    and footnote. Looking
          to the north would have been the other side of the \u201Criver of long
          ago.\u201D The One greater than Ezekiel, Jesus, also saw the heavens open
          at the Jordan River when he was thirty (see  ).      This is the same self-replenishing
          flame that Moses saw before the sacred shrub. This is the all-consuming
          fire of        Ezekiel was witnessing the phenomenon of the glory cloud
          of God, the Shekinah, which envelopes God himself coming to the earth (see 
          ;  ). God was in the blowing wind and in the overshadowing cloud. Moses
          stayed in this cloud of glory for forty days (see  ); perhaps Ezekiel did
          too.      Or \u201Ceye.\u201D Ezekiel uses this Hebrew word five times
          in ch.    (vv.  ,  ,  ,  ,  ). Why not use the usual word for \u201Clike\u201D
          or \u201Cappearance\u201D? Because the eye conveys more than the concept
          of \u201Csomething like.\u201D The eye speaks of clear vision and of the
          twinkling or sparkling of the eye.      Although the word    is not frequently
          used today, it is, in fact, the best description of what Ezekiel saw. Electrum
          is the fusion of gold (a symbol of deity) and silver (a symbol of redemption)
          into a bright metal alloy. The Hebrew word for \u201Celectrum\u201D is   
          and means \u201Csparkling.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'And I also [[COMMENT(0)]] saw standing in the middle of the storm
        what seemed  to be four creatures, each with the appearance of a man.  They
        looked like this: '
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  This encounter of the glory released a wind, a cloud, a fire,
          electrum, and the living creatures.      Fifteen times in ch.  , Ezekiel
          uses terms to show that the vision was supernatural and not ordinary. There
          were    four living creatures or literally \u201Cfour animals.\u201D However,
          he later identified them as a class or rank of \u201Ccherubim\u201D ().
          He described this experience as \u201Cvisions of God\u201D (), so it is
          possible to see in the four living creatures four expressions of God or
          four expressions of the likeness of Jesus Christ. Each one had the appearance
          of \u201Ca man.\u201D In the face of the living creatures, we see Jesus
          Christ (see  ) and his image coming forth in us.      This is the Hebrew
          word  . See also v.  . The church appears on earth as a \u201Cnew creation
          man.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Each had four faces, and each had four wings. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: "  See  . The number four signifies creation, full extent, and dominion
          (four corners of the earth, four winds, four rivers in Eden) and is found
          twelve times in this chapter. Observing the four living creatures and their
          activities, we learn something of what it means to do God\u2019s will on
          earth as it is in heaven. According to  , every Israelite was to have four
          wings (corners) on his garment, into which a blue thread was woven. These
          garment-wings (tassels interwoven with blue, the color of the sky/heaven)
          suggest that every Israelite was to be like a cherub, living in the holiness
          of God, which surrounds him in heaven.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Their legs were straight, [[COMMENT(0)]] but they had hooves  like
        calves.  Their hooves were bright and glistening like polished brass.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:7
        content: "  This is possibly a metaphor for their resolute purpose that did
          not vary or change or bend.      As the hooves of a calf are separated,
          so we are to have \u201Cseparated feet\u201D in our walk in Christ and
          walk separated from the world. We live separated from sin so that we can
          live separated unto God. See  ;  .      See  .      Believers who live
          and preach the gospel have beautiful feet, bright and glistening (see 
          ;  ). Brass is a consistent biblical symbol for judgment. See  ;  . Jesus\u2019
          feet are like gleaming metal (see  ). We need the fire of God in our walk
          with Christ.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'All four of them had faces and wings, and each of the supernatural
        beings had a pair of human hands under its wings. [[COMMENT(0)]] There were
        hands on all four sides of the living creatures. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:8
        content: "  The hands under the wings suggest that the work of our hands
          must be under the wings, or under the anointing of, God. Moses\u2019 hand
          and God\u2019s hand parted the Red Sea (see  ). Hands under wings also
          speaks of a divine partnership with man. God will use our hands to heal
          the sick and to help the poor (see  ). God anoints our hands for service.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: They joined one another with their wings, forming a square. When they
        moved forward in whatever direction, they went together as a group, without
        turning their bodies.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And all four beings had four faces: a human face in front, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        a lion\u2019s  face to the right, an ox\u2019s <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        face to the left, and an eagle\u2019s  face in the back. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:10
        content: "  From the beginning, the earliest writings of our church fathers
          taught that the four living creatures represent the four gospels, including
          the writings of Irenaeus, Epiphanius of Salamis, Jerome, Gregory the Great,
          Hippolytus, Augustine, and others. The faces of the living creatures are
          mentioned eleven times in this chapter. The face of a man suggests human
          compassion and understanding for others (see  ). From whichever direction
          a person looked at the group of the living creatures, it was the human
          face looking at them. And it was the human face that was facing the direction
          in which the whole group went (). Luke\u2019s Gospel highlights Jesus\u2019
          compassionate humanity and is the parallel to the human face here.     
          The face of a lion suggests kingship, strength, and fearless boldness in
          the face of obstacles and opposition (see  ). Matthew\u2019s Gospel brings
          before us the kingly role of Jesus, the Messiah. The lion\u2019s face is
          seen in the Lion of Judah\u2019s tribe. When you look past the frail humanity
          of others and choose not to be offended, you imitate the lion\u2019s face.     
          The face of an ox suggests patient, enduring service, even in weariness
          (see  ). An ox goes to work when called upon, whether it feels like it
          or not. Mark\u2019s Gospel presents the Son of Man as the servant of God
          and one who humbly served humanity. The ox\u2019s face is seen in the servant
          of  who carries our burdens.      The face of an eagle suggests living
          in a high spiritual place, able to soar above the things of the world (see 
          ). John\u2019s Gospel presents the eagle of eternity, one who came from
          above and ascended on high. An eagle\u2019s face is seen in Jesus, the
          heavenly Man. Each creature (animal) is a \u201Cking.\u201D The eagle is
          the king of birds. The ox is the king of domesticated animals. The lion
          is the king of the beasts. And man is the king of creation, made in the
          image and likeness of God. These four living creatures can be seen in two
          dimensions. First, as pointing to Jesus Christ, King of kings, and second,
          as the body of Christ on earth, the new creation man (see  ).    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Their wings [[COMMENT(0)]] were divided into two pairs; one pair
        was extended upward so that each one touched the wingtips of the one next
        to it,  and the other pair covered its body.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  As translated from some ancient translations, including the Septuagint.
          The Hebrew is \u201CTheir faces, their wings.\u201D      This is a display
          of perfect unity. See  ;  ;  ;  . The four gospels are also joined in perfect
          unity.      Two wings raised up in worship in unity with the others (wingtips
          touching) and two wings covering themselves in humility and service.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: And each one moved straight forward, moving where the Spirit directed
        them, [[COMMENT(0)]] and they did not turn as they moved.
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: '  See  . Ezekiel was also taken and directed by the Spirit (see 
          ).    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'These living creatures looked like burning coals of fire, like blazing
        torches. Flames flashed back and forth between the creatures. The light was
        blinding, and lightning was flashing out of it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Wheels within Wheels'
      title: Wheels within Wheels
      number: 14
      content: And the living creatures kept disappearing and reappearing like shooting
        stars. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  The Hebrew meaning of    is uncertain. One suggested meaning
          of the root word    is \u201Clightning.\u201D The implication is that the
          living creatures sped back and forth similar to lightning flashes.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'As I observed the four-faced creatures, I saw four shining wheels
        standing on the ground beside each of them. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: "  As translated from some ancient translations. The literal Hebrew
          is \u201Cbeside the creatures with four faces.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'All four wheels looked entirely alike, glittering like sparkling
        jewels. [[COMMENT(0)]] Each appeared to have another wheel inside it.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  Or \u201Ctopaz\u201D or \u201Cberyl.\u201D Most beryl crystals
          are golden-green, but some are a very dark green or blue-green. See  ; 
          ;  .      Or \u201Ca wheel intersecting a wheel,\u201D or \u201Ca second
          wheel that cut through the middle of it,\u201D or possibly \u201Ca smaller
          wheel inside it.\u201D See  . It appears, however, that the wheel inside
          a wheel forms something like a gyroscope. The Hebrew word for wheels is 
          . Some Jewish scholars,    (71.7), and one Dead Sea Scroll (4Q405) state
          that the    are angelic beings encircling the throne of God, along with
          cherubim and seraphim. Both Jerome and Gregory the Great interpreted the
          wheel inside a wheel as the New Testament spinning inside the Old (see 
          , vol. 48 [Catholic University of America Press, 1947], 75 and    [Etna,
          CA: Center for Traditionalist Orthodox Studies, 1990], 61). The motivating
          power of the living creatures was in the wheels. The power of the life
          of the believer is Christ in us. The wheel inside a wheel can be a metaphor
          for Christ in us, a divine wheel inside a wheel, even as the Father was
          a wheel inside Christ. These wheels can represent many things, but they
          surely speak of God\u2019s power, holiness, and glory.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'And the wheels were able to go in any direction the living creatures
        faced without turning to change direction. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The circumference of the rims seemed enormous, breathtaking in size,
        and all four rims were full of eyes [[COMMENT(0)]] all the way around. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:18
        content: "  \u201CFull of eyes\u201D means they can see with perfect revelation
          in all directions. The living creatures that Ezekiel saw were the same
          that John saw (see  ). Ezekiel saw the creatures with four wings and two
          hands, and John saw them with six wings. The hands had become wings (see 
          ).    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Regardless of the direction the living creatures moved, the wheels
        moved with them, and when the living creatures levitated off the ground,
        the wheels levitated also. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'And the spirit in the living creatures was also in the wheels, and
        wherever the spirit went, the creatures went. Wherever the spirit wanted
        to go, the creatures went there, and the wheels also rose and went with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: The Chariot-Throne'
      title: The Chariot-Throne
      number: 21
      content: So every time the creatures moved, or halted, or levitated, the wheels
        did also because the spirit of the living creatures was in the wheels. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: "  The living creatures went before the chariot of God\u2019s presence
          along with a windstorm, clouds, and fire. The creatures were not yoked
          to God\u2019s chariot but went before it as the Spirit of God moved them.
          Ezekiel saw God\u2019s chariot-throne.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Suspended above the living creatures I saw something that looked
        like a platform [[COMMENT(0)]] spread out above them. The platform was fearsome,
        transparent, and shining like sparkling glass.   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:22
        content: "  Or \u201Clike a dome.\u201D      Or literally \u201Clike ice.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'And under the platform were the four living creatures with wings
        outstretched and touching one another and each with a pair of wings covering
        its body. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'When they moved, I heard the awesome sound of their wings. It was
        like the noise of roaring rapids, [[COMMENT(0)]] like the voice of Shaddai,
        and like the sound of an army advancing!  And when the creatures stopped
        moving, they lowered their wings. <smallcaps>.</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:24
        content: "  See  .      The sounds of the wings are revealed in three dimensions.
          The sound of roaring waters is the Holy Spirit. The thunderous voice of
          Shaddai is the word of God, and the sound of an advancing army symbolizes
          the people of God moving out under God\u2019s leadership and power.     
          The chariot of God is an altar. The four living creatures were like the
          horns of the altar at its four corners. Their wings are like the bronze
          shell of the altar. In the midst of them is the fire burning. By dropping
          their wings, they give Ezekiel access to the altar and the grace it provides,
          access only allowed to the priests. Today, we come to the altar of God,
          his throne of grace, and receive grace to strengthen us in our time of
          need (see  ). It was only when the wings were lowered that Ezekiel could
          hear and receive the word of      "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: Then, as they stood still, I heard someone speaking from above the
        platform over their heads.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: High on the platform over their heads, I saw something that looked
        like a beautiful throne made of sapphire. [[COMMENT(0)]] And high above on
        the throne was one who had the form of a man.
      comments:
      - number: 1:26
        content: "  Or \u201Clapis lazuli,\u201D a deep blue stone with golden flecks.
          The sapphire stone on the high priest\u2019s breastplate was engraved with
          the name Simeon, which means \u201Che who hears and obeys.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'I saw what appeared to be his waist upward, and it was bright and
        dazzling metal; and from what appeared to be his waist downward, I saw what
        looked like flames of fire, giving off a brilliant light all around. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:27
        content: '  The divided likeness of a man is possibly a hint of the two natures
          of Jesus Christ, both human and divine.    '
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: The radiance of the light encircling the throne had in it every color
        of the rainbow like on the day of a downpour. [[COMMENT(0)]] This was the
        appearance of the glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! And when I saw
        this, I fell on my face. Then, I heard the voice of someone speaking to me.
      comments:
      - number: 1:28
        content: "  The rainbow is a consistent emblem of mercy. This fearful vision
          of God\u2019s glory had encircling it the beautiful mercy of God. God always
          looks at his people through the rainbow of covenant-mercy. See  ;  ;  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ezekiel Is Called to Be a Prophet'
      title: Ezekiel Is Called to Be a Prophet
      number: 1
      content: "He said to me, \u201CSon of man, [[COMMENT(0)]] rise to your feet;
        I want to talk to you.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  The phrase \u201Cson of man [Adam]\u201D is used ninety-two times
          in the book of Ezekiel to describe the prophet. In the Gospels, Jesus is
          called the Son of Man over eighty times. (Note that Jesus is never called
          the \u201Cson of    man\u201D but    Son of Man.) This term is also found
          once in Daniel () but is not used of any other prophet. As a Messianic
          title, it reveals our great High Priest, Jesus Christ, as the one who identified
          with humanity. Jesus became partaker of human nature so that believers
          could become partakers of the divine nature (see  ;  ). In taking the title
          \u201Cthe Son of Man\u201D upon himself, Jesus said that Ezekiel was a
          type of Christ.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The moment I heard these words, the Spirit [[COMMENT(0)]] flowed
        into me and set me upright on my feet. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  That is, \u201Cthe Spirit of prophecy.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "And I heard him speaking to me, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CSon
        of man, I am sending you to the rebellious sons of Israel who have refused
        allegiance to me. They and their ancestors have been in revolt against me
        up to the present day. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  Or \u201Che was addressing himself to me.\u201D The reflexive
          mood of the Hebrew verb    conveys the idea of intimate relationship. The
          voice from the throne upon the chariot speaks to the prophet.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I am sending you to a stubborn and hard-hearted people. Tell them,
        \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  God is saying to Ezekiel that every time Ezekiel speaks to the
          people, he will be speaking on God\u2019s behalf.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'And whether they listen or not, this tribe of defiant rebels will
        know that a true prophet is among them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'And you, son of man, do not be afraid of them or of anything they
        say, even though you may feel like you are stepping on thorns and sitting
        on scorpions. Do not be afraid of their angry words or intimidated by their
        glaring stares, for they are rebellion personified! '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'You are to speak my words to them whether they listen to you or rebelliously
        refuse. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: The Vision of the Scroll'
      title: The Vision of the Scroll
      number: 8
      content: "But you, son of man, listen to what I am saying to you: do not be
        like them, for they are a tribe of rebels. [[COMMENT(0)]] Now, open your
        mouth and eat what I am about to give you.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: "  Or \u201Ca house of rebels,\u201D also in  .    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Just then, I saw a hand holding a scroll reaching out to me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "He unrolled it in front of me with writing on both sides. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        On it was written \u201CLament, Mourning, and Cries of Doom.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: '  See  . Covered with writing on both sides would mean that there
          was no room for any sermons from Ezekiel, only the words of God.      On
          the scroll were listed all the judgments God was about to pour out on the
          rebellious people of Israel.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: God Feeds Ezekiel a Scroll'
      title: God Feeds Ezekiel a Scroll
      number: 1
      content: "He said to me, \u201CSon of man, eat what you see in front of you;
        eat this scroll, then go and speak to the people of Israel.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So I opened my mouth, and he fed me the scroll, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "saying, \u201CSon of man, eat this scroll I am giving to you and
        fill your belly with it.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s message inside
        his prophet (see</smallcaps> So I began to chew it, and it tasted as sweet
        as honey. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:3
        content: "  By eating the scroll, Ezekiel was accepting, absorbing, and digesting
          its contents as God\u2019s message for the people. This was a symbolic
          way of placing    ;  ). Eating the scroll would mean Ezekiel would become
          the message, not just deliver it. Isaiah\u2019s lips were touched with
          the burning coal (see  ), God\u2019s hand placed his words in Jeremiah\u2019s
          mouth (see  ), and Ezekiel ate the revelation-scroll. The prophets were
          to embody the message they preached.      See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then he said, \u201CSon of man, now go to the people of Israel and
        speak my words [[COMMENT(0)]] to them. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:4
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cspeak with my words,\u201D that is, \u201Cspeak
          my words with my authority.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "I am not sending you to a nation that speaks a difficult foreign
        language but to the people of Israel\u2014"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'not to nations whose complex languages you could not understand and
        who speak words you cannot even pronounce. Surely, if I sent you to them,
        they would listen to you, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'but the people of Israel will refuse to listen to you because they
        refuse to listen to me. The whole family of Israel has a hard heart and is
        stubbornly defiant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'But now, I will make you as stubborn and defiant as they are! [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:8
        content: "  Or \u201CI will make your face hard against their faces.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "I will make your resolve [[COMMENT(0)]] as hard as the hardest stone,
        even harder than flint. So do not fear them or be afraid because of their
        angry stares, for they are a tribe of rebels.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cyour forehead.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then he said, \u201CSon of man, listen carefully and take to heart
        everything I say to you, "
      comments: []
    - name: "11: Ezekiel\u2019s Second Vision of the Glory of God"
      title: "Ezekiel\u2019s Second Vision of the Glory of God"
      number: 11
      content: "then go to the Jews in exile and say to them, \u2018Listen to what
        Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says,\u2019 whether they listen or not.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then the Spirit lifted me up, and behind me [[COMMENT(0)]] I heard
        a loud, thunderous voice:  \u201CBlessed be the glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        in his sanctuary!\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:12
        content: "  See  ;  .      Or \u201Csound.\u201D It is possible that the
          expression of praise for the glory of God was the sound of the voices of
          the living creatures in the vision\u2014a declaration that may be understood
          here as an interpretive insertion of heavenly praise as the prophet is
          in the process of a Spirit-enabled transport. Verse    would then begin
          as a continuation of the experience of this remarkable sound of the living
          creatures\u2019 wings.      Or \u201Cfrom his place.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'I heard the sound of the living creatures as their wings kissed each
        other and the sound of the rumbling wheels beside them, like the sound of
        a great earthquake. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The Spirit lifted me up and took me away. [[COMMENT(0)]] I went in
        the heat of my spirit,  and the hand of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> rested
        powerfully upon me. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:14
        content: "  Ezekiel became the embodiment of the chariot. As the Spirit directed
          the chariot, so now he directed Ezekiel. Ezekiel flew as did the chariot.
          As the chariot appeared at the River Chebar, so now Ezekiel appeared before
          the exiles at Tel Abib (see v.  ; not to be confused with modern Tel Aviv).     
          Or \u201CI went bitterly in the anger of my spirit\u201D or \u201Cin bitterness
          and the anger of my spirit.\u201D Some commentators say that Ezekiel was
          angry over the message he was given to preach, others state that he was
          annoyed because he was being taken forcefully by the hand of God, and yet
          others believe he was angry with the righteous anger of God because of
          the sins of his people.    "
    - name: '15: Ezekiel Appointed as a Watchman'
      title: Ezekiel Appointed as a Watchman
      number: 15
      content: The Spirit took me to Tel Abib, the very place where the Jewish exiles
        were living beside the River Chebar. I remained there with them for a week,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  dumbfounded and overwhelmed   by what I had seen and heard.
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: '  This was a part of the ordination of Ezekiel. After a priest
          received his ordination, he was to withdraw from the public and stand watch
          at the doorway of the tabernacle for seven days as a test. Afterward, the
          priest would receive his ministry instruction and be assigned to his tasks.
          See  . This same pattern is seen with Ezekiel, as he first received his
          ordination (), and then God told him the essence of his task ().      Ezekiel
          was devastated by the vision of glory he witnessed. The word    is used
          in a physical sense of the destruction and devastation of a city. Clearly,
          Ezekiel was in a state of shock or in a stupor.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Afterward, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke the following words
        to me: '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CSon of man, I am appointing you as a watchman [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for the people of Israel. When you hear me speak to you, give them my warning.   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:17
        content: "  Or \u201Ca lookout,\u201D which in the Hebrew means \u201Cone
          who leans forward to peer into the distance.\u201D The primary purpose
          of the watchman was to look for the dawning day, not the dark night.     
          The Hebrew word for \u201Cwarning\u201D means \u201Cto gleam,\u201D \u201Cto
          shine upon,\u201D or \u201Cto enlighten [by caution].\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "If I say to wicked people, \u2018You are headed toward certain death,\u2019
        and you fail to give them warning by not speaking up to warn the evil ones
        against their evil courses so as to keep them alive, then the wicked ones
        will die for their sinful deeds. But I will hold you responsible for their
        deaths. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:18
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe blood I will require at your hand,\u201D a figure
          of speech denoting responsibility for the person\u2019s death. See v. 
          ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But if you do warn the wicked and they keep sinning anyway, they\u2019ll
        most certainly die for their sin, but you won\u2019t die. You\u2019ll have
        saved your life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'And if righteous people turn away from righteous living and pursue
        a life of sin, [[COMMENT(0)]] I will set calamities  before them, and they
        will die. Because you did not give them warning, they will die for their
        sinful deeds, and all the righteous deeds done earlier in life will not be
        remembered. But I will hold you responsible for their deaths. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:20
        content: "  Or \u201Ccommit iniquity [injustice].\u201D      Although the
          Hebrew is \u201Cstumbling blocks,\u201D its meaning is better conveyed
          as \u201Ccalamities.\u201D God does not set stumbling blocks in order to
          lead one into sin but calamities that will cause a person\u2019s downfall.   
          expresses the meaning more accurately in the context of    as well. God
          will put the sinner in a dangerous situation to cause them to repent.    "
    - name: "21: Ezekiel\u2019s Third Vision of \u2019s Glory"
      title: "Ezekiel\u2019s Third Vision of \u2019s Glory"
      number: 21
      content: "If, however, you do warn a righteous person not to sin and he responds
        to your warning, that person will live, and you will have also saved your
        life.\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "While I was there, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> seized me with his
        power, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s power completely
        took control of Ezekiel. God\u2019s hand can be a symbol for God\u2019s powerful
        presence, authority, or supernatural influence. Ezekiel uses this symbolic
        language seven times in association with God speaking with him or giving
        Ezekiel a vision. See</smallcaps> and he said to me, \u201CStand up, go out
        into the valley, and I will speak with you there.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe hand of  came upon me.\u201D    ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'So I got up and went down into the valley and behold, the awesome
        glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> manifested in front of me! It was
        like the vision of glory I had seen by the River Chebar, and I fell facedown. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then the Spirit [[COMMENT(0)]] flowed into me and set me on my feet.
        And I heard him say to me: \u201CGo home and shut the door behind you. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:24
        content: "  That is, \u201Cthe Spirit of prophecy.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Behold! Son of man, you are about to be tied up with ropes [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and confined to your house and unable to mingle among the people. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:25
        content: "  The early Aramaic translation, the Targum, understood this as
          a metaphor, \u201CI impose my word upon you, as restraining as a prisoner\u2019s
          chains.\u201D However, scholarly opinion is divided on whether Ezekiel\u2019s
          binding here is literal or figurative. It is very significant to note that
          in chs.  , Ezekiel is given a number of vivid, graphic actions to perform
          in public, with a powerful spiritual message accompanying them. Given this
          context, it is much more likely than not that Ezekiel\u2019s binding with
          ropes toward the end of ch.    was a literal experience.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'And I am going to make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth;
        [[COMMENT(0)]] you will be mute and unable to speak to rebuke  this rebellious
        people. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:26
        content: "  That is, God was going to bind Ezekiel\u2019s tongue. Once again,
          Ezekiel became a prophetic sign to his people. The only message he could
          give would be the message God gave him.      Or \u201Cunable to be a reprover
          [a man of reproof].\u201D  "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "But whenever I want to speak through you, I will give you back the
        power of speech. And then you will say to them, \u2018This is what Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says: If you have a heart to hear, then hear! If you refuse to listen, then
        so be it!\u2019\u2014for they are a tribe of rebels.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ezekiel Symbolizes the Siege of Jerusalem'
      title: Ezekiel Symbolizes the Siege of Jerusalem
      number: 1
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  said, \u201CSon of man, take a clay
        tile [[COMMENT(0)]] and lay it in front of you. Sketch the city of Jerusalem
        on the tile. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:1
        content: "  Or \u201Csun-dried brick [slab of clay].\u201D These clay tiles
          were used for building materials and were generally about a foot wide and
          two feet long. Ezekiel, a man of clay, was the \u201Cclay tile\u201D God
          wrote his message upon.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Build a wall around it and, to represent a siege, pile up a dirt
        ramp against the wall. Then prepare to attack it as if it were a real city.
        Surround it with armed soldiers and station battering rams on all sides. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Then take an iron frying pan [[COMMENT(0)]] and place it on edge as
        though it were an iron wall between you and the city. Then direct your gaze
        toward the city, for it is under siege and you are besieging it. This is
        to be a sign, an object lesson for the people of Israel.
      comments:
      - number: 4:3
        content: '  The iron frying pan represented the total severing of relationship,
          like an iron wall of stubbornness that stood between God and the people
          of Jerusalem.    '
    - name: '4-5: '
      title: 
      number: 4-5
      content: "\u201CThen lie down on your left side and stay like that for 390
        days. The people of Israel sinned for 390 years, and you will lie one day
        for each year they sinned. You will symbolically bear [[COMMENT(0)]] their
        guilt for as many days as you lie on that side and bear their punishment. "
      comments:
      - number: "4:4\u20135"
        content: "  Or \u201Clift up.\u201D    "
    - name: '4-5: '
      title: 
      number: 4-5
      content: "\u201CThen lie down on your left side and stay like that for 390
        days. The people of Israel sinned for 390 years, and you will lie one day
        for each year they sinned. You will symbolically bear [[COMMENT(0)]] their
        guilt for as many days as you lie on that side and bear their punishment. "
      comments:
      - number: "4:4\u20135"
        content: "  Or \u201Clift up.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'After that, lie down a second time but turn over on your right side
        and stay like that for forty days, one day for each year of the guilt of
        the people of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then direct your gaze on the model of the siege of Jerusalem, shake
        your fist at the city [[COMMENT(0)]] and prophesy against her. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:7
        content: '  Like a warrior prepared for battle, Ezekiel was to act like he
          was threatening the city to attack it. See  .    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Behold, I am going to tie you up, and you will not be able to turn
        from one side to the other until the period of your seclusion is over. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s
        temple-presence in Jerusalem, as the religious capital of both Israel and
        Judah. Additionally, 430 years was the duration Israel spent as slaves in
        Egypt.</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cuntil you have finished the days of your siege(s).\u201D
          Ezekiel was commanded to be bound with ropes and to lie on his side for
          a total of 430 days as a sign of the guilt of Israel and Judah. The calculation
          of the years must be made in a religious sense, not political. For 390
          years, Jerusalem was the religious capital of all Israel, even during the
          divided monarchy. The only time Jerusalem was the capital of Judah alone
          was for the 40 years before Josiah recaptured the northern region of Israel.
          The sins referred to here are in reference to the 430 years of sins against      "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CNow take some wheat, barley, beans, lentils, and other grains;
        [[COMMENT(0)]] store them all together and make bread for yourself. This
        will be your food for the 390 days you are lying on your side. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cmillet and spelt [emmer],\u201D which are grains not
          generally used for bread.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Of these grains, make a small loaf of bread [[COMMENT(0)]] at a set
        time each day. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cweigh out twenty shekels [about 8 ounces or 220 grams]
          for a daily portion.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'And you are to ration the water you drink to two cups [[COMMENT(0)]]
        at a set time each day. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe sixth part of a hin,\u201D about 1.26 pints (0.6
          liter).    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Eat the food as you would a barley cake. While everyone can see you,
        build a fire with dried human excrement, then bake the bread on the coals.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:12
        content: "  Ezekiel\u2019s actions were meant to dramatize symbolically what
          would happen during the siege of Jerusalem. There would be little food
          and water and little or no fuel to build fires to cook it. And the same
          situation would follow them when they would be taken into captivity. Additionally,
          the mixture of polluted bread and its strange odor can symbolize the traditions
          of men that Paul said were like \u201Cmanure\u201D (; see  ).    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said, \u201CIn this same way the
        Israelites will have to eat defiled food among the nations where I will disperse
        them.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then I replied, \u201COh no! Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        I have never defiled myself, from childhood until now. I have never eaten
        meat from any animal that died a natural death or was killed by wild animals.
        Nothing unclean has ever entered my mouth.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:14
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CVery well,\u201D he said, \u201CI will let you use dried cow
        manure [[COMMENT(0)]] instead of human excrement as fuel to bake your bread.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:15
        content: '  Dried cow dung is commonly used as fuel in the East.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then he added, \u201CSon of man, I am going to cut off Jerusalem\u2019s
        food supply. In their horrible distress, the food they eat and the water
        they drink will be rationed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "They will watch as it all runs out and look at each other in total
        despair. And they will slowly die of starvation [[COMMENT(0)]] because of
        their guilt.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:17
        content: "  Or literally \u201Crot and decay.\u201D There are four prophetic
          signs given in chs.  . (1) The sign of the model of Jerusalem,  . (2) The
          sign of the prophet lying bound on his side,  . (3) The sign of the defiled
          bread,  . (4) The sign of the barber\u2019s razor,  . It appears that all
          these prophetic signs took place during the period of Ezekiel\u2019s silence
          (). These signs became more eloquent than words.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ezekiel Shaves His Hair'
      title: Ezekiel Shaves His Hair
      number: 1
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  said, \u201CSon of man, take a sharp
        sword; use it like a barber\u2019s razor and shave your head and beard. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then take scales and divide the hair into three piles. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:1
        content: '  The sharp sword is a metaphor for the king of Babylon. The hair
          of a priest was a mark of his consecration to serve God (see  ;  ). Shaving
          the head was a sign of humiliation (see  ), catastrophe (see  ), and mourning
          (see  ;  ;  ).    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When the days of your siege are over, burn up a third in the midst
        of the city of Jerusalem. [[COMMENT(0)]] Take another third and chop it up
        with the sword around the perimeter of the tile-city.  Then scatter the last
        third to the wind. I will pursue those who escape the city with my sword.   '
      comments:
      - number: 5:2
        content: '  The third of his hair that Ezekiel burns represents the people
          who will die at the time Jerusalem is destroyed (see  ).      This third
          of his hair represents those who will die by the sword when trying to escape
          Jerusalem.      This third of his hair represents those who escape Jerusalem,
          are scattered among the nations, but will later be killed (see  ).    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Also keep back a few hairs and wrap them up in the folds of your
        cloak. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 5:3
        content: '  These few hairs represent the remnant that is spared (see  ).    '
    - name: '4: God Promises to Destroy Jerusalem'
      title: God Promises to Destroy Jerusalem
      number: 4
      content: "And of those, take just a few hairs and throw them on the fire and
        burn them. [[COMMENT(0)]] That fire will spread to all the people of Israel.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 5:4
        content: '  These few hairs represent some of the exiles who will still be
          destroyed.      That is, God will continue to punish the people of Israel.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Listen to what the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CThis
        represents Jerusalem. I have placed her in the center of the nations, encircled
        by foreign countries. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Yet she has rebelled more wickedly against my ways [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and against my laws than the gentile nations that surround her. Indeed, she
        has deliberately rejected my commands and not kept my laws.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 5:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cregulations,\u201D \u201Cdecisions,\u201D or \u201Cjudgments.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Therefore, the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u201CBecause
        you acted more wickedly than the nations around you, since you do not keep
        my laws or respect my commands, and since you do not respect even the moral
        standards of the surrounding nations, [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 5:7
        content: "  As translated from the most reliable Hebrew manuscripts. However,
          a number of Hebrew manuscripts and the Syriac read \u201CYou have acted
          according to the laws of the nations around you.\u201D That is, Israel
          not only exceeded the other nations in wickedness, but they also added
          heathen customs to their apostasy. See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "therefore, behold\u2014I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, declare
        that I am against you. And I will pass my judgment on you for all the nations
        to see. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Because of all your loathsome practices, I am coming against you
        more severely than I have ever done before or will ever do again. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: As a result, those of you who are parents will eat their children,
        and children will eat their parents. I will punish you and scatter what remains
        of you to the winds.
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CFor as surely as I live, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        declare: because you have defiled my sanctuary with all your horrible and
        loathsome practices, I will withdraw from you and will not even glance on
        you with pity or spare you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Inside Jerusalem, a third of your people will die of plague or starvation.
        Outside the city, a third will fall by the sword. And a third I will scatter
        to the winds and pursue with my sword. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: Then my anger will come to an end [[COMMENT(0)]] and be fully spent
        against them, and then my justice will have been satisfied. When I have carried
        out my anger against them, they will know how jealous I am for them. Afterward,
        they will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken in my zeal.
      comments:
      - number: 5:13
        content: "  Or literally \u201CI will make my fury quiet.\u201D  "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CMoreover, I will reduce you to a heap of ruins, an object of
        scorn to the surrounding nations, in the eyes of all who pass by. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: You will be mocked and insulted. Your downfall will be an appalling
        lesson to the surrounding nations. This will happen when I execute judgment
        on you in my furious anger and with my furious punishment. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CI will release against them the deadly arrows of famine\u2014arrows
        of destruction! Then I will make the famine even worse and cut off your food
        supply. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "I will send severe famine and wild animals against you to rob you
        of your children. Sickness and bloodshed will overtake you, and I will bring
        the sword down upon you. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: God Condemns Idolatry'
      title: God Condemns Idolatry
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me: [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 6:1
        content: "  Or \u201CThe word of  came to me.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward the mountains of Israel and prophesy
        against them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Say to them, \u2018Mountains of Israel, hear the words of Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
        He prophesies to the mountains and hills, to the ravines and valleys: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I
        am wielding a sword against youand I will demolish your shrines."
      comments:
      - number: 6:3
        content: "  The mountains, hills, ravines, and valleys were places where
          the people had set up altars to false gods, also known as \u201Chigh places\u201D
          because they were on raised platforms where the people would offer sacrifices.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Your altars will be deserted,and your incense altars will be smashed.I
        will slay your people before your idols. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 6:4
        content: "  The term    only occurs in the plural form. Ezekiel used it some
          thirty-nine times in his prophecy. The usual meaning indicated in these
          prophetic contexts is that of \u201Cidols.\u201D However, the root sense
          of the term may denote \u201Clogs,\u201D \u201Cblocks,\u201D or shapeless
          things in general. And it even carries the sense of \u201Cdung pellets.\u201D
          It may be argued that the use of this term in Ezekiel\u2019s prophecy is
          a derisive one.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: I will lay the corpses of the Israelitesbefore their idols,and I will
        scatter your bones all around your altars.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: Wherever you live,your cities will be ruinedand your shrines deserted.All
        your altars will be destroyed and desecrated,and your idols shall be broken
        and banished.Your incense altars will be chopped down,and all your works
        wiped out.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: The slain will lie everywhere in your midst,and you will know that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will spare some of you who escape the sword when
        you are scattered among the nations. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Those who escape will remember me among the nations where they are
        exiles. They will remember how my heart was crushed by their promiscuous
        ways when they turned their hearts away from me and by their wandering eyes
        that lusted after idols. They will loathe themselves for the evil things
        they did and all their detestable practices. '
      comments: []
    - name: "10: \u2019s Punishment for Idolatry"
      title: "\u2019s Punishment for Idolatry"
      number: 10
      content: "And they will realize that it was no idle threat when I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        declared that I would bring this severe punishment upon them.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Hear the words of Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>: \u201CStomp
        your feet angrily and pound your fist, and say, \u2018How awful!\u2019 over
        all the evil abominations of the people of Israel. For they will fall by
        the sword, by food shortages, and by plague."
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CThose far away will die by the plague,those nearby shall fall
        by the sword,and those who survive will die of hunger.They will experience
        the fullness of my fury!"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CAnd you will be convinced that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        when their corpses lie scattered around their idols and around their altars,
        on every high hill, on every mountaintop, under every spreading tree, and
        under every leafy oak\u2014every place where they have offered soothing incense
        to all their lifeless idols. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "I will stretch out my mighty arm against them and turn the land wherever
        they live into a complete wasteland from the desert to Riblah. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        And when this happens, they will be convinced that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 6:14
        content: "  As translated from some Hebrew manuscripts. Riblah was a town
          in Syria, about 95 miles (153 kilometers) north of Damascus (see  ;  ; 
          ). The majority of manuscripts have \u201CDiblah,\u201D an unknown location.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The End Has Come'
      title: The End Has Come
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, tell the people of Israel what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to the land of Israel: \u2018Finished! The end has come over all the
        land. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe four corners of the land.\u201D The sense of the
          term  , which means \u201Cend,\u201D here implies the end of God\u2019s
          forbearance and the beginning of judgment (see  ; LaMar Eugene Cooper,   
          [United States: Broadman &amp; Holman Publishers, 1994], 110).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Now the end has come. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, when he will judge
        the world and those who walk in darkness. See</smallcaps> I will unleash
        my anger on you and judge you for the way you have lived. I will judge you
        for all your loathsome practices. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:3
        content: '  Chapter    is best seen as a funeral dirge, a lament over the
          fall of Jerusalem. The frequent repetition emphasizes the message of judgment
          and doom hanging over Jerusalem. The verses are filled with deep emotion
          with a note of finality. This becomes a preview of the coming day of   
          ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I will not show you pity nor spare you. [[COMMENT(0)]] Indeed, I
        will punish you for your conduct\u2014the despicable evil you have done.
        Then you all will be convinced that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 7:4
        content: '  It is important to see that God is both the Father of Mercy and
          the God of Judgment. See  .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CThe Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u2018Look! An
        unheard-of disaster is coming. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:5
        content: "  Or \u201COne disaster after another.\u201D The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "It\u2019s all over for you! The end is near! [[COMMENT(0)]] Doom
        is awakened against you.  Behold, the fateful day! "
      comments:
      - number: 7:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe end has come.\u201D There is some ambiguity about
          the precise meaning of the verb  . The context suggests either that the
          end has arrived or is about to.      The Hebrew has a play on words. The
          Hebrew words for \u201Cend\u201D and \u201Cawakened\u201D are homonyms
          (words with the same triconsonantal root).    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Now it is your turn to be punished. You who dwell in this land, doom
        is coming, for the day of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> is near. The people
        will be shouting in panic, not shouting with joy at the shrines on the mountaintops.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 7:7
        content: "  The mountain summits in Canaan were universally associated with
          idolatrous Israelite worship of local deities, epitomized by the numerous
          references to \u201Chigh places\u201D throughout the Old Testament historical
          books and canonical prophets.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Very soon I will vent my fury on you and punish you until my anger
        is finished. I will judge you for the way you live and punish you for all
        your loathsome practices. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Day of Judgment'
      title: The Day of Judgment
      number: 9
      content: "I will show you no mercy nor spare you, but I will punish you for
        your conduct and for all your detestable deeds. Then you will know that I
        am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> who has punished you.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cwho strikes the blow.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Now is the day of disaster. Behold, your doom has
        come! Brutality has blossomed, and pride is at its peak. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:10
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cthe crown has come, has come out, the rod
          has blossomed.\u201D Some Jewish scholars see the \u201Crod\u201D as Nebuchadnezzar.
          The Hebrew meaning, however, remains uncertain.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Violence has grown up into a rod to punish their wickedness. None
        of these proud, evil people will survive. All their wealth and prestige will
        be swept away. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 7:11
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cnot from them, nor from their multitude, nor
          from their tumult, and they are worthless.\u201D The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The time of your doom is before you; the day of reckoning has come.
        Let not the buyer be happy nor the seller be sad, [[COMMENT(0)]] for wrath
        is upon the entire multitude. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:12
        content: '  That is, commerce will end and have no more place in the land.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'For the seller will not be able to return to what has been sold while
        they live. For the vision concerns them all. Each persists in sin, and no
        one will hold on to their lives. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: The Sins of Israel'
      title: The Sins of Israel
      number: 14
      content: "The trumpet sounds, everyone gets ready, but no one goes into battle,
        since my anger rests on everyone alike.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Enemies [[COMMENT(0)]] are lurking outside the
        city; inside are disease and starvation. Anyone out in the countryside will
        die in battle; anyone in the city will die by starvation and plague. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:15
        content: "  Or \u201CThe sword.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'And those who escape will flee to the mountains, moaning like doves
        of the valleys, each one moaning for his sin. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Every hand will grow weak. Gripped with fear, they wet themselves.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 7:17
        content: "  Literally \u201Call knees walk [with] water,\u201D a euphemism
          for \u201Cthey can no longer hold their water [bladder].\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Terror covers them as they put on sackcloth. Shame covers their faces
        as they shave their heads bald. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 7:18
        content: '  Shaving their heads was a cultural sign of grief and disgrace.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "They will throw their silver away in the streets and their gold like
        filthy menstrual rags. [[COMMENT(0)]] Their wealth will not be able to save
        them on the day of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s fury. For it will
        be worthless on that day to buy food to fill their stomachs since it was
        their wealth that led them into sin. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:19
        content: '  The Hebrew word    implies menstrual impurity.    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Once they were so proud of their beautiful jewelry, out of which
        they made their disgusting, horrible idols. Now I have made their wealth
        and jewels repulsive to them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'I will give your wealth to foreigners, as spoils of war to the evilest
        people on earth, and they will profane it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: I will turn my face away from them [[COMMENT(0)]] while my hidden,
        treasured place  is profaned and thugs force their way in and defile it.
      comments:
      - number: 7:22
        content: "  That is, God will lift his divine, protecting presence from them.     
          Although unstated, God\u2019s \u201Chidden, treasured place\u201D was his
          sanctuary in his temple.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Prepare plenty of chains to bind up the captives.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] For the country is full of bloodshed and murders,  and the
        city is full of violence, "
      comments:
      - number: 7:23
        content: "  Or literally \u201CMake the  .\u201D This is the only place in
          the Bible the word    occurs, and it is of uncertain meaning. The root
          word means \u201Cto bind [with chains],\u201D or possibly \u201Ctie up
          [with ropes].\u201D One ancient translation reads instead \u201CEverything
          is in confusion.\u201D      Or \u201Cjudgments of bloods,\u201D that is,
          such crimes involving the shedding of blood were deserving of death.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'so I will bring evil nations here to seize their homes. I will put
        an end to the pride of their elite, [[COMMENT(0)]] and their sanctuary will
        be profaned. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe pride of the powerful.\u201D  "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Panic is on the way! They will look for peace but never find it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'One disaster will follow another, with rumor upon rumor. They will
        seek a vision from the prophet but in vain. The priestly teaching of the
        divine law will be destroyed, along with the counsel of the elders. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "The king will go into mourning, the officials will be wrapped in
        despair, and the hands of the people will tremble in terror. I will punish
        them for the way they have lived and judge them the same way as they have
        judged others. Then they will be convinced that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Ezekiel\u2019s Fourth Vision of the Glory of God"
      title: "Ezekiel\u2019s Fourth Vision of the Glory of God"
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]In the sixth year of our exile, on the fifth day
        of the sixth month, <smallcaps>.</smallcaps> the elders of Judah and I were
        sitting in my home. Suddenly, I felt the mighty power  of the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        come over me.'
      comments:
      - number: 8:1
        content: "    is the second panel (B) in the chiastic parallel structure
          in Ezekiel. This section contains a series of visions relating to idolatry
          in the temple (see chs.  ) and the departure of the glory cloud from the
          temple (see chs.  )\u2014a sign representing God\u2019s abandonment of
          his people as a punishment for their idolatrous rebellion against him over
          many years. Note, however, that    and following record the promise that
          God will return his people from captivity in due course and renew them
          spiritually as well. This section\u2014panel B\u2014constitutes the contrasting
          parallel with panel B  in chs.  , where Ezekiel is given a vision of the
          glory cloud returning to the temple (see ch.  ) and the renewal of the
          priestly service in the temple, reserved exclusively for the ministry of
          the faithful Zadokite priests (see ch.  ). See    and following in particular.     
          This date is probably September 17, 592 BC, fourteen months after Ezekiel\u2019s
          first vision. Chapter    introduces a new series of Ezekiel\u2019s visions,
          which refer to Jerusalem and the remnant of Judah during King Zedekiah\u2019s
          reign. Ezekiel is transported by the Spirit (see  ;  ;  ) from Babylon
          to Jerusalem to see the vile activities of the people of Israel in the
          temple of        Or \u201Chand,\u201D a symbol of the power of God.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Behold, I saw a fiery human figure. [[COMMENT(0)]] His body looked
        like fire! Below the waist were flames of fire; above the waist he glistened
        as bright as glowing bronze.   '
      comments:
      - number: 8:2
        content: "  Most translations follow the Greek Septuagint that reads \u201Cthe
          appearance of a man\u201D; however, the Hebrew is \u201Cthe appearance
          of fire,\u201D and The Passion Translation team has chosen to merge both
          concepts.      See  .    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "He reached out with what seemed like a hand and grabbed me by my
        hair. Then, in a great and wonderful vision [[COMMENT(0)]] from God, the
        Spirit lifted me up high in the air  and transported me to Jerusalem. He
        took me to the entrance of the north gate of the inner court where the disgusting
        idol  that provokes <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s jealousy was standing.   "
      comments:
      - number: 8:3
        content: "  Although the Hebrew is plural (literally \u201Cvisions\u201D),
          it is used here as a Hebrew plural intensive.      Or \u201Cbetween heaven
          and earth,\u201D which can be emblematic of the mid-heaven realm of the
          soul or mind of man.      Or \u201Cthe idol of idolatry\u201D or \u201Cthe
          statue that outrages,\u201D which was likely the Canaanite goddess Asherah
          (see  ), the Syrian precursor to Venus.      See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: Idolatry in the Temple'
      title: Idolatry in the Temple
      number: 4
      content: And all at once, the dazzling glory of the God of Israel appeared!
        It looked like what I had seen in the Euphrates Valley.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then God said, \u201CSon of man, look now to the north.\u201D So,
        I raised my eyes to the north, and standing there, north of the pathway entrance
        of the altar gate was this vile statue that infuriates God. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 8:5
        content: '  All who entered the inner courtyard of the temple by the north
          gate had to pass close to this idol.    '
    - name: '6: The Leaders of Israel Practicing Secret Idolatry'
      title: The Leaders of Israel Practicing Secret Idolatry
      number: 6
      content: "And he said to me, \u201CSon of man, do you see what they are doing?
        Look at all the repulsive, loathsome things that the people of Israel are
        practicing here! Their disgusting deeds drive me farther and farther from
        my sanctuary. And you will see even more shocking things than these.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He next transported me to the entrance to the outer courtyard. I
        looked carefully and noticed there was a hole in the wall. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "He said, \u201CSon of man, dig through the wall.\u201D When I dug
        into the wall, I discovered a doorway. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "He said, \u201CNow, go in and look at the shocking, despicable things
        they are doing inside.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So I went through the door, and I noticed the walls were covered
        with drawings [[COMMENT(0)]] of every kind of snake, bugs, creeping things, 
        repulsive animals, and all the disgusting idols of the people of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:10
        content: "  Or \u201Ccarvings.\u201D      These creeping things pertain to
          the dust realm, with humanistic wisdom twisting the Scriptures to violate
          truth.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Worshiping these animals were seventy leaders of Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and standing among them was Jaazaniah  son of Shaphan. Each one had an incense
        burner in his hand, from which rose a fragrant cloud of incense. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:11
        content: '  That is, the Sanhedrin, seventy leaders who were chosen to instruct
          the people of God. Ezekiel discovered they were in fact leading the people
          into idolatry.      Although difficult to identify with absolute certainty,
          this may have been the Jaazaniah who was one of those responsible for the
          reforms of King Josiah (see  ).    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "God said to me, \u201CSon of man, have you seen what these leaders
        of Israel are doing in secret, each one worshiping in his own personal shrine?
        They say, \u2018Oh, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> cannot see us; he has left
        the land.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: The Women of Judah Worshiping Tammuz'
      title: The Women of Judah Worshiping Tammuz
      number: 13
      content: "Then God said, \u201CThis is not even the worst of the practices.
        You will see things more terrible than this.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Next he took me to the entrance of the north gate of the temple of
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> where women were weeping over the death of
        the god Tammuz. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:14
        content: "  This is the only place in the Bible where the worship of Tammuz
          is mentioned. It dates back as far as 3000 BC. The passage here refers
          to a religious ceremony of an annual feast of mourning for Tammuz (precursor
          of Adonis) every year in the month of Tammuz (June\u2013July) to commemorate
          the period of his stay in the underworld.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "He said, \u201CSon of man, do you see their worship of Tammuz? You
        will see even more terrible things than that.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Next he transported me to the north gate to the inner court of his
        temple. And there, at the entrance to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sanctuary, between the porch and the altar, [[COMMENT(0)]] were about twenty-five
        men standing with their faces to the east worshiping the sun with their backs
        to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s sanctuary. They bowed down to the
        east, before the rising sun. "
      comments:
      - number: 8:16
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "God said to me, \u201CSon of man, do you see this? It is bad enough
        that the people of Judah are doing these despicable things, but they also
        spread violence throughout the land and provoke my anger further! Look at
        how they insult me in every possible way they can. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 8:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey put the branch to their nose.\u201D This was something
          done in Assyrian religious practices (see Martin Haug,    [United Kingdom:
          Houghton, Osgood, 1878], 4). Some scholars see this act as a vile attempt
          to insult God with crude gestures. Whatever their actual action was, it
          was a provocative attempt to insult and scorn the living God, the God of
          Israel.  "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Therefore, with wrath I will deal with them. I will show neither
        pity nor mercy. They can cry to me as loudly as they want, but I will not
        listen to them.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Slaughter of Those with No Mark'
      title: The Slaughter of Those with No Mark
      number: 1
      content: "Then I heard the Lord shout loudly for me to hear, \u201CExecutioners,
        draw near! [[COMMENT(0)]] Each bring your weapon of destruction!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 9:1
        content: "  Or \u201CThe executioners have drawn near.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Immediately six men [[COMMENT(0)]] advanced from the upper north
        gate,  each one holding a deadly weapon. Also, I saw with them a man clothed
        in white linen,  with a scribe\u2019s case  tied to his belt. They came and
        stood in front of the bronze altar.   "
      comments:
      - number: 9:2
        content: "  That is, angels.      This upper gate was built by Jotham (see 
          ), also called the Benjamin Gate (  means \u201CSon of My Right Hand\u201D;
          see  ) and was also known as the New Gate (the dawning of a new day; see 
          ;  ).      This man in linen was an angel, or messenger, and was the seventh
          man that Ezekiel saw. White linen is a frequent biblical symbol of righteousness.     
          This was a writing kit that contained an inkhorn and pen.      The bronze
          altar is the place of sacrifice. For believers today, it represents the
          cross of Christ.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then the dazzling glory of the God of Israel rose from above the
        cherubim where it had been resting and moved toward the threshold of the
        temple. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then he called to the man dressed in white linen with
        a scribe\u2019s case at his side, "
      comments:
      - number: 9:3
        content: '  The glory of the Lord had moved from its place over the cherubim-throne
          in the Holy of Holies to the threshold (or possibly outer gates) of the
          temple. God was reluctant to leave his throne in Jerusalem, waiting for
          the people to have a change of heart and repent.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to him, \u201CGo throughout
        Jerusalem, and place a mark [[COMMENT(0)]] on the foreheads of all who grieve
        and are greatly distressed over all the disgusting things done in the city.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 9:4
        content: "  Or \u201Ctav,\u201D the last letter of the Hebrew alphabet that
          in ancient Hebrew was shaped somewhat like \u201CX,\u201D the mark of a
          cross. Another possible meaning of    is \u201Cdesire.\u201D      Those
          with discernment, the intercessors who agonized over Israel\u2019s demise,
          were spared. The righteous were left behind (see  ;  ). Their \u201Cforeheads\u201D
          were marked, for their thoughts were turned toward God and his glory. Those
          with no \u201Cmark [cross]\u201D on their foreheads (thoughts) were those
          walking in the mindset of man. See  .    "
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "And I heard him say to the other six, \u201CFollow the man in white
        linen through the city and strike down everyone with no mark on their forehead\u2014old
        men, young men, girls, children, women\u2014kill them all. Show no mercy,
        not even one glance of pity. But do not touch anyone with a mark on his forehead.
        And begin at my sanctuary.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] So, they began with those
        men in front of the temple and with the elders. "
      comments:
      - number: "9:5\u20136"
        content: '  See    and first footnote.    '
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "And I heard him say to the other six, \u201CFollow the man in white
        linen through the city and strike down everyone with no mark on their forehead\u2014old
        men, young men, girls, children, women\u2014kill them all. Show no mercy,
        not even one glance of pity. But do not touch anyone with a mark on his forehead.
        And begin at my sanctuary.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] So, they began with those
        men in front of the temple and with the elders. "
      comments:
      - number: "9:5\u20136"
        content: '  See    and first footnote.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "He said to the executioners, \u201CGo make my temple unfit for worship.
        Fill its courtyard with corpses. Now get to work.\u201D They departed and
        began to strike the people throughout the city."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "While they were slaying, I was left alone in the temple. I threw
        myself facedown on the ground and cried out, \u201COh, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        are you really going to wipe out the remnant of Israel by venting your fury
        on Jerusalem?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "He answered me, \u201CThe guilt of the people of Israel and Judah
        is enormous. The land is full of bloodshed, and Jerusalem full of perverted
        justice. They say, \u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> can\u2019t see us!
        He has abandoned the nation.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So, I no longer will show them any mercy nor give them one glance
        of pity. They hereby suffer the consequences of their own behavior.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Just then, the man dressed in white linen with the scribe\u2019s
        case came back and made his report: \u201CIt is finished; I have carried
        out your orders.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 9:11
        content: '  God is using symbolic and metaphorical language in the book of
          Ezekiel. The man clothed in linen is a picture of our Savior. The only
          one worthy of this task is our Lord Jesus Christ, and he is the one who
          places this mark or seal upon the heads of believers. See  ;  . He is the
          one who fulfills the will of his Father (see  ). We are marked or sealed
          with the Holy Spirit (see  ;  ;  ;  ;  ).  '
  - verses:
    - name: "1: God\u2019s Glory Leaves the Temple"
      title: "God\u2019s Glory Leaves the Temple"
      number: 1
      content: 'Then I saw a vision. On top of the dome over the heads of the cherubim,
        I saw something that looked like a sapphire throne. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to the man dressed in white linen,
        \u201CGo among the whirling wheels below the cherubim and take a handful
        of burning coals from between the living creatures and scatter them over
        the city.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] While I was watching, he went in among the
        whirling wheels."
      comments:
      - number: 10:2
        content: '  See  ;  ;  . Spreading the burning coals around the city of Jerusalem
          was a prophetic act that prophesied the eventual burning and destruction
          of the city.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The cherubim were on the south side of the temple as the man went
        in, and the billowing glory cloud filled the inner courtyard. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:3
        content: '  See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The dazzling glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> rose from between
        the cherubim and rested over the entrance of the temple. The temple was filled
        with the cloud, and the court was full of the radiance of the glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The noise of the living creatures\u2019 wings was as loud as the
        voice of God Almighty! [[COMMENT(0)]] The people could even hear it in the
        outer courtyard!"
      comments:
      - number: 10:5
        content: "  Or \u201CEl Shaddai.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Afterward, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> commanded the man dressed
        in white linen to go among the wheels and take fire that was burning among
        the cherubim. So, the man went among them and stood beside one of the wheels. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: One of the living creatures then reached his hand into the fire between
        the cherubim and took some fire and placed it into the hands of the man dressed
        in white linen, who took it and left.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'It seemed that the living creatures had what looked like a human
        hand under their wings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'I saw the four wheels by the living creatures, one wheel beside each
        living creature. And the wheels sparkled like precious gemstones. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cberyl.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: Each wheel appeared to be [[COMMENT(0)]] identical with another wheel
        inside it.
      comments:
      - number: 10:10
        content: '  The Hebrew text indicates that there was an    similarity between
          the wheels (with each having another wheel inside it). This lack of precise
          language in the description of the elements of prophetic visions is a common
          feature of the book of Ezekiel.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'As the wheels moved, they would go in any one of the four directions
        the living creatures faced, without having to turn around. They went in whatever
        direction their head faced without turning as they went. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Their entire bodies, their backs, their hands, their wings\u2014along
        with all four of their wheels\u2014were covered with eyes all around. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "I heard a voice refer to the wheels as \u201Cwhirling wheels.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Each living creature had four faces; the first was a cherub\u2019s
        face, the second a human face, the third a lion\u2019s face, and the fourth
        an eagle\u2019s face. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then the cherubim rose to the sky. They were the same living creatures
        I had seen by the River Chebar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'When the living creatures moved as a group in any direction, the
        wheels followed them, and when the living creatures levitated off the ground
        by spreading their wings, the wheels did not leave their place beside them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: When the living creatures stopped, the wheels stopped; when the former
        rose, the wheels rose with them, since they shared the same living Spirit.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 10:17
        content: "  The living creatures went before the chariot of God\u2019s presence
          along with a windstorm, clouds, and fire (see  ). The creatures were not
          yoked to God\u2019s chariot but went before it as the Spirit of God moved
          them. Ezekiel saw God\u2019s chariot-throne.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then the dazzling glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> departed
        from the entrance of the temple and hovered over the living creatures. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "They spread their wings, and before my eyes, I saw them levitate
        from the ground, with the wheels spinning beside them. Then they paused at
        the entrance to the eastern gate of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        temple, with the dazzling glory of the God of Israel shining over them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'These were the same living creatures I had seen beneath the throne
        of the God of Israel by the River Chebar; I knew that they were cherubim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Each had four faces, [[COMMENT(0)]] four wings, and what appeared
        to be human hands under their wings. '
      comments:
      - number: 10:21
        content: "  The word \u201Cfour\u201D () is written twice\u2014an instance
          of dittography.  "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: Each one moved straight ahead. Their faces were identical to those
        I had seen by the River Chebar.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Jerusalem\u2019s Corrupt Leaders"
      title: "Jerusalem\u2019s Corrupt Leaders"
      number: 1
      content: "God\u2019s Spirit [[COMMENT(0)]] swept me off my feet and transported
        me to the eastern gate of the temple of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. And
        behold, there at the entrance to the gate facing east stood twenty-five men, 
        including the two officials Jaazaniah son of Azzur and Pelatiah son of Benaiah."
      comments:
      - number: 11:1
        content: "  Or \u201CA wind.\u201D      It is likely that these twenty-five
          men were the same as those mentioned in  .    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]] said to me, \u201CSon
        of man, these men are making evil plans to spread their wicked counsel throughout
        this city. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:2
        content: "  As found in the Septuagint and Syriac. The Hebrew is \u201Che.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "They say, \u2018Isn\u2019t it time to start building houses again?
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Jerusalem is like an iron storage pot, and we are like meat,
        stored safely away.\u2019   "
      comments:
      - number: 11:3
        content: "  Or possibly \u201CThis is not yet the time to be building houses.\u201D     
          Or \u201CThe city [Jerusalem] is a cooking pot, and we are the meat.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Therefore, prophesy against them. Prophesy, son of man!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then the Spirit of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> fell [[COMMENT(0)]]
        on me, and said to me, \u201CTell the people: \u2018I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to the people of Israel, I know what you think, your every secret thought. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:5
        content: '  That is, the Holy Spirit overpowered the prophet. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You have murdered so many people in this city that its streets are
        filled with corpses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this: Yes, this
        city is the pot, and the corpses you have thrown into the streets, they are
        the meat! But I will drive you out of the city. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:7
        content: "  As translated from most ancient versions. The Hebrew is, \u201CHe
          has brought you out of it [the city].\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Are you afraid of the sword? Then I will bring the sword against
        you, declares the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'And I will bring you to justice and will drive you out of Jerusalem
        and hand you over to foreigners! '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'I will judge you at the border of Israel and you will fall by the
        sword. Then you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'For this city will not be your safe storage pot, nor will you be
        the meat inside. I will execute justice on you on the border of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "And then you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, whose
        laws and commands you have disobeyed. Instead, you have embraced the customs
        of the neighboring nations.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: "13: Hope for Israel\u2019s Restoration"
      title: "Hope for Israel\u2019s Restoration"
      number: 13
      content: "While I was prophesying, Pelatiah son of Benaiah dropped dead. I
        threw myself facedown to the ground and cried out, \u201COh no, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        are you going to annihilate the remnant left in Israel?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the people living in Jerusalem are talking about
        you, your close relatives, and all the people of Israel. They are saying
        that the people in exile are away from <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. \u2018This
        country was given to us as our possession!\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 11:15
        content: '  Jeremiah had already prophesied that  would favor the exiles,
          not those spared from deportation (see  ). Now, those left behind and living
          in the land considered themselves the chosen ones of the nation.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Now give this message to your fellow exiles: \u2018The Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Although I have sent you far away among the nations and I have
        scattered you to foreign countries, yet I have been your sanctuary [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for the time being  wherever you have gone.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 11:16
        content: "  See  .      Or \u201Cto some extent\u201D or \u201Cfor a little
          while.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "And tell them, \u2018The Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says
        this: I will gather you back from the peoples, and draw you together from
        the countries where you have been scattered and give you the land of Israel.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 11:17
        content: "  Literally \u201Cthe dirt [dust] of Israel,\u201D possibly a hint
          that God will give them the \u201Cnature\u201D of Israel (  means \u201Ca
          prince with God\u201D; see    and footnote).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'When you return, [[COMMENT(0)]] you will purge the land of all its
        filthy idols and detestable practices. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:18
        content: '  That is, when they return to the Father, not just return to the
          land.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "I will give you a new, undivided heart, [[COMMENT(0)]] and I will
        put a new spirit in you. I will remove your stubborn heart of stone and give
        you a tender heart that responds to me\u2014a devoted heart.   "
      comments:
      - number: 11:19
        content: "  Or \u201Ca different heart\u201D (LXX) or \u201CI will give them
          one [undivided] heart.\u201D For the believer today, this is fulfilled
          by our new birth, our life given from above.      Or \u201Ca heart of flesh.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Therefore, you will keep my laws and faithfully obey my commands.
        Then you will truly be the people of my heart, and I will be the God you
        worship. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: The Glory of  Leaves Jerusalem'
      title: The Glory of  Leaves Jerusalem
      number: 21
      content: "But I will punish those whose hearts are devoted to their filthy
        idols and detestable practices. I will repay them for their conduct, declares
        Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Then the cherubim raised their wings to fly, and the wheels moved
        in unison with them; above them was the radiant glory of the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: And the glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> went up from Jerusalem
        and stood above the mountain to the east of the city. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 11:23
        content: '  That is, the Mount of Olives, where Jesus stood and wept over
          Jerusalem (see  ).    '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Then, the Spirit snatched me away and transported me back among the
        exiles in Babylon. This was the vision given to me by the Spirit of God.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Then the vision faded away. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:24
        content: '  Everything Ezekiel describes in chs.    was what the prophet
          experienced in a trance-like vision.  '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: And I told the exiles everything that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had revealed to me.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ezekiel Acts Like a Refugee'
      title: Ezekiel Acts Like a Refugee
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]The word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> was revealed
        to me: '
      comments:
      - number: 12:1
        content: "    is the third panel (C) in the chiastic parallel structure in
          Ezekiel. This section contains indictments of the corruption of Israel\u2019s
          leaders, their condemnation, and their judgment. There is also the implied
          destruction and desecration of the temple in Jerusalem, along with the
          promised destruction of all the cities and towns in the land (see  ). This
          section\u2014panel C\u2014constitutes the contrasting parallel with panel
          C  in chs.  , containing the visionary plans for the \u201Cideal\u201D
          Jerusalem temple. These \u201Cplans\u201D contain details of the ideal
          environment for Israel\u2019s godly leaders in the new covenant age, who
          will lead the nation in a renewed spirit of true worship.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, you are living among a rebellious people. They
        have eyes, but they will not see; they have ears, but they will not hear
        [[COMMENT(0)]] because they are bent on rebellion. "
      comments:
      - number: 12:2
        content: '  They had eyes but could not see the goodness of God and his care
          for their lives. They had ears but could not hear his words of warning.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Therefore, son of man, pack a small bundle of your belongings and
        leave your home before nightfall. Let everyone see you go into exile. And
        go somewhere else, like you are a prisoner of war, while they watch you depart.
        Then perhaps they will understand that they are a rebellious people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "While everyone is watching, pack your things like a refugee\u2019s
        bundle, by daylight, and leave like an exile at sunset. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 12:4
        content: '  People in hot and arid climates would only begin their journey
          in the evening when the heat subsided.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Dig through the wall of your house and crawl out, carrying the bag
        with you. [[COMMENT(0)]] Make sure everyone is watching. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:5
        content: "  The walls of the homes in Babylon were made of dried mud bricks
          that could easily be broken through. Ezekiel\u2019s actions became a parable
          of the broken-down walls of Jerusalem through which the Jews went when
          the Babylonians took them as prisoners of war.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Let them watch as you shoulder your pack and go out into the dusk.
        And cover your face so that you cannot see the land you are leaving since
        I have made you a walking parable\u2014a sign to warn the people of Israel.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "So, I did as I had been told. I packed my bag like an exile\u2019s
        bundle, by daylight. And that evening, I dug a hole through the wall with
        my hands. Then while everyone watched, I shouldered my pack and went out
        into the dark."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The next morning <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CSon of man, did not the rebellious Israelites ask you, \u2018What
        are you doing?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Answer them with these words: \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you that this prophetic oracle from God concerns the ruler [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in Jerusalem and all the people who live there.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 12:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cprince,\u201D that is, King Zedekiah.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CTell them, \u2018I am a sign [[COMMENT(0)]] for you, for what
        I did is what is going to happen to them.\u2019 They will be deported into
        exile. "
      comments:
      - number: 12:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cmiracle,\u201D from a root word that means \u201Cbright\u201D
          or \u201Cbeautiful.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Their ruler will shoulder his pack, and they will dig a hole in the
        wall to let him out at night. He will cover his face so that he cannot see
        the land he is leaving. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'I will throw my net over him and trap him in it. [[COMMENT(0)]] I
        will take him to Babylon, to the land of the Chaldeans, where he will die
        without having seen it.   '
      comments:
      - number: 12:13
        content: "  God\u2019s \u201Cnet\u201D was the Babylonian army.      They
          blinded King Zedekiah (see  ) so that he was unable to see the land where
          they took him. Josephus writes that Ezekiel sent a copy of this prophecy
          to King Zedekiah, but the king rejected the word as false (see    10.100.7).  "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'And I will scatter in every direction all his attendants, officials,
        and his armies, and I will chase after them with the sword. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'When I scatter them among different nations and peoples, they will
        recognize that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: Eating and Drinking with Fear'
      title: Eating and Drinking with Fear
      number: 16
      content: "But I will let a few of them escape the sword, plague, and food shortages.
        I will let them live so that they can describe all their terrible actions
        to the people in the lands where they will go. And they will recognize that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CSon of man, eat your food with quaking and trembling. Shudder
        with fear as you drink your water. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Tell the people, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this
        to the inhabitants of Jerusalem who remain in the land of Israel. They will
        tremble as they eat their food, and shake with fear when they drink their
        water because their enemies will strip the land bare on account of the violence
        of those who live there. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: The Visions Will Come True'
      title: The Visions Will Come True
      number: 20
      content: "When your populous cities have been destroyed and the countryside
        has been deserted, then you will recognize that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CSon of man, what do you understand of the proverb you say among
        yourselves in the land of Israel, \u2018Time goes by, and these visions never
        happen\u2019? "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Very well, tell them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says
        this: I will put an end to this proverb, and it will never be repeated in
        Israel again.\u2019 Tell them instead: \u2018The time has arrived for every
        vision to come true, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'for there will be no more false visions or deceptive prophecy among
        the people of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, will speak the word, and what I
        say will come true without delay. For what I speak, I will accomplish in
        your own lifetime, you tribe of rebels. For I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CSon of man, behold, the people of Israel are saying that your
        visions and prophecies are about the distant future, not today. They say,
        \u2018He is prophesying of times in the distant future.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "So tell them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you:
        There will be no more delay. My words will be fulfilled now! What I have
        prophesied will be done. Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has spoken!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: False Prophets Condemned'
      title: False Prophets Condemned
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy against the prophets of Israel who claim
        to speak for me but are prophesying out of their own imagination. Say to
        them: \u2018Listen, you lying prophets, to the words of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "for the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has a message for you.\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Disaster
        is in store for the wicked [[COMMENT(0)]] prophets who make up their own
        visions,  but they have seen and heard nothing! "
      comments:
      - number: 13:3
        content: "  The Hebrew word    here carries the connotation of \u201Cwicked\u201D
          or \u201Cungodly\u201D as well as \u201Cfoolish.\u201D The context indicates
          that the problem with these false prophets was not merely their folly but
          also their underlying impiety and godlessness.      Or \u201Cwho follow
          their own spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Israel, your prophets have been like scavengers [[COMMENT(0)]]  prowling
        among the city ruins. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cjackals\u201D or \u201Cfoxes.\u201D The prophets that
          remained in Jerusalem were like scavengers, and the people of Israel left
          behind were their prey.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "They have not denounced the people\u2019s sin or warned them of trouble
        coming [[COMMENT(0)]] so that Israel might stand up in battle on the day
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:5
        content: "  Or \u201CYou did not enter the breaches and repair the walls
          for the house of Israel,\u201D which is symbolic of their refusal to help
          the people and the city by warning them of the disaster ahead.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Their visions are phony and their prophecies of what is coming are
        lies. They say, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says,\u201D when I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        did not send them with my message, and yet they actually expect me to fulfill
        their words! "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Have you not seen false visions and prophesied false prophecies of
        the future? You declare: \u201CThis is what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says,\u201D when I had not spoken."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says
        to you: Because you have spoken your false prophecies and lying visions,
        behold, I am against you, says Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: I will punish [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, the false prophets will experience
        the power of his punishment.</smallcaps> the false prophets who see false
        visions and speak lies about what they see coming in the future. They will
        no longer belong to my council of elders,  nor will their names be inscribed
        in the register of the people of Israel,  nor will they ever return to the
        land of Israel. And then the people will know for sure that I am Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
      comments:
      - number: 13:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cmy hand [power] will be against.\u201D The irony is
          clear. Instead of speaking true words by the power of        Or \u201Cthe
          council of my people.\u201D See  ;  .      At least forty prophets are
          named in the Old Testament, but not one false prophet\u2019s name is recorded.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018For in truth, they have gravely misled my people,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CEverything is fine,\u201D when devastation is
        at hand.  When the false build a \u201Cwall of words\u201D they cover it
        with the whitewash of their lies.   "
      comments:
      - number: 13:10
        content: "  See  .      Or \u201C&nbsp;\u2018Peace,\u2019 when there is no
          peace.\u201D See  ;  .      The prophets were guilty of plastering over
          the hypocrisy and evil of the people to give the impression that all was
          solid and secure. The term for \u201Cwhitewash\u201D () refers to plaster
          that is cosmetic only without providing any structural support.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Prophesy to those who do so that their wall will fall! [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> For I will send a stormy wind that will break loose with a deluge
        of rain and great hailstones. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:11
        content: "  The \u201Cwall\u201D becomes a metaphor for the false confidence
          of the people that  would protect Jerusalem and his temple and they were
          secure. Cooper notes that the term    denotes an unstable wall made of
          stones that are simply stacked together without a cement binding (see LaMar
          Eugene Cooper,    [United States: Broadman &amp; Holman Publishers, 1994],
          156). The \u201Cwhitewash\u201D (see v.  ) is the false, self-inspired
          prophecies of the prophets who remained in Jerusalem telling the people
          that everything would be fine and that God wouldn\u2019t bring judgment
          on the city. See  . The Hebrew contains a notable word play, for the word
          for \u201Cplaster\u201D or \u201Cwhitewash\u201D can also mean \u201Cuseless.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "And down will come the wall! [[COMMENT(0)]] When it crumbles, will
        not the people say to you, \u201CWhere\u2019s that whitewashed wall of yours
        now?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 13:12
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Therefore this is what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to you: My anger will break forth as a windstorm and my wrath will break
        loose like a torrential rain, and I will send great hailstones to destroy
        your wall! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 13:13
        content: "  Symbolically, the stormy wind can represent God\u2019s glory
          as the Spirit pours out upon an awakened people (see  ;  ;  ). The torrential
          rain can represent the revelation-rain of truth as it pours out upon the
          earth (see  ;  ;  ). And the hailstones can represent God\u2019s truth
          crashing through the stronghold of lies (see  ;  ). God\u2019s last-days
          awakeners will demolish the flimsy \u201Cwall\u201D of bondage and lies
          that hold the church back from total victory (see  ;  ;  ) and lay bare
          the crooked foundations of the religious systems of the earth (see  ; 
          ;  ). Just as God sends human armies to execute his judgment on nations,
          so he also sends his spiritual armies to demolish strongholds and expose
          darkness (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Yes, I will level this plastered wall to the ground and lay bare its
        flimsy foundation. And when it crumbles, you, too, will crumble and perish.
        And then you will realize that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018For then my wrath will be spent against the wall
        and upon those who have smeared it with plaster. And I will say to you, \u201CThe
        wall is gone, and so are those who smeared plaster over it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: False Prophetesses Condemned'
      title: False Prophetesses Condemned
      number: 16
      content: "Those prophets of Israel who prophesied that Jerusalem would be fine,
        when devastation was near, will be no more!\u201D For I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CAs for you, son of man, prophesy against the women of your
        people, [[COMMENT(0)]]  who are witches masquerading as prophets. For they
        prophesy out of their own imagination. Prophesy against them "
      comments:
      - number: 13:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cset your face against the daughters of your people.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "and say, \u2018Hear what Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says
        to you: You women are doomed who sew magic bands on their wrists and make
        veils of varying sizes for their heads in order to ensnare the lives of people,
        young and old. Do you think you can get away with entrapping the lives of
        my people and still preserve your own lives? "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: You have dishonored my name among my people for a few handfuls of
        barley and a few pieces of bread. [[COMMENT(0)]] You put to death people
        who should not have died and kept alive people who should not have lived,
        because you lied to my people, and they listened to your lies!
      comments:
      - number: 13:19
        content: "  Some scholars believe the \u201Chandfuls of barley\u201D and
          \u201Cpieces of bread\u201D may have been used for divination. By scattering
          them on the ground and seeing how they fell, they could determine if a
          person were to live or die. It is more likely that these seeds and scraps
          of bread were used as payment for their (false) prophecies.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Therefore I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to you: I am against your wristbands with which you ensnare people\u2019s
        souls. I will tear them from your arms! And I will let your victims go free,
        those whom you hunt down like birds. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'I will rip off your scarves and deliver my people from your hands.
        They will no longer be trapped by your power, and then you will know for
        sure that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'By your lies you have made righteous people greatly discouraged (although
        I have not discouraged them). And by your lies you have encouraged the wicked
        not to repent from their wicked ways and save their lives. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Therefore you will no longer conjure up false visions or practice
        witchcraft. [[COMMENT(0)]] I will rescue my people from your deceptive power.
        And then you will know without a doubt that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 13:23
        content: "  Ezekiel gives us eleven characteristics of false prophets: (1)
          They spoke out of their own imagination, not God\u2019s will (see vv. 
          ,  ). (2) They used and manipulated people rather than serving and ministering
          to others to help them (see v.  ). (3) They were like scavengers looking
          for bruised and ruined lives to manipulate for personal gain (see vv. 
          ,  ). (4) They did not strengthen or warn the people about what was coming;
          instead, they only had lying words (see v.  ). (5) They claimed God was
          speaking to them, but their prophecies were meant to deceive their followers
          (see vv.  ). (6) They refused to expose sin (see vv.  ) and prophesied
          delusions. (7) They preached a message of peace and protection when, in
          fact, disastrous judgment was imminent (see vv.  ). (8) Their lies provoked
          God\u2019s anger and brought judgment upon them (see vv.  ,  ). (9) They
          were not prophesying by the Spirit of God but, instead, used witchcraft
          and occultic practices to hold their victims under their control (see vv. 
          ,  ). (10) They discouraged the righteous and encouraged wickedness (see
          vv.  ). (11) They were rebellious and self-willed, and set up idols in
          human hearts (see  ). See also  ;  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Idols of the Heart'
      title: Idols of the Heart
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]One day, some leaders of Israel came to me to consult
        about what God was saying. While they were sitting there with me, '
      comments:
      - number: 14:1
        content: "    contains a series of prophecies of God\u2019s coming judgment,
          meant to show that God was right to punish the people using invading enemies
          to capture Jerusalem.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CSon of man, these men have set up idols deep within their hearts.
        And they have set idols [[COMMENT(0)]] before their eyes, so why should I
        let them ask me anything?   "
      comments:
      - number: 14:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe stumbling block of iniquity,\u201D that is, idolatry.
          The implied meaning is that these leaders had idols set up both in their
          hearts and in their homes.      Clearly, these men were hypocrites who
          wanted to hear a word from God while hiding idolatry in their hearts. They
          had no intention of forsaking their sins; they merely wanted to have a
          prophet give them a word they wanted to hear.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So tell them this, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says:
        If any Israelite comes to consult with the prophet despite a heart that worships
        idols and eyes looking on that which leads into wickedness, I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        will answer that person directly. I will give the answer that is deserved
        because of the great extent of the idolatry. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "And in this way I hope to capture the hearts of the people of Israel
        who have all been estranged because of all their idols.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CTherefore, prophesy to the people of Israel, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Repent! Come back to me and forsake your idols. Once and for
        all, turn your backs on all your detestable practices. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'If any Israelite or a foreigner living among you rejects me with
        idolatry of the heart and has intentionally gazed on that which leads into
        wickedness, yet goes to consult with a prophet, then, I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        will answer that person myself. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'I will oppose that person! [[COMMENT(0)]] I will cut the idolator
        off from my people as an example and a warning  to others. And then you will
        know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:8
        content: "  Or \u201CI will set my face against that person.\u201D      Or
          \u201Ca proverb.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'And if the prophet is tricked into speaking a prophetic word, it
        is I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, who allowed this to happen, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for I have decided to punish him with death. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:9
        content: "  Or \u201Centiced that prophet.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Both the prophet and the one who consults him will be equally punished
        for their guilt. '
      comments: []
    - name: "11: God\u2019s Justice"
      title: "God\u2019s Justice"
      number: 11
      content: "I will do this so that they will never stray from me again or defile
        themselves with their rebellion. Then they will be my faithful people, and
        I will be their faithful God. For I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments:
      - number: 14:12
        content: "    is the fourth panel (D) in the chiastic parallel structure
          in Ezekiel. This section contains allegorical judgments against Israel,
          as well as the foretelling of new covenant blessing for the people of God.
          This section\u2014panel D\u2014constitutes the parallel with panel D  in
          chs.  , containing the Gog and Magog prophecies\u2014symbolic judgment
          against the nations. There is likewise the promise of renewal and new covenant
          blessing for Israel.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CSon of man, suppose all the people living in a certain country
        wander from me in pursuit of their sin, then I decide to come against them.
        I would punish them by destroying their food supply, inflicting famine on
        them, and causing people and animals to starve to death. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Even if the three godly men, Noah, Daniel, and Job, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        all lived there, their righteous lives could only save themselves\u2014no
        one else. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken."
      comments:
      - number: 14:14
        content: "  These three godly men, Noah, Daniel (although Ezekiel uses a
          slightly different Hebrew spelling, \u201CDanel\u201D), and Job, were heroes
          in the Jewish faith and known for their virtue and exceptional integrity.
          Daniel was a contemporary of Ezekiel, and the Jews in captivity would have
          known who he was.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201COr suppose I unleash wild animals on that country to roam through
        the land killing its people, [[COMMENT(0)]] making the land so dangerous
        that no one would dare pass through it. "
      comments:
      - number: 14:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cand [the animals] make it [the land] childless.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Even if these three godly men lived there, as surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        am the living God, they would not be able to save even their own children.
        They alone would be spared, and the country would become a desert.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201COr suppose I were to bring war upon that country, sending enemies
        with swords to devastate the land and wipe out both people and animals. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: Even if these three godly men lived there, as surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        am the living God, they would not be able to save either son or daughter;
        they alone would be saved.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201COr suppose I were to send a pandemic on that country and pour
        out my wrath upon the people with a bloody death and wipe out both people
        and animals. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: Destruction of Jerusalem'
      title: Destruction of Jerusalem
      number: 20
      content: "Even if Noah, Daniel, and Job lived there, as surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        am the living God\u2014their righteousness would only be able to save themselves
        and not even their own children.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, \u201CHow
        much worse it will be for Jerusalem when I send my four dreadful scourges\u2014sword,
        famine, wild animals, and pandemic\u2014to destroy both people and animals. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Even so, there will be a remnant left, a few who survive. Enemy soldiers
        will bring your wicked sons and daughters out of the city, and they will
        be brought here to Babylon. [[COMMENT(0)]] When you see them and realize
        how sinful are their ways and deeds, then you will not feel so sad when you
        understand that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, brought all these disasters
        upon Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cand when they come out to you [in Babylon].\u201D  "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "You will feel better when you see their evil way of life and actions,
        for then you will realize that I had a good reason to do what I did. I, Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Parable of the Worthless Vine'
      title: Parable of the Worthless Vine
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, and the parable of two eagles and a
        vine.</smallcaps><smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments:
      - number: 15:1
        content: '  In    we find three parables that demonstrate that Jerusalem
          has no hope of deliverance: the parable of the worthless vine, the parable
          of the unfaithful wife of      '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, how is the wood of the grapevine different than
        that of other tree branches of the forest? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 15:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cof all the branches of the trees of the forest, what
          happens to the wood of the grapevine?\u201D The grapevine is a common biblical
          metaphor for Israel (see  ;  ). In the New Testament, Jesus describes himself
          as the true sprouting vine and believers as his branches (see  ). God is
          humbling Israel and us with these words. The lowly grapevine is nothing
          compared to the lofty trees of the land, yet God has shown us his grace
          and loving favor.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Can its wood be used for making anything? Can it be used as pegs
        to hang things on? '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Look, it is good only for building a fire. When fire burns off both
        ends and the middle is charred, [[COMMENT(0)]] is it useful for anything? '
      comments:
      - number: 15:4
        content: '  The burned off ends are the Northern Kingdom of Israel and the
          Southern Kingdom of Judah. The charred middle is Jerusalem.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Even while it was intact, you could make nothing with it. When it\u2019s
        burned and charred, it\u2019s even more worthless.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CJust like I made
        the wood of the vine only useful as firewood, so I will treat the people
        of Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'I will oppose them! They may have escaped one fire, but another fire
        will yet devour them. [[COMMENT(0)]] When I set my face against them, then
        you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! '
      comments:
      - number: 15:7
        content: "  The first \u201Cfire\u201D refers metaphorically to the first
          time Nebuchadnezzar captured Jerusalem in 597 BC. People who survived that
          invasion were still living in Jerusalem when Ezekiel prophesied. The second
          \u201Cfire\u201D refers to the final destruction of Jerusalem by Nebuchadnezzar
          in 586 BC.  "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Because of their unfaithfulness and infidelity, I will reduce the
        land to a desert. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: A Parable of \u2019s Unfaithful Wife"
      title: "A Parable of \u2019s Unfaithful Wife"
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke again to me, saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 16:1
        content: "    is the most vivid and shocking chapter in all the Bible in
          its description of the harlotry of Israel (Jerusalem). It is an expressive
          parable of God\u2019s queen (see v.  ) becoming a prostitute (see v.  ).
          Idolatry in God\u2019s eyes is like the unfaithfulness of a wife to her
          husband. The language is so scandalous and jarring that according to the
          Mishnah (oral Torah), it should never be read in public. Modern readers
          will find this chapter full of terms and phrases that are sexually expressive
          and vulgar, so much so that most modern translations soften the text to
          help lessen its jolt to our senses. For the most part, the translation
          team has kept the expressive language as it is stated in the Hebrew text.
          So, why did God speak so vulgarly to Jerusalem? To shock her out of her
          complacency and deception. Thankfully, the chapter ends with a promise
          of grace and restoration (see vv.  ).    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, confront Jerusalem concerning all the despicable
        things they have done. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Tell them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you:
        Your ancestral origins were in the land where the Canaanites lived. Your
        father was an Amorite [[COMMENT(0)]] and your mother a Hittite. "
      comments:
      - number: 16:3
        content: '  That is, Jebus, the tribal head of the Jubusites, who once occupied
          the stronghold that David conquered and established as the city of Jerusalem.
          Jebus was an Amorite.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'On the day you were born, there was no one there to cut your umbilical
        cord or wash you clean in water. There was no one there to rub you with salt
        and oil  [[COMMENT(0)]] or wrap you in a baby blanket. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:4
        content: '  The addition of oil to the rubbing with salt on a newborn infant
          is a plausible insertion here, given the citation of Allen in his Ezekiel
          commentary, where he adduces evidence for such a practice originating in
          ancient Near Eastern culture (see Leslie C. Allen,  , Word Biblical Commentary,
          vol. 28 [Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan, 1987], 223).    '
    - name: '5: Adopted by God'
      title: Adopted by God
      number: 5
      content: "No one did anything to help you. No one felt sorry for you or showed
        sympathy for you. Instead, you were dumped into an open field and forgotten.
        From the day you were born you were rejected and unloved.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Then I passed by, and I saw you there squirming
        in your blood. And as you lay there covered with blood, I spoke over you:
        \u201CLive!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'And I made you grow and flourish like the grass of the fields. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        You grew up  and developed until you produced the most beautiful of features. 
        You developed the breasts and hair  of a young woman, but you were still
        quite naked and exposed. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:7
        content: "  There is a subtle play on the idea of a baby being abandoned
          in a field and then living and sprouting in that field where she once was
          abandoned.      Or \u201CI made you into a multitude.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe
          most beautiful jewels.\u201D      Or \u201C[pubic] hair,\u201D having reached
          puberty.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then later, I passed by again and looked upon you. And behold, I
        saw that your time had come\u2014you were now old enough for love. So, I
        spread the edge [[COMMENT(0)]] of my robe over you and covered your nakedness. 
        I gave you my sacred oath. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, made a
        divine covenant with you, saying, \u201CYou will be mine,\u201D and I took
        you as my own and promised to care for you. "
      comments:
      - number: 16:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cwing.\u201D      The act of a suitor spreading his robe
          or garment over a woman was a symbolic gesture indicating his desire to
          marry her and provide for her (see  ).    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then I washed the blood off you and anointed you with fragrant oil.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:9
        content: '  Believers have also been washed and anointed with oil (the Holy
          Spirit). See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'I dressed you in beautiful, embroidered gowns, fine leather shoes,
        a fine linen headband, and wrapped you in rich fabric. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I adorned you with jewels, beautiful bracelets, and necklaces. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:11
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I gave you a nose ring and earrings and placed a sparkling crown
        on your head. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'You were decked with gold and silver jewelry and dressed in luxurious
        linen and rich embroidered cloth. [[COMMENT(0)]] Your meals were feasts,
        made with the best bread, honey, and oil. You grew more and more beautiful,
        and you rose to be queen. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:13
        content: "  Or \u201Csilk.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: Unfaithful to God'
      title: Unfaithful to God
      number: 14
      content: "And you became famous throughout the world because the splendor I
        lavished on you made your beauty perfect, declares Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018But you became confident in your own beauty and
        used your fame to act like a prostitute. You offered your sexual favors to
        each one who came along\u2014and you became his! "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'You took some of your fine clothes to decorate the tents on the high
        places where you worked as a prostitute. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:16
        content: "  This verse ends with some untranslatable words, which may have
          been a coarse idiom with sexual meaning, lost in translation. However,
          some translations suggest what amounts to a divine exhortation inserted
          into a sordid allegorical discourse, such as, \u201Cthese things should
          not happen; they should never occur.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'You also took your gold and silver jewelry, which I had given you,
        and made yourself male images and acted like a prostitute with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'You took your embroidered clothes and used these to dress them up,
        and you offered them my sacred oil and my sacred incense. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I gave you food made with the best flour, olive oil, and honey. But
        you offered it as a fragrant incense to these idols. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        declare: that is exactly what you did! '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'You even took the sons and daughters I had given you and sacrificed
        them as food for the idols. As if your prostitution was not bad enough, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'you slaughtered my children and burned them as offerings to idols! '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: While you were doing the things I hate and behaving like a prostitute,
        you entirely forgot how you were when you were young. I found you naked and
        exposed, squirming in your own blood.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Now I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say
        you are doomed! Not only did you do these evil things, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'in every city square you built an elevated shrine [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        for the worship of idols. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cvaulted chamber [to practice your prostitution].\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'At the entry to every alley you put up your brothel [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and dragged your beauty through the mud. You spread your legs to all who
        passed by in countless acts of prostitution. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:25
        content: "  As translated from the Syriac, Vulgate, and the Septuagint. The
          Hebrew is \u201Cyou put up your lofty place.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'You slept with your well-endowed [[COMMENT(0)]] neighbors, the Egyptians,
        provoking my anger with your lifestyle of a prostitute. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:26
        content: "  Literally \u201Cbig of flesh\u201D (i.e., like an erect penis).    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'So listen, I have taken action to punish you and remove your portion
        of my blessing. [[COMMENT(0)]] I have put you at the mercy of your enemies, 
        the Philistine women, who blushed over your lewd behavior.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:27
        content: "  God\u2019s \u201Cblessing\u201D in this context may refer to
          the reduced size of their land.      Literally \u201CI have given you over
          to the throat of those who hate you.\u201D      Some scholars suggest that
          the Philistine women (in the parable of this chapter) were competing with
          the women of Judah in forming political alliances (also acting like prostitutes
          with other nations).    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Still unsatisfied, you prostituted yourself to the Assyrians and
        played the harlot with them. But even then, you were not satisfied. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: Worse Than a Prostitute'
      title: Worse Than a Prostitute
      number: 29
      content: "You committed further acts of fornication with the Babylonians, that
        nation of merchants, but that still did not satisfy you.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say: You
        make me extremely angry [[COMMENT(0)]] because of all these things that you
        have done. You have acted like a brazen prostitute who has no shame. "
      comments:
      - number: 16:30
        content: "  This verse begins with three Hebrew words that are extremely
          difficult to translate. Some translations omit them entirely. The meanings
          fall into four possibilities: (1) \u201CHow weak-willed you are!\u201D
          (2) \u201CHow wild is your lust!\u201D (3) \u201CHow sick is your heart!\u201D
          (4) \u201CHow angry you make me!\u201D Option 4 seems to be the best interpretation
          after comparing other Semitic languages and a revocalization of the text.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'You built an elevated shrine on every street to worship idols, put
        up your pavilion in every public square. But you are not like a common prostitute
        just out for the money. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'You are an adulterous wife who would rather have sex with strangers
        [[COMMENT(0)]] than her husband. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:32
        content: '  That is, foreigners (foreign nations).    '
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Men will pay a prostitute, but you give presents to all your lovers!
        You bribe them to come from everywhere just to sleep with you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: God Will Punish Jerusalem'
      title: God Will Punish Jerusalem
      number: 34
      content: "You are so different from other prostitutes. No one came to ask you
        for sex. The men you slept with did not pay you, but you paid them. Therefore,
        you are worse than a prostitute!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Very well, Jerusalem, you whore! Hear the word
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: You poured out your
        lust [[COMMENT(0)]] and are ready for sex. As a prostitute, you uncovered
        your genitals for your lovers and for all those disgusting idols. You killed
        your children  to honor those false gods. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:36
        content: "  Or \u201CYour juice was poured out.\u201D (See Moshe Greenberg, 
          , Anchor Yale Bible Commentaries, vol. 22 [New Haven &amp; London: Yale
          University Press, 1983], 286.) The meaning of the Hebrew    is disputed
          here. It carries the literal meaning of \u201Cwealth\u201D or \u201Cmoney,\u201D
          but some have seen it as an expression of sexual anticipation.      Or
          literally \u201CYou gave the blood of your children.\u201D      Or \u201Cidols.\u201D    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Behold, I will bring together all your lovers to
        whom you gave pleasure\u2014all those you loved and all those you hated.
        Yes, I will bring them from everywhere, and I will strip you naked in front
        of them and let them see your genitals."
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will judge you with the same death sentence of
        an adulterer or murderer and bring upon you the fury of my burning rage.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 16:38
        content: "  Or \u201CI will bring on you the blood of my rage and zeal.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "I will hand you over to your \u201Clovers,\u201D and they will destroy
        your elevated chamber and pull down your sacred shrines. They will strip
        you of your clothes, take away your lovely jewels, and leave you stark naked. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'Then they will gather an angry mob against you who will stone you
        to death and hack you to pieces with their swords. '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "They will burn down your homes and execute justice on you while many
        other women look on. I will once and for all put an end to your wicked harlotry\u2014no
        more paid lovers for you!"
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Once my fury is exhausted with you, I will calm
        down and let my anger die away. Then I will not be angry anymore. "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: Compared with Samaria and Sodom'
      title: Compared with Samaria and Sodom
      number: 43
      content: "You have entirely forgotten how I treated you when you were young.
        And you have done nothing but provoke me, so now I, in turn, will cause you
        to suffer the consequences for your own behavior. [[COMMENT(0)]] And haven\u2019t
        you committed such gross lewdness in addition to all your other shocking
        sins? I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 16:43
        content: "  Or \u201CI will bring your conduct down on your own head!\u201D    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  says, \u201CBehold, all who quote
        proverbs will surely apply this proverb to you, Jerusalem: Like mother, like
        daughter. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 16:44
        content: "  That is, a mother passes on her nature and characteristics to
          her children. A comparable proverb in English is \u201Cthe apple doesn\u2019t
          fall far from the tree.\u201D    "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Yes; you are a daughter exactly like your pagan mother, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who hated her husband and her children. And you have become exactly like
        your sisters,  who hated their husbands and their children. You and your
        sister cities had a Hittite mother and an Amorite father. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:45
        content: "  That is, the Hittites (see v.  ). God is telling the people of
          Jerusalem that they are as pagan as the Canaanites were when they came
          into the land.      Although singular in this verse, elsewhere in the chapter
          it is plural (see vv.  ,  ,  ). The \u201Csisters\u201D are Samaria and
          Sodom. Jerusalem is as compromised and corrupt as the two cities of Samaria
          and Sodom (see v.  ).    "
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'Your big sister is Samaria with her daughter-villages to the north
        of you. Your little sister is Sodom with her daughter-villages to the south
        of you. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:46
        content: "  The Hebrew is literally \u201Cat your left hand [north]\u201D
          and \u201Cyour right hand [south].\u201D The temple faced east with Samaria
          on the left hand and Sodom on the right.    "
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: 'Yet you were not satisfied to live as the people of Samaria and Sodom
        lived, copying all their wicked ways and imitating their loathsome practices.
        In very little time, you became more wicked than they were in all your ways. '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'As surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, live, your sister
        Sodom and her daughters never did the evil that you and your daughters have
        done. '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: 'Behold, the guilt of your sister Sodom! She and her daughters were
        arrogant, gluttonous, and lived in carefree complacency. They never thought
        to help the poor and needy. '
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'They were proud, stubborn, and defiantly evil before me, and so I
        swept them away as you have seen. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:50
        content: "  Or \u201Cwhen I saw it\u201D (see  ).    "
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: 'And yet Samaria never committed half the sins that you have. You
        have done more detestable things than they. When compared to all your gross
        practices, you have made your sisters seem innocent! '
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: So now you will bear the shame of your deeds, which provides a measure
        of justification for your sisters, since your sins are viler than theirs.
        They now appear more upright than you are. So, suffer the utter disgrace
        and humiliation of having made your sisters appear more righteous than you!
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: "\u201CI will restore their fortunes; I will restore Sodom and her
        daughters. I will restore Samaria and her daughters, and then I will also
        restore your fortunes along with them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: 'You will be totally ashamed of yourself and bear disgrace for all
        you have done in giving them comfort. '
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: 'When your sisters, Sodom and her daughter-villages and Samaria and
        her daughter-villages, are restored to what they were, then you, too, and
        your surrounding villages will be restored to what you were. '
      comments: []
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: 'Jerusalem, did you not gloat in your pride over your sister Sodom '
      comments: []
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: 'before your wickedness was uncovered? [[COMMENT(0)]]  Now you are
        just like her! You have become the laughingstock of the Philistines, the
        Syrians,  and all your neighbors who hate you and heap scorn on you. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:57
        content: "  The Hebrew also allows for this sentence to be a statement rather
          than a rhetorical question: \u201CYou did not even talk about your sister
          Sodom.\u201D      Or \u201CAram.\u201D Many translations and a few Hebrew
          manuscripts read \u201CEdom [the Edomites].\u201D    "
    - name: '58: An Everlasting Covenant'
      title: An Everlasting Covenant
      number: 58
      content: "You have brought this on yourself with your lewdness and your disgusting
        deeds. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: "\u201CFor I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> say to you: I will
        treat you as you deserve, for you have broken your marriage covenant [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> and despised your promises to me.   "
      comments:
      - number: 16:59
        content: '  This marriage covenant was made between  and Israel on Mount
          Sinai.      See  ; compare  ,  .    '
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: 'But I [[COMMENT(0)]] will remember my covenant that I made with you
        in the days of your youth.  I will renew that covenant with you, and it will
        last forever.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:60
        content: "  The pronoun \u201CI\u201D is emphatic in the Hebrew text: \u201CI,
          yes, I!\u201D      \u201CThe days of your youth\u201D include the time
          from the Exodus through the wilderness wanderings. God entered into a marriage
          covenant with Israel knowing that she would wander and be unfaithful. Yet
          he still loved her deeply, and he promised to renew his covenant with her.
          Our \u201Cwanderings\u201D will not separate us from God\u2019s love. See 
          .      The Hebrew prophets never left God\u2019s people in despair without
          hope. Today, God\u2019s true prophets likewise must expose sin and bring
          God\u2019s people to repentance, but they must also leave them with the
          gracious promise of restoration and hope. Part of the prophetic calling
          is to bring hope, comfort, and encouragement to God\u2019s people. See 
          .    "
    - name: '61: '
      title: 
      number: 61
      content: 'When you get back your older and younger sisters, then you will remember
        your ways and feel ashamed. I will make them like daughters to you, but not
        on the basis of my new covenant with you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '62: '
      title: 
      number: 62
      content: 'Yes, I will graciously renew my covenant with you, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and then you will know me as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:62
        content: "  This renewal of a broken covenant was not bestowed upon Jerusalem
          as a reward for her repentance. It was freely given because of God\u2019s
          grace. In a sense, this is a shadow of the new covenant that we have entered
          into today based entirely on God\u2019s endless grace and mercy toward
          us who believe. See  ;  ;  ,  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '63: '
      title: 
      number: 63
      content: "You may remember your wretched past and feel deep remorse, yet you
        will be reduced to silence when you realize that I have forgiven you [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for everything you have done. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have
        spoken.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 16:63
        content: "  Or \u201Cmade atonement.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Parable of the Eagles and the Vine'
      title: Parable of the Eagles and the Vine
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, propose this riddle to Israel, and speak this parable
        [[COMMENT(0)]] to the people. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:2
        content: "  There is a play on words in the Hebrew. The words for \u201Cspeak\u201D
          and \u201Cparable\u201D come from the same Hebrew triliteral root word.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Tell them to guess the meaning of what I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have to say to them:\u201CThere once was this great eagle with huge wings,whose
        wingspan was very wide,with many beautiful colored feathers around its head.One
        day he came to the Lebanon Mountains,and taking a new branch of a cedar tree,"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: he broke it off and carried it off to a land of traders.He planted
        it there in a city of merchants.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Next, he took a young seedling from the landand planted it in a fertile
        field.He placed it like a willow treeby the side of a flowing stream.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: The young plant sprouted until it became a low spreading vine.Its
        branches grew up toward the great eagle, [[COMMENT(0)]]and its roots grew
        down deep into the soil.So, it became a vine,branching out and sprouting
        new shoots.
      comments:
      - number: 17:6
        content: "  The \u201Cgreat eagle,\u201D the king of birds, represents King
          Nebuchadnezzar, whose power (wings) extended over a large area. He deported
          King Jehoiachin and put Zedekiah on the throne in 597 BC.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: But another great eagle [[COMMENT(0)]] appearedwith huge wings and
        many feathers around its head.And soon the vine bent its roots toward himand
        stretched its branches toward this eaglefrom the place where it was planted,expecting
        this eagle to nourish it.
      comments:
      - number: 17:7
        content: "  This second great eagle is Egypt. King Zedekiah trusted in vain
          for Egypt\u2019s help against the Babylonian invaders.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: The vine was planted in good soil,by the side of a generous stream
        [[COMMENT(0)]]so that the vine could branch out,bear fruit, and become a
        wonderful vine.
      comments:
      - number: 17:8
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: So I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, ask you:Will the vine thrive?Will
        not the first eagle come and tear out its roots?Will it not strip off its
        grapesso that all its foliage withers?Then, even weak ones could easily uproot
        it!
      comments: []
    - name: '10:  Unlocks His Riddle'
      title: ' Unlocks His Riddle'
      number: 10
      content: "Yes, it is planted\u2014but will it thrive?Will it not shrivel up
        when the east wind [[COMMENT(0)]] blows?Will it not wither in the fertile
        soil where it had grown?\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 17:10
        content: '  That is, the Babylonian armies.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CAsk that tribe of rebels if they know the meaning of my parable.
        Tell them: \u2018Listen, the king of Babylon swooped into Jerusalem. Then
        he carried away the king and top officials and took them off to Babylon.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 17:12
        content: '  See  . Babylon and Egypt (see  ) also represent spiritual forces
          that affect the growth and advance of the church today. We, too, are a
          vine, a low spreading vine that is meant to bear much fruit in our union
          with Christ (see v.  ;  ). Babylon pictures the world system, and Egypt
          pictures leaning on the strength of man (the flesh). We need to be set
          free from our captivity to the world and our trust in man.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'He took one from the royal family [[COMMENT(0)]] and made a treaty
        with him, forcing him to swear an oath of allegiance to him. He also carried
        off to Babylon the leading men of Israel '
      comments:
      - number: 17:13
        content: '  That is, Zedekiah, who was the uncle of King Jehoiachin of Judah.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'so that their kingdom would be humbled and not rise again and to
        ensure that the treaty would be kept. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:14
        content: "  Or \u201Csurviving only by keeping his treaty.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'But he rebelled against Nebuchadnezzar and sent envoys to Egypt to
        procure himself horses and a large army. Will he get away with that? Will
        a man who has done this go unpunished? Will he break the treaty and still
        escape? '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'As surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, live, this king
        will die in Babylon! He will die in the country of the king who put him on
        the throne, because he despised his oath and broke the treaty he had made. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Despite Pharaoh\u2019s mighty army and numerous troops, he will not
        be able to save him in war. When the Babylonians build siege ramps and wooden
        towers to kill many in the city, the Egyptians will not lift a finger to
        help! "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: For he despised his oath by breaking the treaty to which he had pledged
        himself, and he will not go unpunished.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Therefore, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        decree, as surely as I live, I swear it. It was my oath that he has despised
        and my treaty which he has broken. I will punish him for this! "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'I will throw my net over him and trap him in it. I will take him
        to Babylon and render judgment against him there for all the wicked things
        he did against me. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:20
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '21: Parable of the Cedar Tree'
      title: Parable of the Cedar Tree
      number: 21
      content: "All his elite troops will fall by the sword, and the survivors will
        be scattered in every direction. And then you will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have decreed it.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says:\u201CI will take the highest
        branch from a cedar tree.I will break off from the very top a tender shootand
        plant it myself on a high and lofty mountain."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: I will plant it on the highest mountain in Israel,where it will put
        out branches and bear fruit [[COMMENT(0)]]and grow into a stately cedar tree.
        Every kind of bird will find a home in it. Yes, in the shade of its branches
        the birds will make their nests.
      comments:
      - number: 17:23
        content: "  See  ;  .      This image is similar to the one in vv.  , except
          here it is God, not an eagle, who takes the top cedar branch and plants
          it. This is a parable of God restoring the kingdom of Israel (cedar tree)
          and giving hope to his people once again.      Or \u201Clive beneath it.\u201D
          See  ;  .    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "And all the trees of the field [[COMMENT(0)]] will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        am the onewho brings the tall tree low and raises the low tree high,who withers
        the green tree and makes the withered tree sprout again. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken and have done it!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 17:24
        content: '  That is, the nations of the earth.      Both humiliation and
          exaltation are the work of the sovereign God. He will humble the proud
          and give grace to the humble. See also  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Personal Responsibility'
      title: Personal Responsibility
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again,
        saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 18:1
        content: "    is the fifth panel (E) in the chiastic parallel structure in
          Ezekiel. This section contains the announcement of the covenant curse against
          Israel, followed by a divine exhortation to new life and heart renewal.
          This section\u2014panel E\u2014constitutes the parallel with panel E  in
          ch.  , containing the vision of the valley of dry bones that conveys the
          promise of new life and covenant renewal\u2014a spiritual resurrection
          from the dead.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CWhy do you keep repeating this proverb in the land of Israel:\u201CThe
        parents have eaten sour grapes,but the children are the ones with the sour
        taste in their mouths? [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 18:2
        content: "  Ezekiel\u2019s generation seemed to overlook the truth that they
          were worse than their fathers and yet were blaming their fathers. The meaning
          of this parable is that children suffer for something their parents did.
          The people were quoting this parable because they felt that God was treating
          them unfairly. They were taken into captivity and lost their homes and
          land, and they did not think that they deserved to be punished in that
          way. The basis of this belief is found in  ;  . This fatalistic attitude
          left the people of Israel feeling like they had no control over their lives,
          and it no longer mattered how they lived. Even if they were good, they
          believed God would punish them for their parents\u2019 evil. In effect,
          God was annulling Moses\u2019 declaration found in  , that God would punish
          up to the third and fourth generation for their ancestors\u2019 sins. This
          chapter expounds on the doctrine of individual responsibility.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CAs I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, live, you will have
        no reason to repeat this proverb in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: Three Examples of Personal Responsibility'
      title: Three Examples of Personal Responsibility
      number: 4
      content: "Listen, every human life belongs to me; both the parent and the child
        are mine. The one who sins is held responsible and will die.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 18:4
        content: '  See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . Since God is the Creator and owner of the
          soul of every person, each individual must stand or fall according to their
          relationship with God. The sins of others can never determine your destiny.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CSuppose a man is morally good, and his actions are righteous
        and honest. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He does not take part in the heathen feasts on the mountains nor
        worship the false gods [[COMMENT(0)]] of the people of Israel. He does not
        commit adultery nor have sex with a woman during her period. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:6
        content: "  Or \u201Clift up his eyes to idols.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He exploits and defrauds no one. [[COMMENT(0)]] He does not steal
        but generously feeds the hungry and clothes the needy.   '
      comments:
      - number: 18:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cdoes not withhold a debtor\u2019s collateral.\u201D
          See  .      See  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He does not lend at interest or take any profit. He refuses to do
        anything evil and gives honest judgment between one person and another. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: He keeps my laws and is honest in all that he does. A person like
        this is righteous, and he will certainly live. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have decreed it.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CBut suppose he has a son who is prone to violence and bloodshed, "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'doing what his father never did. He takes part in the heathen feasts
        on the mountains, commits adultery, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'exploits the poor and needy, robs, and defrauds others. He worships
        the false gods and engages in despicable practices '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "and charges exorbitant interest for profit when lending money\u2014such
        a person will by no means live. [[COMMENT(0)]] Because he committed all these
        appalling deeds, he will surely be put to death, and he alone will be responsible
        for his own death. "
      comments:
      - number: 18:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cand living, he will not live.\u201D      Or \u201Chis
          blood will be upon himself.\u201D See  ,  ;  .    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CBut suppose this evil man has a son who sees all the sins his
        father practiced, yet chooses not to follow his poor example "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "and refuses to take part in the heathen feasts on the mountains or
        worship the false gods of the people of Israel. He does not seduce another
        man\u2019s wife, "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'nor exploit nor defraud anyone. He does not steal but feeds the hungry
        and clothes the needy. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He refuses to do anything evil and does not lend for profit or charge
        exorbitant interest. He faithfully keeps my laws and teachings\u2014such
        a person will certainly live and not die for his father\u2019s sins. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: As for his father, because he practiced fraud, cheated, and robbed
        others, doing what is wrong among his people, he will most certainly die
        in his guilt. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 18:18
        content: "  Or \u201Che will die for his iniquity.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CYet you ask, \u2018Why doesn\u2019t the child bear his father\u2019s
        guilt?\u2019 If a person lives an honest and upright life and keeps my laws
        and faithfully follows my teachings, he will most certainly live. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: The Power of Repentance'
      title: The Power of Repentance
      number: 20
      content: "It is the one who sins who will die. A child is not to bear his father\u2019s
        guilt nor a father his child\u2019s guilt. Good people will be credited for
        their own righteousness and the wicked with his own wickedness.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CHowever, if the wicked man renounces all the sins he has committed,
        obeys my laws, and does what is fair and upright, he will most certainly
        live and will not die. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 18:21
        content: '  God is teaching us that sinners can not only be set free from
          the guilt of their ancestors but also be freed from the guilt and shame
          of their own past. The individual, not the collective group, is held responsible
          for sin. See  .    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'I will not remember any of the sins he committed in the past. Because
        he has done what is right, he will most certainly live. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say: Do you think I enjoy
        seeing the wicked die? I would much rather see him renounce his sins and
        live!'
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CHowever, if the righteous man abandons his righteous ways and
        acts wickedly, and follows all the despicable practices of the wicked, should
        he be allowed to live? None of his righteous deeds will be remembered from
        then on, for he is guilty of being unfaithful to me, and he will most certainly
        die."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CBut you complain, \u2018The Lord is being unfair. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        That\u2019s not right.\u2019 Now people of Israel, listen to me: Do you think
        my way of doing things is unjust? Aren\u2019t you the ones who are acting
        unjustly? "
      comments:
      - number: 18:25
        content: "  Or \u201CThe way of Lord is not equal [balanced].\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'When the righteous man abandons his righteous ways, does what is
        evil, and dies, he dies responsible for the wrong that he himself committed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Similarly, when the wicked man abandons his wicked ways to do what
        is good and right, he saves his own life. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Having considered his ways and having chosen to renounce all his
        former sins, he will most certainly live and not die. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "And yet the people of Israel say, \u2018What the Lord does is not
        just.\u2019 Really? What I do is not just, people of Israel? Aren\u2019t
        you the ones who are acting unjustly? "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'So from here on, you people of Israel, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to you: I will judge each of you by what he does. Repent, turn away from
        all your sins, or your own wickedness will be your downfall. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 18:30
        content: "  Or \u201Cso that iniquity will not be a stumbling block to you.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'You must get rid of all the guilty sins you have committed and clothe
        [[COMMENT(0)]] yourselves with a new heart and a new spirit. People of Israel,
        choose life!   '
      comments:
      - number: 18:31
        content: "  Or \u201Cmake yourselves [over].\u201D See  .      Or \u201Cwhy
          die?\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "I find no pleasure watching anyone die, [[COMMENT(0)]] so repent
        and live! I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:32
        content: '  See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Song of Sorrow'
      title: A Song of Sorrow
      number: 1
      content: "\u201CNow Ezekiel, sing this funeral song to mourn the rulers [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Israel, "
      comments:
      - number: 19:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cprinces,\u201D the term Ezekiel uses throughout his
          book for kings.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "saying,\u201C&nbsp;\u2018What a lioness was your mother among lions!
        [[COMMENT(0)]]She lay down among the young lionsand reared her cubs."
      comments:
      - number: 19:2
        content: "  Or \u201CWhat is your mother? A lioness!\u201D The \u201Clioness\u201D
          is a metaphor for the royal lineage of King David (see  ). The \u201Cmother\u201D
          likely represents Israel; however, some see the mother as Hamutal, the
          wife of Josiah and mother of Jehoahaz and Zedekiah. In  , there are four
          different Hebrew words used for the lions (words for \u201Clioness,\u201D
          \u201Clions,\u201D \u201Cyoung lions,\u201D and \u201Ccubs\u201D).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: One of the cubs she raisedgrew into a young and powerful man-eating
        lion [[COMMENT(0)]]who learned to hunt and devour his prey.
      comments:
      - number: 19:3
        content: '  This ferocious lion is King Jehoahaz, who was only twenty-three
          when he ascended to the throne.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: The nations heard about him,and they trapped him in their pit.With
        hooks they dragged him off to Egypt. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 19:4
        content: '  Jehoahaz was deposed and taken captive to Egypt in 609 BC. See 
          .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: When she realized that he was not coming back,she despaired and her
        hopes were dashed.She chose another of her cubs to take his placeand made
        a powerful lion of him too. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 19:5
        content: '  Modern Christian commentators see here a reference to King Jehoiachin
          while Jewish scholars believe it is King Jehoiakim.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: He prowled among the prideand grew into a powerful man-eating lion,who
        learned to hunt and devour his prey.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: He demolished their strongholds [[COMMENT(0)]]and destroyed their
        cities.Whenever the lion released his roar,the land and all the people were
        terrified!
      comments:
      - number: 19:7
        content: "  As translated from ancient versions, Theodotion, and the Targum.
          The Hebrew is \u201CHe knew [had sex with] their widows,\u201D which was
          the custom of kings in the ancient world when they had defeated a rival.
          Similarly, when a new lion becomes the dominant male of the pride, he mates
          with all the females to establish his status. Thus, this clause suggests
          that the mother\u2019s second son became Judah\u2019s king.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: The nations marched out against himfrom all around.They threw their
        net over him,and he was trapped in their pit.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'With their hooks they captured him, [[COMMENT(0)]]led him with bands
        around his neck to the king of Babylon.They threw him into a dungeonso that
        his roar could never be heard againon the mountains of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: 19:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cput him in a cage.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Your mother was like a grapevineplanted beside
        a stream,with luscious fruit and full of branches,because the water flowed
        so abundantly. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 19:10
        content: '  In vv.    the parable changes to a different metaphor but with
          the same theme. Here Israel is the fruitful vine, and her sons are the
          branches.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: She grew strong branches, and some grew very high,which became royal
        scepters.The vine grew higher and higher,up into the clouds.Everyone could
        see her towering heightand the vast number of her branches.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: But disaster struck the vine.Angry, mighty hands pulled it up by its
        roots [[COMMENT(0)]]and threw it to the ground.The hot east wind dried it
        up,and her fruit shriveled and fell to the ground. Her strong stem  was witheredand
        was consumed by the fire.
      comments:
      - number: 19:12
        content: "  That is, the hands of God came against Israel in judgment and
          devastated the nation.      Literally \u201C[her fruit] was broken in pieces.\u201D     
          Her \u201Cstrong stem\u201D is likely a reference to King Zedekiah.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: Now what remains of her has been transplanted to the desert,to a dry
        and thirsty land. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 19:13
        content: "  That is, Israel was \u201Ctransplanted\u201D into captivity in
          Babylon.  "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Fire spread from her stemand devoured its fruit.There is not a strong
        branch leftthat could become a scepter for a king.\u2019&nbsp;\u201DThis
        is a funeral song of lament, and it should be used as such."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Egypt"
      title: "Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Egypt"
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]It was the seventh year, the fifth month, and the
        tenth day after our deportation to Babylon.  Some of the elders of Israel
        came to request that I ask <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> for his message
        to them. As we sat together, '
      comments:
      - number: 20:1
        content: "    is the sixth panel (F) in the chiastic parallel structure in
          Ezekiel. This section contains the declaration of the judgment against
          Israel and the promise of new covenant blessing and restoration. This section\u2014panel
          F\u2014constitutes the corresponding parallel with panel F  in ch.  , which
          also contains a declaration of judgment against Israel, followed by the
          promise of new covenant blessing.      That is, August 14, 591 BC. The
          dating of this event would be four to five years before the destruction
          of the temple in Jerusalem.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give the elders of Israel this message: \u2018Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: Are you really coming to consult
        with me? As surely as I live, I will tell you nothing. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CJudge them, Ezekiel! Bring a charge against
        them, son of man! [[COMMENT(0)]] Confront them over the disgusting practices
        of their ancestors! "
      comments:
      - number: 20:4
        content: "  Or \u201CWill you judge them, Ezekiel? Will you bring a charge
          against them, son of man?\u201D Although this is the imperfect verb, the
          Hebrew verb can be viewed as the desiderative mood.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Tell them what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say: \u2018On
        the day when I chose Israel to be my people, I pledged my word [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to the tribes of Jacob, and I revealed myself to them in Egypt.  I pledged
        my word to them and said: I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God.   "
      comments:
      - number: 20:5
        content: "  Or \u201CI raised my hand toward,\u201D which was done when taking
          an oath.      God revealed his mighty power to Israel in the plagues he
          sent against Egypt and in the Passover miracle.      See  ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "That day I promised that I would bring them out of Egypt to a land
        I had searched out especially for them\u2014a land flowing with milk and
        honey, the most splendid land of all. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:6
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "And I said to them, \u201CEvery one of you, get rid of the things
        you love that I hate. Don\u2019t make yourselves unfit for my presence by
        worshiping the idols of Egypt. For I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your
        God.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But they rebelled against me and refused to listen to me. Not one
        of them rejected the detestable things their eyes feasted on, nor did they
        give up the idols of Egypt. So in my anger, I decided to pour out my wrath
        on them and vent my anger against them in the midst of Egypt.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: "9: Israel\u2019s Disobedience in the Wilderness"
      title: "Israel\u2019s Disobedience in the Wilderness"
      number: 9
      content: "I acted to protect the honor of my name, so that I would not be profaned
        in the eyes of the surrounding nations who saw me reveal myself by bringing
        the Israelites out of Egypt.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSo I brought them out of Egypt and led them into the desert. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I gave them my laws and taught them my commands, [[COMMENT(0)]] so
        that they would follow them and live by them. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:11
        content: '  This refers to the law given to Israel at Mount Sinai. See  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'And I also gave them my Sabbaths as a sign between me and them [[COMMENT(0)]]
        so that they might know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, am the one
        who sets them apart as my own. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:12
        content: '  See  . The Sabbath was a unique sign of the covenant between
          God and Israel. There is no command to keep the Sabbath today for gentile
          believers. See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But the Israelites rebelled against me in the wilderness and refused
        to keep my laws and rejected my commands (the one who obeys my laws will
        live by them), and they completely dishonored my Sabbaths. I was about to
        vent my fury on them in the desert and destroy them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'But I chose to withhold my punishment for the sake of my holy name,
        that it not be profaned in the eyes of the nations who had seen my power
        in bringing the Israelites out of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So, I made a vow in the desert that I would not bring that generation
        [[COMMENT(0)]] into the most splendid land that I had given them, a land
        flowing with milk and honey. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cthem.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'For they had scorned my commands, refused to keep my laws, dishonored
        my Sabbaths, and their hearts were attached to idols. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: In spite of this, I took pity on them, so I spared them from destruction
        and did not make an end of them in the desert.
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CI warned their children in the wilderness: \u2018Do not follow
        the ways of your ancestors, do not practice their standard of justice, and
        do not defile yourselves with their foul idols. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God. Keep my laws, obey my
        commands, and follow them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Keep my Sabbaths as holy days. Let them be a covenant-sign between
        me and you, to remind you that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> your God.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CHowever, like their parents, the next generation rebelled against
        me; they refused to keep my laws and did not respect or practice my standard
        of justice so that they would follow my laws and live by them. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        They also dishonored my Sabbaths. So, in my fury I decided to punish them
        and pour out my anger on them in the desert. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:21
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But I restrained myself to protect the honor of my name so that I
        would not be profaned in the eyes of the surrounding nations who saw me reveal
        myself by bringing the Israelites out of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Moreover, I made a vow to them in the wilderness that I would scatter
        them throughout the nations and disperse them into foreign countries. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'I did this because they had broken my laws, refused to obey my commands,
        dishonored my Sabbaths, and their hearts chased after the idols [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of their ancestors. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey fastened their eyes on the idols.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'And for this reason I gave them laws and regulations that resulted
        in punishment, not life. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:25
        content: "  Or \u201CI gave them statutes that were not good and rules they
          could not keep to have life.\u201D    "
    - name: "26: Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Canaan"
      title: "Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Canaan"
      number: 26
      content: "And because they sacrificed their firstborn children in the fire,
        I declared them defiled and unfit to worship me. I did this to fill them
        with revulsion so that they would know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CTherefore, son of man, speak to the people of Israel in exile
        and say to them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: Here
        is another instance of your ancestors blaspheming me by their infidelity. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'When I had brought them into the promised land, they discovered all
        sorts of high hills and all kinds of spreading trees. That is where they
        offered sacrifices and made offerings to false gods that provoked my anger.
        That is where they burned incense and poured out drink offerings to false
        gods. '
      comments: []
    - name: "29: Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Exile"
      title: "Israel\u2019s Disobedience in Exile"
      number: 29
      content: "So I asked them: What is this high place where you go?\u2019&nbsp;\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]] (So its name is called High Place to this day.)"
      comments:
      - number: 20:29
        content: "  This verse contains a significant paronomasia. The Hebrew term
          for \u201Chigh place\u201D () has a homonym that can be translated \u201Cwhere
          we go.\u201D The Hebrew play on words, lost in translation, would not be
          missed by a Hebrew speaker.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CSay to the Israelites in exile, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Will you defile yourselves in the same way your ancestors did
        and act like a prostitute with your idol worship? "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: For when you offer your gifts and sacrifice your children as sacrifices
        by fire, you defile yourselves with all your idol worship to this very day.
        Do you think you can come and consult with me? As surely as I live, I will
        not answer you. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken!
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018You are saying that you want to worship idols of
        wood and stone and be like the nations around you. But what you have in mind
        will never happen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: Another Exodus'
      title: Another Exodus
      number: 33
      content: "As surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, live, I warn
        you: I will continue to rule over you with a strong hand and with all my
        power and my wrath poured out!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018You have been scattered into many different nations
        and lands. But with a strong hand and my mighty power and outpoured wrath,
        I will bring you back. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'I will bring you into the desert of many nations, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and there I will enter into judgment  with you face-to-face! '
      comments:
      - number: 20:35
        content: "  This is likely a reference to the Syrian desert or the Arabian
          desert, both of which are surrounded by other nations.      The Hebrew
          verb    can mean either \u201Cto plead with\u201D or \u201Cto execute judgment.\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Just as I entered into judgment with your ancestors in the wilderness
        of Sinai, so I now judge you. I am Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, and
        I declare this to you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "I will make you pass under the shepherd\u2019s rod and take note
        of you, as a shepherd sorts his sheep. [[COMMENT(0)]] And I will bring you
        into the bond of the covenant.   "
      comments:
      - number: 20:37
        content: "  See  . The metaphor of the shepherd\u2019s rod may also include
          the notion of discipline.      The \u201Cbond\u201D of the covenant entails
          a mandatory obligation to obey the terms of the covenant.    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'I will purge out the rebels from among you, those who sin against
        me. I will remove them from the land where they are exiled, but they will
        not enter the land of Israel. Then you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: "39: Israel\u2019s Future Transformation"
      title: "Israel\u2019s Future Transformation"
      number: 39
      content: "And now, you people of Israel, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says: Go ahead, all of you, worship your foul idols, if that\u2019s what
        you want to do. But later you will have to listen and obey me! Then you will
        no longer dishonor my holy name by worshiping your foul idols and bringing
        your offerings to them.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: On the
        high mountain of Israel set apart for me, [[COMMENT(0)]] all the people of
        Israel\u2014everyone in the land\u2014will worship me. I will be pleased
        with you and accept your sacrifices to me. And there I will require your
        best offerings, all your best gifts dedicated to me, and your holy sacrifices. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:40
        content: '  That is, Mount Zion.    '
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'I will take you out from among the nations and lands where you have
        been scattered and gather you together. Then I will be pleased with you just
        as I am pleased with the sweet aroma of burning sacrifices. And I will put
        my holiness on display through you before the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'And when I bring you back to the soil of Israel, the land that I
        pledged my word to give to your ancestors, you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'You will remember your ways and all the vile actions by which you
        have defiled yourselves, and you will be disgusted with yourselves for all
        the evil things you did. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:43
        content: '  When God shows mercy, we become ashamed of our past and repent
          and turn to God for restoration. We then see that our transformation is
          not according to our merit but solely by his kindness and grace. See  ; 
          .    '
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "And when I deal with you, not as you deserve because of your wickedness,
        but in a way that brings honor to my name, then you, the people of Israel,
        will recognize that I am God. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "\u201CSon of man, look toward the south and prophesy against the
        forests of the southern land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "Prophesy to the southern forest, \u2018Hear the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>:
        Behold, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say to you that I am about
        to light a fire in you that will consume every green tree and every dry tree
        of your land! This blazing fire will not be extinguished as it spreads to
        the north and consumes everything in its path. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:47
        content: "  Or \u201Call faces from south to north will be scorched by it.\u201D    "
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "Everyone will know that it was I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        who started that fire, and no one will ever be able to put it out.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "But I protested and said, \u201CBut Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        everyone is already complaining that I only speak in riddles.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 20:49
        content: "  Or \u201CI am the maker of parables [allegories].\u201D See 
          .  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s Sword"
      title: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s Sword"
      number: 1
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s sword.</smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s
        judgment against Israel. This panel G constitutes the corresponding parallel
        with panel G</smallcaps><smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again,
        saying, "
      comments:
      - number: 21:1
        content: "  No other chapter in the Bible speaks more of      has been called
          the Song of the Sword. The Hebrew word for sword is used fourteen times
          in this chapter. Fourteen is the biblical number of salvation and deliverance.
          For the believer today, the \u201Csword\u201D is a metaphor for the Word
          of God. See  ;  . Just as Jesus is the Word of God with a sword coming
          from his mouth (see  ), we who follow him will be the \u201Csword company,\u201D
          who are conformed to his image and speak his words from our mouths. The
          words of his mouth are our cutting edge.    is the seventh panel (G) in
          the chiastic parallel structure in Ezekiel. This section contains an oracle
          dealing with Babylon as the instrument of    in ch.  , which contains an
          oracle of judgment against Edom for attacks against Israel and for their
          rejoicing over the destruction of Jerusalem at the hands of the Babylonians.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward Jerusalem [[COMMENT(0)]] and denounce
        her place of worship.  Prophesy against the land of Israel "
      comments:
      - number: 21:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cset your face toward Jerusalem.\u201D      Or \u201Csanctuaries.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "and say to the people, \u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to
        you: I am your enemy, and I am about to draw my sword and destroy the good
        and evil alike. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I am going to use my drawn sword to cut off the upright and wicked
        alike, everyone alive from the south to the north. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then everyone will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, am
        the one who has unsheathed my sword, and I will not put it back again!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CSon of man, groan with bitter grief before their eyes. Groan
        as though your heart is breaking with sorrow. "
      comments: []
    - name: "7: A Poem\u2014\u2019s Sword"
      title: "A Poem\u2014\u2019s Sword"
      number: 7
      content: "And when they ask, \u2018Why these groans?\u2019 reply, \u2018Because
        of what I\u2019ve heard is about to happen. Every heart will melt with fear,
        and every hand grow limp. Everyone will faint with fright and wet themselves.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Behold, it is coming now! It is here!\u2019 I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 21:7
        content: "  The Hebrew reads literally \u201Cand every knee will run with
          water,\u201D an image consistent with the classic depiction of visceral
          fear that gives rise to incontinence.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy the message that I, the Lord, give you:\u201CA
        sword, a sword of judgmenthas been sharpened and polished,"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "sharpened for a great slaughter, [[COMMENT(0)]]polished to flash
        like lightning!Should we rejoice in the dynasty  of my son, Judah? No!The
        sword despises every such stick. <smallcaps>\u2019s divine instrument of
        judgment (viz., the Babylonian army) against his people for their willful
        violation of his covenant over hundreds of years. And the statement that
        the \u201Csword despises every such stick [or \u201Cwooden rod,\u201D i.e.,
        the scepter of royal authority]\u201D means that the power of the invading
        Babylonian forces was unstoppable and inevitable. For under the permissive
        will of God, Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s army was granted leave to arrogantly trample
        on the Judean kingdom, without having any respect whatever for the legitimacy
        of her governing authority.</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 21:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cto slaughter a slaughter.\u201D      Or \u201Cscepter,\u201D
          a symbol of kingly authority. The historical context leaves us without
          doubt that this oracle refers to the impending demise of the Judean kingdom
          at the hands of the Babylonian army under King Nebuchadnezzar.      The
          last sentence of this verse is so unintelligible in the Hebrew text that
          a few translations omit it entirely. It could be understood in three ways:
          (1) It refers to the way Judah despised all the warnings of God. (2) It
          refers to the sword of God that takes no account of the status of the one
          it punishes. (3) It refers to the way King Zedekiah despised Nebuchadnezzar
          and disregarded the threats of the Babylonians. There is no doubt that
          in this chapter the \u201Csword\u201D refers to      "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: I handed over the sword for someone to polishso he can use it,sharp,
        shiny, and readyfor the hand of the executioner.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Shout and wail, son of man,for the sword will come against my people,and
        all the leaders of Israel.They are thrown to the sword like the rest of my
        people.So beat your breast in anguish, [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 21:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cslap your thigh.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: for surely, I am testing my people.What if the scepter of Judah,despised
        by the sword, does not survive? [[COMMENT(0)]]I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.
      comments:
      - number: 21:13
        content: "  Or literally \u201CWhat if even the rod that despised will not
          survive?\u201D or \u201CWhat if even the rod despises? It will not be!\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CSo prophesy, son of man, and strike hand to hand in anger!
        [[COMMENT(0)]]Let the sword strike twice, even three times. For the sword
        is prepared for those to be slain,a mighty sword to terrify,with a great
        slaughter from every side!"
      comments:
      - number: 21:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cclap your hands together.\u201D See v.  .      Or \u201CAnd
          the sword will be doubled a third time,\u201D with the possible meaning
          of \u201CLet the sword be twice, three times [as cruel].\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: This sword will make them stumble and fall,and their hearts will melt
        with fear.I have posted the threatening sword at every gate [[COMMENT(0)]]to
        flash like lightning, polished for the slaughter.
      comments:
      - number: 21:15
        content: "  Or \u201CI have taken the sword from its sheath at the [city]
          gates.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Slash to the right, and ready on the left,whichever way your blade
        turns!
      comments: []
    - name: '17: The King of Babylon Comes to Destroy Jerusalem'
      title: The King of Babylon Comes to Destroy Jerusalem
      number: 17
      content: "I also will strike hand to hand in angerand satisfy my fury!I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me: '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CSon of man, mark out two roads for the king of Babylon to come
        with his sword; both should originate from the same land. Then put up a signpost
        at the place where the road branches off to the city. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 21:19
        content: '  The signpost will indicate the city where each road leads. God
          was telling Ezekiel to make it easy for the King of Babylon to choose which
          city he wanted to attack.    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Mark out the routes for the sword to come to Rabbah-of-the-Ammonites,
        and to Judah, and its fortress of Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'For the king of Babylon is already at the place where the two roads
        begin. He is consulting his gods to decide which way to go by shuffling arrows
        and throwing them on the ground to see where they point. [[COMMENT(0)]] He
        asks his favorite idols  for advice, and he examines the liver of a sacrificed
        animal.   '
      comments:
      - number: 21:21
        content: "  This was the ancient practice of belomancy, tossing arrows with
          the names of enemies written upon them.      The Hebrew word    means \u201Chousehold
          gods [figurines].\u201D      This is the only instance in the Bible of
          a person seeking omens through studying the liver of an animal, a practice
          known as hepatoscopy.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: It tells him to take the road on the right leading to Jerusalem, so
        the king decides to go there. His plan is to ready the battering rams to
        be prepared when he gives the order for slaughter. His army will shout the
        battle cry and set up the battering rams against the gates. They will make
        siege ramps and construct siege towers.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CThe people of Jerusalem will believe that these omens are false,
        for they have made sworn treaties and think they are safe. But Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s
        decision to attack will remind them of their sins against God, and as a result,
        they will be captured. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u2018You have
        uncovered your waywardness by parading all your evil deeds. You flaunt your
        sins in everything you do. Because of this, your enemies will capture you
        by force!"
      comments: []
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018As for you, wicked and unholy prince of Israel,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has a message for you.
        Your doom is approaching. Your time is up, and I will put an end to your
        crimes. Take off your royal turban and remove your crown. Everything is about
        to be turned upside down. Lowly ones will be raised up, and those who seem
        important now will become nobodies.   "
      comments:
      - number: "21:25\u201326"
        content: '  That is, King Zedekiah.      See  ;  .    '
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018As for you, wicked and unholy prince of Israel,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has a message for you.
        Your doom is approaching. Your time is up, and I will put an end to your
        crimes. Take off your royal turban and remove your crown. Everything is about
        to be turned upside down. Lowly ones will be raised up, and those who seem
        important now will become nobodies.   "
      comments:
      - number: "21:25\u201326"
        content: '  That is, King Zedekiah.      See  ;  .    '
    - name: "27: \u2019s Punishment of the Ammonites"
      title: "\u2019s Punishment of the Ammonites"
      number: 27
      content: "A ruin, a ruin, I will make this city a ruin [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014until
        the one arrives, the rightful ruler.  Then I will hand him the crown to rule.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 21:27
        content: "  The three-fold use of the word \u201Cruin\u201D stresses how
          terrible will be the destruction of Jerusalem. The Hebrew word for \u201Cruin\u201D
          () is a play on the word for \u201Cguilt\u201D or \u201Cpunishment\u201D
          () in vv.  .      Who is this \u201Crightful ruler\u201D? Some believe
          the rightful ruler was Jehoiachin, previously dethroned. Some see it as
          a reference to Nebuchadnezzar, whom God was using to punish Jerusalem,
          or as perhaps a cryptic reference to the future Messiah, our Lord Jesus.
          See  .      Jesus Christ is the one who has the right to wear the \u201Cturban\u201D
          of vv.    (as our High Priest) and the \u201Ccrown\u201D (as the King).
          He is the one who initiated the King-Priest ministry after the order of
          Melchizedek. And he has made us part of his King-Priest ministry on earth.
          See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy and announce what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to the mocking [[COMMENT(0)]] Ammonites: \u2018A sword, a sword is drawn
        and ready for slaughter! It is a sharp, polished sword to flash like lightning
        and to destroy.   "
      comments:
      - number: 21:28
        content: "  The term    has the literal meaning of \u201Ctheir reproaches\u201D
          or \u201Ctheir expressions of contempt.\u201D However, in this context
          it is clear that these meanings also contain an element of mocking or taunting
          directed toward the people of Israel, as is made abundantly clear in  , 
          ; compare  .      The \u201Csword\u201D becomes a metonymy for the armies
          of the king of Babylon.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The visions you had are false. When you consulted your gods about
        what would happen, their answers were lies. Your day of judgment has come!
        It\u2019s high time for your punishment to reach its climax. The sword is
        going to cut off your heads!"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Put the sword back in its scabbard. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I will punish you in the land where you were born, the land of your origin. "
      comments:
      - number: 21:30
        content: "  In vv.  , God is speaking of the punishment coming to Nebuchadnezzar
          and Babylon for what they did to Jerusalem. God is going to punish the
          very \u201Csword\u201D he used to destroy the city. God will punish Nebuchadnezzar
          and his people in their homeland\u2014that is, Nebuchadnezzar will die
          in Babylon.  "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'I will vent my fury on you, blow the fire of my rage against you,
        and hand you over to brutal men whose skill is destruction. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "You will be fuel for the fire. Babylonian blood will flow in your
        homeland, and no one will remember anything about you. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Jerusalem\u2019s Sins"
      title: "Jerusalem\u2019s Sins"
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again and
        said, '
      comments:
      - number: 22:1
        content: "    is the eighth panel (H) in the chiastic parallel structure
          in Ezekiel. This section contains an oracle condemning the perversity of
          Israel\u2019s leaders\u2014the two adulterous sisters. Panel H constitutes
          the corresponding parallel with panel H  in ch.  , which also contains
          a parallel oracle of judgment focusing on \u201Cshepherds\u201D and \u201Csheep\u201D
          ()\u2014condemning the immoral and idolatrous leaders of Israel.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, are you ready to judge the city of murderers? [[COMMENT(0)]]
        You must confront her with all the disgusting things she has done! "
      comments:
      - number: 22:2
        content: "  Or literally \u201Ccity of bloods.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Prophesy to the city what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to them: \u2018Jerusalem, you bring doom upon yourselves because you
        have shed the blood of so many. You are defiled by your man-made gods. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'You have become guilty by the blood you have shed and defiled by
        your hand-made gods. Your time is up! [[COMMENT(0)]] Your day of reckoning
        is on the way. Therefore, I have made you an object of scorn and a laughingstock
        to all the nations. '
      comments:
      - number: 22:4
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cyou have come to your years,\u201D that is,
          your time has run out.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Nations near and far will taunt you, O&nbsp;infamous [[COMMENT(0)]]
        city, full of turmoil.
      comments:
      - number: 22:5
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cunclean of name.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Behold! The leaders of Israel within your walls,
        one and all, have selfishly abused their power to shed blood. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'They have despised their fathers and mothers, cheated the foreigners
        who live within your walls, and mistreated the widow and orphan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'All that I call holy, you have treated with contempt. You have dishonored
        my Sabbaths. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'In your city are those who slander in order to have someone murdered.
        Living among you are those who eat food sacrificed to false gods in mountain
        shrines and commit obscene acts. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Your men have sex with their father\u2019s wives. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        They force themselves on women who are having their periods and are ceremonially
        unclean. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:10
        content: "  Or \u201C[in your city are] men who uncover their father\u2019s
          nakedness.\u201D Although this seems to imply incestuous acts, it is more
          likely a euphemism for a stepmother\u2014another woman in his father\u2019s
          harem besides his own mother.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "In your city a man commits adultery with his neighbor\u2019s wife,
        and another man seduces his daughter-in-law or sister, his own father\u2019s
        daughter. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Some of your people will murder for pay. Some extort their neighbors
        with threats of violence, charging them exorbitant interest for obscene profits,
        yet they have entirely forgotten about me! I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Now I will bring my fists down [[COMMENT(0)]] on
        your acts of robbery and murder in your midst! "
      comments:
      - number: 22:13
        content: "  Or \u201CI will strike my hands together [in anger].\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Do you think your courage will endure when I am through with you?
        Do you think your hands will remain steady on your day of reckoning? I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken, and I will do it!
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will scatter you among the nations and send you
        into exile to foreign countries. I will put an end to the uncleanness within
        you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: The Refining Furnace'
      title: The Refining Furnace
      number: 16
      content: "Because of your own actions, you will be grossly defiled in the sight
        of the nations, and then you will understand and realize that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CSon of man, for me, the people of Israel have become worthless
        dross. They all have become like the useless byproduct of refined silver,
        bronze, tin, iron, lead, all mixed up together and left in the smelter; they
        are dross. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Therefore, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say to the people
        of Jerusalem, \u2018Since you have all become worthless dross, leftover metal,
        I will collect you inside Jerusalem. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 22:19
        content: "  It is likely that this prophecy of Ezekiel was fulfilled shortly
          before the siege of 589\u2013587 BC, when the people of Judah were crowding
          into Jerusalem to take refuge.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Just as the metalsmith collects silver, bronze, iron, lead, and tin
        in the furnace, and the fire is fanned underneath to melt them down, so I
        will collect you there and melt you down in my furious anger. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'I will put you all in the furnace and fan the fire of my rage to
        burn against you. I will melt you there in the middle of the furnace. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 22:21
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '22:  Punishes the Leaders'
      title: ' Punishes the Leaders'
      number: 22
      content: "As silver is refined in the smelter, so you will be melted down inside
        the city, and you will understand and recognize that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have vented my fury against you.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again and said: '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CSon of man, say to Israel, \u2018You are a land that has had
        no shower nor cleansing rain on the day of my anger. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Your prophets [[COMMENT(0)]] plot conspiracies as lions stalk their
        prey. They have devoured the people, enriched themselves by seizing their
        wealth and jewels, and left behind many widows. '
      comments:
      - number: 22:25
        content: "  Or \u201CYour princes\u201D (LXX).    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Her priests have violated my law and have no respect for what is
        holy. They have made no distinction between what is holy and what is common.
        They have not taught people the difference between clean and unclean; they
        ignore my Sabbaths, and I have been defiled among them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Within the land are leaders who are like a pack of wolves who rip
        apart their prey, shed blood, and kill people to get money dishonestly. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Her false prophets have plastered over these things with their empty
