    - name: "14: Death of Ezekiel\u2019s Wife"
      title: "Death of Ezekiel\u2019s Wife"
      number: 14
      content: "I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have decreed it. The time has come,
        and I will do it! I will not hold back or relent. I will show you no pity.
        I will judge you according to the way you have lived and acted. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CSon of man, behold, in the blink of an eye I am about to take
        from you your heart\u2019s dearest treasure, the one you love the most. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        But you must not weep or wail or let your tears stream down your cheeks. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe delight of your eyes.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Let no one hear your sobbing; don\u2019t show that you are grieving.
        Wrap a turban around your head, put sandals on your feet, and dress normally.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Don\u2019t cover your face,  and don\u2019t eat the customary
        food of mourners.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 24:17
        content: "  In that culture and time, mourners would go barefoot with their
          heads uncovered and their lower face covered with a veil. God instructed
          Ezekiel to dress normally and act like nothing had happened as a sign that
          Jerusalem\u2019s grief would come suddenly with no time to grieve or lament.
          The dearest thing to Ezekiel was his wife. The dearest thing to Jerusalem
          was her temple.      Literally \u201CDo not cover your mustache.\u201D
          Also in v.  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'So, I preached to the people the next day as usual, and by evening,
        my wife had died. And I did as I had been instructed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "The people then said to me, \u201CWhat\u2019s the meaning of this?
        Why are you acting this way?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and I replied, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        told me "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "to prophesy to the people of Israel the words of Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>:
        \u2018Behold! I am about to make my sanctuary ritually unclean. My temple
        has become your boast, the pride of your strength, the delight of your eyes,
        the joy of your hearts, and you believe it will keep you safe. But your children
        whom you left behind in Jerusalem will be killed by the sword. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Then you will do as I have done; you will not cover your faces nor
        eat the customary food of mourners. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'You will keep turbans on your heads and your sandals on your feet.
        You will not mourn nor weep but will waste away for your sins and groan among
        yourselves. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Thus Ezekiel is a sign for you. Everything he has done, you will
        do. And when this happens, you will certainly know that I am Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CAnd you, son of man, this is what will happen on the day that
        I deprive them of their temple-stronghold, their beautiful joy and glory,
        their heart\u2019s desire, and their greatest treasure\u2014I will also take
        away their sons and daughters. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'And on that day a survivor from Jerusalem will bring you the report. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "That same day, [[COMMENT(0)]] when he comes to you, your mouth will
        be opened, and you will be able to prophesy to the survivor and be silent
        no longer.  And you will be a living symbol of hope for them,  and they will
        see and acknowledge that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 24:27
        content: "  That is, the day when Nebuchadnezzar conquers Jerusalem.     
          This affirmation that Ezekiel will no longer be silent indicates the lifting
          of the prophet\u2019s mute condition, imposed upon him by God, except when
          God spoke directly to him, and he conveyed those messages to the people
          (see  ;  ).      Ezekiel\u2019s prophetic messages in the second half of
          the book will begin to focus more and more on the promised hope of divine
          forgiveness and spiritual renewal for the people of God.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Prophecy against Ammon'
      title: Prophecy against Ammon
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>. This panel J constitutes the corresponding
        parallel with panel J</smallcaps><smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me
        and said, '
      comments:
      - number: 25:1
        content: "    is the tenth panel (J) in the chiastic parallel structure in
          Ezekiel. This section is the first of three panels that contain oracles
          of judgment against the nations. Chapter    includes divine judgments against
          Ammon, Moab, Edom, and Philistia, of whom the first two will be destroyed
          by the Babylonians (\u201Cthe tribes of the eastern desert,\u201D v.  )
          and the latter two by Israel and    in  , which contains oracular judgments
          against Sidon and Egypt\u2014the latter at the hands of the Babylonians.
          Chapters    detail a series of prophecies of judgment against seven nations
          surrounding the land of Israel. God begins with Ammon, which is due east
          of Israel. The Ammonites can represent the principle of mixture. They lived
          on the edge of the desert north of Moab. Their origin was an incestuous
          relationship (see  ; see also  ;  ;  ).    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward the land of the Ammonites and prophesy
        against them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Say to them, \u2018Hear the words of Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        He says to you: You gloated when my temple became unfit for my presence.
        You celebrated when the land of Israel was left in ruins. And when the people
        of Judah were taken into captivity, you shouted, \u201CHooray!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Therefore, behold! I am handing you over to the tribes of the eastern
        desert to come and take possession of you. They will take over your country
        and make their home in you. They will feast on the crops of your fields and
        drink the milk. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: I will turn your great city Rabbah into a camel yard. Yes, I will
        turn all the land of Ammon into sheepfolds. Then you will recognize that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Furthermore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Since you have clapped your hands and danced for joy, full of
        malicious glee [[COMMENT(0)]] at Israel\u2019s fate, "
      comments:
      - number: 25:6
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cwith all your malice in [your] soul.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: Prophecy against Moab and Edom'
      title: Prophecy against Moab and Edom
      number: 7
      content: "therefore behold! My mighty hand will be against you for this. I
        will hand you over to be looted by the nations, and I will obliterate you
        as a nation and you will perish as a country. I will reduce you to nothing,
        and then you will recognize that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CMoab [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and Seir  have said that the people of Judah are no different from any other
        nation. "
      comments:
      - number: 25:8
        content: "  Although the Moabites were related to the Israelites (see  ),
          they became enemies when Israel came into the land after the Exodus (see 
          ). They joined with the Babylonians in the attack on Jerusalem. The Moabites
          can represent the principle of passivity or the inability to change or
          grow.      Seir is a mountain in Edom, also known as Mount Hermon. Some
          translations and the Septuagint omit \u201CSeir,\u201D believing it to
          be a gloss since Edom has its own prophecy in vv.  .    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Therefore, behold! I will let your enemies clear out the cities that
        defend the border of Moab\u2014your fine cities, jewels of your land\u2014Beth
        Jeshimoth, [[COMMENT(0)]] Baal-Meon,  and Kiriathaim.   "
      comments:
      - number: 25:9
        content: '  See  .      See  .      See  .    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'To the same eastern desert tribes that invade Ammon, I will hand
        over Moab so that Ammon will be forgotten forever as a nation. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Prophecy against Edom'
      title: Prophecy against Edom
      number: 11
      content: "I will carry out my punishment of Moab, and then they will know that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CThe people of Edom
        [[COMMENT(0)]] took revenge on the people of Judah and sinned greatly in
        doing so. "
      comments:
      - number: 25:12
        content: '  Although the Edomites were related to the Israelites as descendants
          of Esau (see  ;  ), they lived as enemies throughout their history. It
          is believed the Edomites joined Nebuchadnezzar in his attack on Jerusalem,
          rejoicing when the city was destroyed (see  ). The Edomites can represent
          the principle of the flesh or the natural man.    is a variant form of 
          .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: \u2018My
        hand will be against you, and I will slaughter every person and animal living
        among you. There will be no one left anywhere in the land, from Teman to
        Dedan, all the people will fall by the sword! "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Prophecy against the Philistines'
      title: Prophecy against the Philistines
      number: 14
      content: "I will use my people Israel to take my vengeance on Edom. My people
        will treat Edom as my furious anger demands, and they will realize that this
        is my vengeance! I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u201CThe Philistines [[COMMENT(0)]]
        took revenge on the people of Judah, with deep hatred.  They did their best
        to destroy them because of their long-standing hatred. "
      comments:
      - number: 25:15
        content: "  The Philistines lived on the coast of the Mediterranean Sea,
          southwest of Judah. They were a constant threat to Israel from the time
          of King David. They, too, came to the aid of Nebuchadnezzar when he attacked
          Jerusalem. The Philistines can represent the principle of the mind of man,
          an earthly mindset that wallows in the mud of humanity. They can also be
          likened to their champion Goliath, the giant who opposed God\u2019s people
          from advancing. Goliath is a picture of the mind of man.      Or \u201Cmalice
          of soul.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: My hand
        will be against the Philistines; I will exterminate the Cherethite tribe
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and destroy the rest of the coastal peoples. '
      comments:
      - number: 25:16
        content: "  The Cherethites were another tribe of people who lived in the
          southern territory occupied by the Philistines. \u201CThe Cherethites\u201D
          was a general term used for the Philistines.  "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "I will execute frightful acts of vengeance and punish them in my
        wrath! And then they will realize that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        exacted my vengeance on them.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Prophecy against Tyre'
      title: Prophecy against Tyre
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>. It is a judgment
        that is climactic and irreversible. From this point on, principally after
        the judgments against Sidon and Egypt (panel J</smallcaps>On the first day
        of the month  in the eleventh year of our captivity, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to me and said: '
      comments:
      - number: 26:1
        content: "    is the eleventh panel (K) in the chiastic parallel structure
          in Ezekiel. This section is the second of three panels that contain oracles
          of judgment against the nations. This section contains the climactic oracle
          of judgment against the nation of Tyre. In Ezekiel\u2019s prophecy, Tyre
          is the embodiment of blasphemous arrogance, the personification of satanic
          pride\u2014the quintessential heart of idolatry. Panel K is the central
          panel, or locus, of the chiasmus as it demonstrates the climactic judgment
          of  against the most godless of nations at the time of Ezekiel. This judgment
          marks the turning point of the prophecy in that it highlights the pinnacle
          of God\u2019s anger against gross idolatry and rebellion against  \u2014),
          chs.    (panels I  through A) emphasize the glorious provisions of God\u2019s
          promised renewal, spiritual transformation, and everlasting forgiveness
          of sin, encapsulated in the provisions of the coming new covenant and the
          certainty of the promise of the arrival of the Messiah, Jesus Christ, the
          Son of God, on earth. Chapters    contain prophecies of judgment against
          Tyre. The city of Tyre was a prosperous commercial center situated north
          of Israel on an island in the Mediterranean Sea just off the coast of Phoenicia
          (see  ). Tyre and her sister city, Sidon, had significant influence on
          the Northern Kingdom of Israel. Jezebel, wife of Ahab, came from Tyre (see 
          ). Tyre was a city of trade and commerce. Hiram, king of Tyre, was a devoted
          friend to King David (see  ) and helped him and King Solomon in their building
          operations (see  ;  ;  ,  ). The god of Tyre was Melkart, an idol with
          hands outstretched to receive human blood. Located today in modern Lebanon,
          Tyre has become a historical example of what happens to a people that mock
          Israel\u2019s God. Tyre\u2019s worldwide trading empire represents the
          principle of the love of money, trafficking, and merchandising\u2014the
          pride of the satanic world system.      The dating of this prophecy is
          incomplete because it does not specify what month of the year. Some translations
          leave a gap, assuming it is missing from the manuscripts. It is difficult
          to know what month Ezekiel received this prophecy; however, Jewish scholars
          conclude it was the fifth month since it was the month that Jerusalem fell.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the people of Tyre have been cheering the demise
        of Jerusalem, saying, \u2018Hooray! She is fallen! The Gateway to the Nations
        is shattered! An opportunity has swung open for us. Now we will grow rich
        off her destruction!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CTherefore, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say to Tyre,\u2018Behold,
        I am against you,As the sea raises up its wavesI will raise up many nations
        surging against you."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: They will destroy the walls of Tyre,and demolish her high towers.I
        will sweep away her rubbleand reduce her to nothing but a bare rock. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 26:4
        content: "  A play on words since    means \u201Crock.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Tyre will be an island where fishermen dry out their nets.Your enemies
        will take away everything you have.I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have decreed it.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: Nebuchadnezzar Will Attack Tyre'
      title: Nebuchadnezzar Will Attack Tyre
      number: 6
      content: "And as for her settlements [[COMMENT(0)]] on the mainland,they will
        all be slaughtered,and they will certainly learn that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 26:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cdaughters.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to Tyre:\u201CLook!
        I will bring Nebuchadnezzar,king of Babylon, the world\u2019s most powerful
        king,sweeping down from the north to destroy youwith horses, chariots, cavalry,
        and an enormous army. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 26:7
        content: '  The siege of Tyre lasted thirteen years, but the complete destruction
          of the city was accomplished later by Alexander the Great.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: His armies will massacre your settlements on the mainland.They will
        lay siege to you and construct towers to attack you.They will build siege-ramps
        against youand lay siege to you with interlocking shields over their heads.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 26:8
        content: "  Or literally \u201Craise a shield on you.\u201D This is likely
          a reference to the Roman military formation called the Tortoise. When Roman
          soldiers attacked a city wall, they would raise their shields above their
          heads to protect themselves from arrows, spears, and stones hurled at them.
          A \u201Croof of shields\u201D is a good description of this defensive military
          practice.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: His soldiers will pummel your walls with battering ramsand demolish
        your towers with iron bars.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "You\u2019ll be covered with dust from their many horses and chariots.Your
        walls will shake at the rumble of their chariot wheels.His thundering horses
        will make your walls trembleas they storm through your gates and breach your
        walls."
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: With galloping horses they will trample through every streetand slaughter
        your people with the sword!They will throw your mighty pillars [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to the ground.
      comments:
      - number: 26:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe pillars of your strength.\u201D This is likely a
          reference to the famous pillars of the Temple of Heracles in Tyre.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Your enemies will take for themselves your valuable possessionsand
        loot your merchandise.They will break down your walls and destroy your luxurious
        homes. [[COMMENT(0)]]And they will hurl the rubble and timber into the sea.
      comments:
      - number: 26:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe houses of your desire.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: I will silence the sound of your songs,and the music of your stringed
        instruments will not be heard again.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Lament over Tyre'
      title: Lament over Tyre
      number: 14
      content: "I will reduce you to a bare rockwhere fishermen dry their nets,never
        to be rebuilt.I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken, and I have
        decreed it.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to Tyre: \u201CSurely, the
        islands will quake with fear at the sound of your fall. They will hear the
        groan of your wounded when your slaughter takes place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'All the princes of the sea [[COMMENT(0)]] will vacate their thrones,
        laying aside their regal robes and embroidered cloaks. They will clothe themselves
        with trembling as they sit on the ground, stunned at your fate. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:16
        content: '  That is, the leaders of the islands and seacoast nations that
          traded with Tyre.    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "This is the funeral song they will sing over you:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018How
        you have vanished from the seas,O&nbsp;famous city, once a sea power with
        many people!You inspired great terrorin all those who lived in her."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: Tyre Will Go Down to the Abyss'
      title: Tyre Will Go Down to the Abyss
      number: 18
      content: "Now, on the day of your fall,the islands and coasts are trembling
        with fear.They are paralyzed with great fear,because Tyre has vanished completely!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CWhen I make you a
        place of ruins like other deserted cities and I raise the deep to sweep over
        you and the ocean depths to cover you, "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'then I will fling you down to the world of the dead to join the people
        of long ago. I will make you dwell deep in the underworld, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the abyss. And like the ruins of long ago, you will sink with them into
        oblivion. I will make sure that no one will ever live in you again, nor will
        you take your place in the land of the living.   '
      comments:
      - number: 26:20
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cthe land of the lowest places.\u201D     
          As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cbut I will set my
          beauty [glory] in the land of the living.\u201D By implication, the judgment
          of God against Tyre will set his glory on display. Ezekiel prophesied the
          fall of Tyre 250 years before it happened.  "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "I will bring you to a dreadful, terrifying end, and you will be no
        more! People will look for you but never find you again. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Funeral Song for Tyre'
      title: A Funeral Song for Tyre
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, sing a funeral song for Tyre. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Say to Tyre, the city with ports on the Mediterranean Sea, merchant
        city for many peoples and many islands:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you:Tyre, you have boasted: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CI am the most beautiful
        city in the world!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 27:3
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Your frontiers were on the high sea,and those who built youmade you
        perfect in beauty.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: As if they were building a shipthey used cypress from Mount Hermon
        [[COMMENT(0)]]for all your boards,and a tall cedar from Lebanonto make a
        mast to stand above you.
      comments:
      - number: 27:5
        content: "  Or \u201CJuniper [fir tree] from Senir.\u201D Senir is the Amorite
          name for Mount Hermon (see  ). In    God uses the metaphor of a ship to
          describe Tyre. The Grecian juniper tree is known to grow to a height of
          over sixty feet (eighteen meters).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: They made your oarsfrom oaks of Bashan,and made you a fine deck with
        pinesthey took from the coasts of Cyprus,and they decorated it with ivory.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Your sails and banners were of colorfulembroidered linen from Egypt.Your
        deck awnings were made fromthe finest purple and scarlet cloth from Cyprus.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 27:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe coasts of Elishah,\u201D a city on the island of
          Cyprus.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: Your oarsmen were rulers  [[COMMENT(0)]] from the cities of Sidon
        and Arvad,and your own seasoned men were your sailors.
      comments:
      - number: 27:8
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. In vv.  , God lists those
          who worked on the \u201Cship\u201D of Tyre and describes the crew and those
          who repaired it.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The elders and craftsmen of Byblos [[COMMENT(0)]]were those who caulked
        your seams.\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Ships and sailors the world over came to trade
        with you. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:9
        content: "  Or \u201CGebal,\u201D better known as Byblos, a town about 90
          miles (144 kilometers) north of Tyre.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Your army was composed of warriors from Persia, [[COMMENT(0)]] Lud, 
        and Libya.  By hanging their weapons on your deck,  they displayed your splendor. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:10
        content: "  This is the first mention of Persia in the Bible. The ancient
          Persian people lived in the land known today as Iran.      Or \u201CLydia,\u201D
          the western part of modern-day Turkey.      Or \u201CPut,\u201D identified
          as modern-day Libya.      Soldiers who traveled by ship in that day would
          hang their helmets and shields on the sides of the ship. In the sunlight
          the dozens of shiny shields and helmets would have looked impressive.    "
    - name: "11: Tyre\u2019s Former Influence"
      title: "Tyre\u2019s Former Influence"
      number: 11
      content: "Soldiers from Arvad [[COMMENT(0)]] and Helech manned your walls all
        around. Brave warriors  manned your watchtowers, hanging their shields all
        around your walls to make your beauty complete.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 27:11
        content: "    means \u201Cden of thieves.\u201D Arvad was an island renowned
          for its seamen.      Or \u201Cmen of Gamad.\u201D Although many scholars
          see this as a reference to a town in Syria, the Hebrew word    means \u201Cbrave
          warrior.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018The people of Tarshish [[COMMENT(0)]] traded with
        you because of your abundant resources of every kind. They imported your
        products and exported silver, iron, tin, and lead. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:12
        content: '  Tarshish was a trading colony on the west coast of Spain. The
          influence of Tyre was great, for Tarshish was almost twenty-five hundred
          miles (four thousand kilometers) from Tyre. Tarshish at that time was considered
          at the edge of the known world (see  ). There are about twenty countries
          and lands mentioned in    that traded with Tyre. The countries range from
          the western end of the Mediterranean Sea to the northern tip of Mesopotamia
          and the southern tip of the Arabian Peninsula. This impressive list demonstrates
          how important and influential Tyre and her worldwide trade were.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The Greeks [[COMMENT(0)]] along with nations of Tubal  and Meshech 
        traded with you. They sold you slaves  and metal utensils. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:13
        content: "  Or \u201CJavan,\u201D the word for \u201CIonia\u201D or \u201CGreece.\u201D
          It is the ancestral branch of the Greek people.        means \u201Cbrought
          forth.\u201D In contemporary scholarship Tubal is considered to be Tabal,
          an Anatolian state and region north of the Black Sea, identified in Assyrian
          sources. There is a city in Russia named \u201CTubolsk.\u201D        means
          \u201Cdrawing out.\u201D Meshech was the ancestor of a people identified
          by Assyrian records as the \u201CMuscu\u201D and by Josephus as the Cappadocian
          \u201CMosocheni\u201D (or \u201CMushki,\u201D possibly Moscow).      Or
          \u201CThey traded with the soul of man.\u201D They were human traffickers.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The people of Beth Togarmah [[COMMENT(0)]] traded for your goods,
        your war horses and work horses and mules. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:14
        content: '  Beth Togarmah likely refers to the people of Turkey, although
          some scholars identify Beth Togarmah with Armenia, which is known for horse
          breeding.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The people of Rhodes [[COMMENT(0)]] traded with you; many coastal
        lands were your special customers and paid you in ivory tusks and ebony wood.   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:15
        content: "  Or \u201CDedan,\u201D an oasis in the Arabian desert. Rhodes
          is a Greek island and more easily fits as a sea trading partner with Tyre.
          The Septuagint is \u201CRhodes.\u201D      The Targum and the Jewish sage
          Rashi interpret the Hebrew word used here as \u201Cpeacocks.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Edom [[COMMENT(0)]] traded with you emeralds, purple cloth, embroidered
        work and fine linen, coral and rubies for your many fine manufactured goods. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:16
        content: "  Or \u201CAram [Syria].\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Judah and the land of Israel also paid for your goods with the finest
        millet, [[COMMENT(0)]] spices,  honey, olive oil, and balm. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cwheat from Minnith,\u201D a region in Ammon recognized
          for its strain of wheat. See also  .      The meaning of this Hebrew term 
          \u2014a hapax legomenon\u2014is unknown. But the context suggests it is
          some kind of food, possibly a general term for \u201Cspices.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Damascus traded with you, for quantities of your abundant resources
        of every kind, furnishing you with wine from Helbon [[COMMENT(0)]] and unbleached
        wool,   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:18
        content: "  Helbon is a Syrian town (present day Chalbum) located about ten
          miles (sixteen kilometers) north of Damascus, famous for high-quality wine.     
          Or \u201Cwool from Zahar.\u201D Since the location of Zahar is unknown,
          some etymologists believe it is a reference to the color of light yellow,
          thus \u201Cunbleached wool.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'casks of wine from Izalla, [[COMMENT(0)]] polished iron, cassia and
        calamus  in exchange for your goods. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:19
        content: "  The Hebrew text is uncertain. It reads literally \u201CVedan
          [or Dan] and Javan from Uzal.\u201D It is somewhat strange to link Dan
          in northern Israel and Javan (Greece) with Uzal, a region in southern Arabia.
          The Hebrew word    is related to an Akkadian word for \u201Cbarrel\u201D
          or \u201Ccask\u201D for storing wine. Izalla is a city in northeast Syria,
          near the upper Tigris River.      Cassia and calamus (or \u201Ccane\u201D)
          are spice plants found in northern India and China.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Dedan [[COMMENT(0)]] traded with you in saddle blankets.   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:20
        content: "  Dedan may be identified as the modern-day oasis of Al-\u2019Ula
          in northern Arabia or possibly Kuwait.      Or literally \u201Cclothes
          of freedom.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Arabia and all the sheikhs of Kedar [[COMMENT(0)]] were your clients, 
        selling sheep and goats to you. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:21
        content: "  Kedar was one of the sons of Ishmael (see  ), whose descendants
          lived as nomadic tribes in the northern Arabian Desert.      Or literally
          \u201Ctraders of your hand,\u201D a possible phrase to describe them as
          Tyre\u2019s agents who acted on their behalf.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Businessmen of Sheba [[COMMENT(0)]] and Raamah  traded with you the
        finest spices, precious stones, and gold. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:22
        content: '  Sheba was a kingdom in the southwestern part of the Arabian Peninsula.
          See  .      Raamah was possibly the capital city of Sheba.    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Haran, [[COMMENT(0)]] Canneh,  and Eden,  the merchants of Sheba,
        Asshur,  and Chilmad  were your trading partners. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:23
        content: "  Haran was an Assyrian city about 310 miles (498 kilometers) from
          Tyre. Haran was the place from which Abraham migrated to Canaan (see  ).     
          Canneh was an Assyrian trade center of uncertain location.      This is
          not the \u201Cgarden of Eden\u201D but a Syrian city-state called Beth
          Eden located west of Haran.      Asshur was the capital city of Assyria
          on the Tigris River almost five hundred miles (over eight hundred kilometers)
          from Tyre.      Chilmad was an Assyrian city of unknown location. This
          chapter lists thirty-six nations or people groups that traded with Tyre.    "
    - name: '24: Tyre, the Mistress of the Mediterranean'
      title: Tyre, the Mistress of the Mediterranean
      number: 24
      content: "In your marketplace they sold you gorgeous embroidered clothing,
        purple cloaks, multi-colored carpets, and well-made cords for your merchandise.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Heavily loaded Spanish ships [[COMMENT(0)]]carried
        your wares in the heart of the seas."
      comments:
      - number: 27:25
        content: "  Or \u201CShips of Tarshish [from Spain],\u201D a phrase that
          came to mean large, seagoing cargo vessels.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: Your oarsmen rowed youout to the open sea.Stormy east winds wrecked
        youand sent you to the bottom of the sea.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: On the day of your shipwreck,your riches, your goods, your cargo,your
        seamen, your sailors,your caulkers, your dealers,all the warriors you carry,and
        all the passengers who are aboardwill sink into the heart of the sea!
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: When they hear the shouts of your drowning sailors,the people on shore
        will tremble with fear. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 27:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe waves will surge.\u201D The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: All the oarsmen will abandon ship;the seamen and sailors will come
        ashore.
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: They will wail aloud over youand weep bitterly.They will throw dust
        on their heads in mourningand lie in ashes.
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: They will shave their heads in sorrow for youand dress themselves
        in sackcloth.They will weep bitterly for you, Tyre,with heartfelt sorrow
        over your fall.
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Grieving, they will chant a funeral song for you,and wail with lament
        over you, saying:\u201CWho is like Tyre,like a tower surrounded by the sea?\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cnow silent in the midst of the sea.\u201D The Hebrew
          is uncertain.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: When you exported your goodsto satisfy so many peopleswith the abundance
        of your wealth and waresyou enriched the kings of the earth.
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: Now you are broken to pieces by the waves;you lie at the bottom of
        the sea.Your cargo and all your crewhave foundered with you.
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: Those who dwell on the coast and the islandsare stunned at your fate.Horror
        is written on the faces of their kings,and their hair stands on end.
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Your trading partners hiss at you in scorn,for you have come to a
        dreadful end.You are gone forever, never to return!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:36
        content: "  The kingdom of Tyre can be compared to Babylon, the harlot of 
          . Tyre enriched the kingdoms of the world with her wealth and merchandise
          (see  ). Those who traded with her bought and sold, exemplifying the ones
          who will receive the mark of the beast (see  ) and reminding us of Jesus,
          who cleansed God\u2019s temple, throwing out all those who bought and sold.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Judgment on the King of Tyre'
      title: Judgment on the King of Tyre
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, say to the prince of Tyre, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Because your heart is swollen
        with pride, you have said,\u201CI am a god. I sit in the seat of a god,enthroned
        in the heart of the sea.\u201DYou think you are as wise as a god,but you\u2019re
        nothing but a man,   not a god at all!"
      comments:
      - number: 28:2
        content: "  The prophecy in the following verses details the judgment of
          the king of Tyre, who, according to Phoenician annals and the Jewish historian
          Josephus, was Ithobalus II. Ezekiel prophesied his judgment as though it
          had already happened. Although Ezekiel was giving a prophecy over a literal
          king, he was dealing with the spiritual principality of Tyre, not simply
          a man. This chapter can be interpreted figuratively since it does not entirely
          apply to a human king. This is recognized as a difficult text that inspired
          diverse interpretations. According to rabbinic tradition, the prophecy
          speaks of the fall of the first man, Adam, while the church fathers found
          in the same text a description of the fall of Lucifer. The first half of
          Ezekiel\u2019s prophecy (vv.  ) seems to refer to a human (Adam) while
          the second half (vv.  ) seems to refer to Satan (Lucifer). Verses    are
          addressed to the \u201Cprince of Tyre\u201D while verses    are addressed
          to the \u201Cking of Tyre.\u201D For a detailed study of this chapter,
          see Hector M. Patmore,    (Leiden: Brill Academic Publishers, Inc., 2012).     
          Or \u201Cyou are Adam [man].\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So, you really think you are wiser than Daniel, [[COMMENT(0)]]and
        no mystery baffles you? '
      comments:
      - number: 28:3
        content: "  See  ;  .      Or literally \u201Cno secret is dark from you.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: By your wisdom and vast understandingyou have amassed a great fortune!You
        have accumulated gold and silverand placed them into your royal treasuries.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Through your great wisdom in trading,your fortune has continued to
        increase,but it has made your heart grow prouder.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you:Do you really
        think your heart is like the heart of God? [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 28:6
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: See for yourself as I bring ruthless enemies against you,the most
        brutal of the nations!They will unleash their swordsagainst all that your
        marvelous wisdom has built,and they will strike down your splendor! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 28:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cprofane your brightness.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: You will die a violent deathin the heart of the sea.They will throw
        you down into the abyss!
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Will you still say in the presence of your killers,\u201CDon\u2019t
        you know I\u2019m a god?\u201DBut you will be merely a mortal man, and not
        a god,when you are in the clutchesof the ones who strike you down!"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: The King of Tyre Is Dead'
      title: The King of Tyre Is Dead
      number: 10
      content: "You will die like an outcast, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s ownership
        of his covenant people in the old covenant era.</smallcaps>a shameful death
        at the hand of foreigners.I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have decreed
        it!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 28:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cdie the death of the uncircumcised,\u201D that is, the
          death of an outcast, cut off from others. The term \u201Cuncircumcised\u201D
          () is a universal descriptor in Scripture to describe those who have been
          excluded from the community of God\u2019s people, primarily because of
          their rejection of God\u2019s unique character as the one true and living
          God. The physical mark of circumcision was, of course, the badge of      "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CSon of man, mourn for the king of Tyre. Say to him, \u2018Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018You were once
        the consummate model of perfection. [[COMMENT(0)]]You were full of great
        wisdom,and your beauty seemed perfect."
      comments:
      - number: 28:12
        content: "  Or \u201Ca seal of perfection\u201D (LXX). The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: You lived in Eden, in the very garden of God.Every precious jewel
        formed your mantle.You were dressed in splendor with diamonds,carnelian,
        topaz, chrysolite, beryl,onyx, sapphire, turquoise, and emeralds; [[COMMENT(0)]]each
        gem engraved in settings of gold. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, made
        them for you on the day I created you.
      comments:
      - number: 28:13
        content: "  The nine precious stones listed in this verse are nearly impossible
          to identify with any certainty, as a comparison of other translations reveals.
          Although the high priest\u2019s breastplate had twelve stones, the three
          missing stones in this list are included in the Septuagint. See  ;  ; 
          ;  .      The Hebrew of this clause is uncertain.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I placed you with an anointed guardian cherub. [[COMMENT(0)]]You
        were on the holy mountain of God <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>where you walked
        among the fiery stones. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:14
        content: "  The meaning of this Hebrew sentence is uncertain.      The mountain
          of God is the dwelling place of  (see  ). The garden of Eden is likely
          a metaphor for this mountain, for the elevated location of the garden of
          Eden is indicated by the fact that a single river flows out of it, then
          divides into four rivers (see  ). The mountain of God is also the location
          of the New Jerusalem (see  ).      Or \u201Cyou came to be in the midst
          of the firestones.\u201D These firestones were possibly the hedge surrounding
          the manifestation of God\u2019s glory (see  ).    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: Your ways were blameless from the day I created you,until wickedness
        first appeared in you.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Your vast wealth filled you with violence and sin.So, I have cast
        you down in disgracefrom the mountain of God.I banished you, O&nbsp;guardian
        cherub,from among the stones of fire.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: Your heart became swollen with pride because of your beauty;your thirst
        for glory corrupted your wisdom.So, I hurled you down to the earth,and displayed
        you as a warning to other kings.
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "So great was your sin\u2014the injustice of your buying and selling.You
        defiled your sanctuaries.So, I set a fire inside of you,and it consumed you
        entirely!I reduced you to ashes on the groundbefore the eyes of all who saw
        you."
      comments: []
    - name: '19: Prophecy against Sidon'
      title: Prophecy against Sidon
      number: 19
      content: "All who once knew youare stunned at your fate.You have come to a
        terrible, dreadful end,and will be no more!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me and said, '
      comments:
      - number: 28:20
        content: "    constitutes panel J  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          These chapters deal with the divine judgment on Sidon and Egypt\u2014the
          latter at the hands of the Babylonians. This section serves as the first
          panel of the \u201Cdescending\u201D arm of the chiasmus. It parallels the
          group of oracles against other pagan nations in ch.    (i.e., panel J).    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward Sidon [[COMMENT(0)]] and prophesy against
        her "
      comments:
      - number: 28:21
        content: "  Sidon is a port city on the eastern coast of the Mediterranean
          Sea about twenty-five miles (forty kilometers) north of Tyre. The city
          was founded by Canaan\u2019s firstborn son (see  ). The king of Sidon rebelled
          against the Babylonians in 594 BC and was conquered by Nebuchadnezzar during
          the same campaign that destroyed Jerusalem. Sidon is the seventh of the
          enemies surrounding Israel that are dealt with in  . Sidon is now known
          as Saida, a small seaport in Lebanon. See  ,  ;  ;    (and second footnote);   
          (and footnote);  .    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "with these words: \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to
        you:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Behold, I am against you, Sidon;I will manifest my
        glory in youwhen I bring my judgment upon you!Everyone will see my display
        of holinessand they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: Israel Delivered and Restored'
      title: Israel Delivered and Restored
      number: 23
      content: "For I will send a plague,and there will be blood in her streets.Enemies
        will attack her on all sidesby the sword raised up against her,and the dead
        will fall in heaps [[COMMENT(0)]] within the city.Then they will know that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 28:23
        content: "  The Pilel form of the verb stem    likely denotes intensity,
          thus, \u201Cfall in heaps.\u201D  "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CAs for the people of Israel, there will no longer be any hostile
        nation surrounding them like thorns or briars that would hurt or pierce them.
        Then people will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CWhen I regather the
        people of Israel from every place where they have been scattered, I will
        display my holiness among them for all the nations to see. They will live
        in the land that I gave to my servant Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "And they will live there securely, building houses and planting vineyards.
        When I execute judgment on all the mocking, hostile nations surrounding them,
        they will live in safety, and they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God they worship.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Prophecy against Egypt'
      title: Prophecy against Egypt
      number: 1
      content: 'In the tenth year of our exile, on the twelfth day of the tenth month,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 29:1
        content: '  This would have been January of 586 BC, six months before the
          fall of Jerusalem and fifteen years before Nebuchadnezzar invaded Egypt.
          Chapters    contain seven prophecies against Egypt.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward Hophra  [[COMMENT(0)]] king of Egypt
        and prophesy against him and against all Egypt. "
      comments:
      - number: 29:2
        content: "  Or \u201CPharaoh,\u201D which means \u201Cking.\u201D Hophra,
          mentioned in  , was the fourth king of the Twenty-sixth Dynasty of Egyptian
          pharaohs. He reigned from 589 to 570 BC.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Tell them what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Behold,
        I am against you, Pharaoh king of Egypt\u2014the great monster [[COMMENT(0)]]
        wallowing in its waterways.You boasted: \u201CI made the Nile River for myself,
        and I own it!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 29:3
        content: "  Possible translations of the Hebrew word    include \u201Cserpent,\u201D
          \u201Cdragon,\u201D \u201Csea monster,\u201D \u201Ccrocodile,\u201D and
          \u201CLeviathan.\u201D See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . This \u201Cgreat monster\u201D
          was one of the gods of Egypt. Egypt represents bondage\u2014the bondage
          of sin and of the world.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: I will put hooks through your jaws,and make the fish of the Nile stick
        to your scales.Then I will drag you out of your waterwayswith all your fish
        clinging to your scales.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: I will leave you and all your fishon the ground to die in the desert.You
        will die in the open field,and I will feed youto the wild animals and the
        birds of heaven,and no one will collect your bones or bury them.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then all the inhabitants of Egypt will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201C&nbsp;\u2018The
        Lord says to Egypt:You have been no help whatsoever to my people, Israel;you
        are nothing more than a crutch of flimsy reeds!"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Wherever they grasped you, you broke in their handsand splinters pierced
        their hands. [[COMMENT(0)]]Whenever they leaned on you, you collapsed,and
        sent them sprawling.
      comments:
      - number: 29:7
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Ctore [dislocated]
          their shoulders.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018So, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to
        you: I will bring war against you to eliminate both people and animals. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The land of Egypt will become an empty desert, and they will know
        that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. Because you boasted, \u201CThe Nile
        is mine, I made it. It\u2019s all mine,\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'therefore, I am your enemy and the enemy of your waterways. I will
        reduce Egypt to a desolate, empty desert, from Migdol [[COMMENT(0)]]  in
        the north to Syene   in the south, as far as the border of Ethiopia.   '
      comments:
      - number: 29:10
        content: "  Migdol was a fortress in northern Egypt where Jews found refuge
          (see  ;  ).      Syene is modern Aswan in southern Egypt.      Or \u201CCush.\u201D
          To the Egyptians all the territory south of Aswan was known as Cush, which
          was called Ethiopia in Greco-Roman times and included portions of modern
          Sudan.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'No person or animal will pass through it. For forty years it will
        remain uninhabited. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: I will turn Egypt into the most desolate of lands, and for forty years
        its cities will be the most desolate of ruined cities. And I will scatter
        your people among the nations and disperse them among foreign lands.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018However, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says
        this: After forty years, I will gather the Egyptians back from the nations
        where I scattered them. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 29:13
        content: '  Like the exiled Israelites, the Egyptians were promised that
          they, too, would be brought back to their land.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I will bring the Egyptian captives back and restore them to the way
        they were before in their homeland of Pathros. [[COMMENT(0)]] There they
        will be an insignificant kingdom. '
      comments:
      - number: 29:14
        content: '  That is, southern Egypt.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Egypt will be the weakest kingdom of all and no longer dominate other
        nations. For I will reduce it so that it will never again rule over the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: Nebuchadnezzar Will Conquer Egypt'
      title: Nebuchadnezzar Will Conquer Egypt
      number: 16
      content: "It will never again be strong enough for the people of Israel to
        trust in. Its fate will be a reminder of Israel\u2019s sin when they put
        their confidence in Egypt to help them. Then they will know that I am Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'In the twenty-seventh year of our exile, on the first day of the
        first month, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CSon of man, Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon has taken his army
        and launched an attack against Tyre and inflicted a heavy toll upon his soldiers.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Their helmets have rubbed their heads bare, and their heavy
        loads made their shoulders raw and chafed, yet neither Nebuchadnezzar nor
        his army gained any reward from the campaign he led against Tyre. "
      comments:
      - number: 29:18
        content: '  The Babylonian siege against Tyre lasted thirteen years.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, will hand Egypt over to Nebuchadnezzar,
        king of Babylon. He will carry off its riches and loot the wealth of Egypt
        to pay the wages of his army. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: I am giving him Egypt as a reward for the labor he has undertaken
        on my behalf. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken!
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CAt that time, I will raise up a new day of power [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for the people of Israel. And Ezekiel, I will open your mouth, and when you
        speak, the people will listen to you. Then they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 29:21
        content: "  Or literally \u201Ca horn.\u201D The horn of an ox or ram was
          a symbol of power, authority, and prosperity. God was decreeing that he
          would cause Israel to grow strong again.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Prophecy against Egypt'
      title: Prophecy against Egypt
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me again, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy and announce what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to Egypt: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Weep and wail, for the day
        of disaster is here! "
      comments:
      - number: 30:2
        content: "  Mighty Egypt, a dominant world power for centuries, known for
          her pagan worship, was being judged by the Sovereign God. King Nebuchadnezzar
          and the Babylonians were the instruments in God\u2019s hands to bring Egypt\u2019s
          downfall.      Literally \u201CWoe worth the day.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Yes, the day is near, the day of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> is
        near!It will be a day dark with clouds,a time of trouble for the nations.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CWar will come upon Egypt, and terror will invade the land of
        Ethiopia. [[COMMENT(0)]] Egypt\u2019s foundations will be leveled, multitudes
        will be slaughtered, and her riches  will be carried away. "
      comments:
      - number: 30:4
        content: "  Or \u201CCush,\u201D that is, the upper Nile region.      These
          \u201Criches\u201D would also include the people themselves.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Egypt and all her allies, [[COMMENT(0)]] Ethiopia, Libya,  and Lydia, 
        all Arabia, and Kub \u2014they will all fall by the sword!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cand the sons of my covenant\u201D (LXX), that is, the
          Jews.      Or \u201CPut.\u201D      Or \u201CLud.\u201D      Or \u201CLub\u201D
          (LXX). The location of this land is unknown.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u201CEgypt\u2019s allies will
        fall, and the pride of Egypt\u2019s might will crumble. They will fall by
        the sword from Migdol in the north to Syene in the south. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken."
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CThey will be the most desolate in the midst of wasted countries,
        and their cities the most ruined among ruined cities. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: Then they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> when I
        set fire to Egypt and shatter all who support her.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CAt that time, I will dispatch messengers by river ships [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to terrify the unsuspecting Ethiopians. They will panic on the day of Egypt\u2019s
        doom. Judgment is sure to come! "
      comments:
      - number: 30:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cswift messengers\u201D (LXX).    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: I will use the armies of
        Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon to destroy the huge population [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Egypt. '
      comments:
      - number: 30:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cwealth,\u201D which includes Egypt\u2019s people. See
          v.  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I will bring him and his savage armies to ravage the country. They
        will wage war against Egypt and fill the country with corpses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "I will dry up the waterways of the Nile and hand over the country
        to evil men. I will cause the land to be destroyed and everything in it,
        at the hand of foreigners. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CI will demolish the
        idols and destroy the false gods from Noph. [[COMMENT(0)]] Egypt will be
        left without a ruler and a plague of fear will sweep over Egypt. "
      comments:
      - number: 30:13
        content: "  Or \u201CMemphis,\u201D once a very important governmental center
          of Egypt, located about thirteen miles (twenty kilometers) from the southern
          point of the Nile delta. When judging a nation, God begins with destroying
          their false gods.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I will make southern Egypt deserted, burn Zoan [[COMMENT(0)]] to
        the ground, and punish Thebes.   '
      comments:
      - number: 30:14
        content: "  Zoan was a city on one of the eastern branches of the Nile delta,
          not far from the mouth of the river. It is also known by its Greek name,
          Tanis. See  .      Or \u201CNo\u201D or \u201CNo-Amon,\u201D after the
          god Amon. Thebes was a magnificent city and the second most important city
          in Egypt after Memphis. It was the religious capital of Egypt, where many
          Egyptian kings built magnificent temples. See  .    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'I will pour out my fury on Pelusium, [[COMMENT(0)]] the stronghold
        of Egypt. I will wipe out the great population of Thebes. '
      comments:
      - number: 30:15
        content: "  Or \u201CSin,\u201D a strategic city on the border of Egypt and
          the Philistine lands.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'I will set Egypt on fire! Pelusium will be seized with great agony!
        The walls of Thebes will be torn down, and Noph will face distress daily
        from her enemies. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 30:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cface her enemies by day.\u201D The meaning of the last
          clause in the Hebrew is uncertain. The Septuagint reads \u201CMemphis will
          be flooded.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'And the cities of Heliopolis and Bubastis [[COMMENT(0)]] will go
        into captivity and their young soldiers will fall by the sword. '
      comments:
      - number: 30:17
        content: "  Or \u201COn and Pi-Beseth,\u201D two cities located on the eastern
          branch of the Nile delta. Both cities were important religious sites in
          Egypt.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "At Tahpanhes, [[COMMENT(0)]] I will turn day to darkness when I shatter
        Egypt\u2019s strength  and silence the boast of her might. I will blanket
        Egypt with dark clouds, and her people  will go into captivity. "
      comments:
      - number: 30:18
        content: "  Tahpanhes was a fortress city in the eastern Nile delta.     
          As translated from the Targum. The Hebrew is \u201C[yoke] bars.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cdaughters\u201D or \u201Cvillages.\u201D The term    is a homonym
          that may denote both meanings.    "
    - name: '19: God Will Defeat Egypt'
      title: God Will Defeat Egypt
      number: 19
      content: "That is how I will punish Egypt, and then they will acknowledge that
        I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'In the eleventh year of our captivity, on the seventh day of the
        first month, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying: '
      comments:
      - number: 30:20
        content: "  This date was probably April 29, 587 BC, almost four months after
          Ezekiel\u2019s prophecy against Egypt in  .  "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CSon of man, I have broken the powerful arm of Pharaoh king
        of Egypt. Behold, you can see that no one has set the bone to make it heal.
        No one has wrapped it to help it heal and get strong enough to hold a sword
        again. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u2018Behold,
        I am against you, Pharaoh king of Egypt; I will break both his arms, the
        strong one and the broken one, and I will make him drop the sword from his
        hand. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'I will scatter the Egyptians to the wind and disperse them among
        the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon and put my sword
        in his hand. I will break Pharaoh\u2019s arms, and he will moan in pain like
        a dying man before the Babylonian king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon, but I will make
        the arms of Pharaoh hang limp. And they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        when I put my sword into the hands of the king of Babylon and he wields it
        against Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations and disperse them
        among foreign lands. And then the people of Egypt will acknowledge that I
        am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Parable of the Cedar Tree'
      title: Parable of the Cedar Tree
      number: 1
      content: In the eleventh year of our captivity, on the first day of the third
        month, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying,
      comments:
      - number: 31:1
        content: '  Probably June 21, 587 BC.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, say to Pharaoh king of Egypt and his multitude:\u2018Who
        is comparable to you in your greatness?"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'I know who: Assyria! Once it was like a cedar tree in Lebanon,with
        its noble branches, its forest shade, and its lofty height,its treetop among
        the clouds.'
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Plenty of water has made it grow,deep springs have made it tall.Streams
        flow all around where it was planted,sending rivulets to all the other trees.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: So it towered high, much higher than the other trees of the forest.Because
        of the plentiful waters making it grow,its branches increased in number and
        spread out very far.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'All the birds of heaven nested in its strong branches,and wild animals
        gave birth under its shade. [[COMMENT(0)]]Many, many people sat in its shadow. '
      comments:
      - number: 31:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cboughs.\u201D      That is, great nations lived under
          its protection. This parable is a warning to Pharaoh from the fate of the
          Assyrian Empire. Assyria, like Pharaoh, had exalted herself in pride above
          the nations. Having ruled supreme for four centuries, Assyria was overthrown
          by the united forces of the Babylonians and the Medes in 605 BC.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: It was beautiful in its greatness, tall, with such large branches!For
        its roots were planted in plentiful waters.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The mighty cedar tree was unrivaled in God\u2019s garden.No cypress
        compares to such lovely branches as these;No sycamore [[COMMENT(0)]] could
        match its splendor.No tree in the garden of God could match its beauty."
      comments:
      - number: 31:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cplane tree.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: God Pronounces Judgment on the Cedar Tree'
      title: God Pronounces Judgment on the Cedar Tree
      number: 9
      content: "I made it so lovely with its many branches.It was the envy of every
        tree in Eden, the garden of God.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CBecause
        it towered so high with its top into the clouds and its heart was proud about
        its height, "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I have rejected it! I have handed it over to the mightiest of the
        nations [[COMMENT(0)]] to be punished as its wickedness deserves. '
      comments:
      - number: 31:11
        content: "  Or literally \u201Ca ram of the nations,\u201D a metaphor for
          Nebuchadnezzar, the powerful king of Babylon.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The most ruthless of nations cut down the cedar and left it deserted.
        Its broken branches littered the mountains, the valleys, and every ravine
        throughout the country. Those who once sat in its shadow have fled and abandoned
        it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: All the birds of heaven settled in the fallen tree, and all the wild
        animals lay among its branches.
      comments: []
    - name: "14: The Nations Quake over the Cedar\u2019s Destruction"
      title: "The Nations Quake over the Cedar\u2019s Destruction"
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CSo from now on, let no tree, no matter how well-watered, grow
        that high again with its top pushing into the clouds. And let no watered
        tree grow that tall again. For all of them are doomed to death, and they
        will join those in the depths of the underworld of mortals with those who
        go down to the pit.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CThe day I cast it
        down to Sheol, [[COMMENT(0)]] I caused it to mourn, covering it with the
        deep springs.  For I stopped its underground rivers, and I reduced the flow
        of the once plentiful waters. I clothed Lebanon with gloom as they mourned
        for the cedar tree, and all the trees withered because of it. "
      comments:
      - number: 31:15
        content: "    is a Hebrew word for the underworld, the realm of the dead.
          The word    is derived from a root word that means \u201Cto ask a question.\u201D
          We all have questions about the afterlife, don\u2019t we?      The meaning
          of the Hebrew of this sentence is uncertain.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'I made the nations quake at the crashing sound of its fall. They
        trembled as I hurled it down to Sheol with those who sink into the pit. In
        the depths of the underworld, all the trees of Eden, the finest well-watered
        trees of Lebanon, were comforted when the cedar tree joined them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: And the nations who sat in its shadow went down to Sheol with it to
        join those slaughtered by the sword. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 31:17
        content: '  This parable of the cedar tree is about Pharaoh, and the other
          trees are the other kings ruling in their earthly paradise. These other
          kings (trees), having gone down to the underworld, will find pleasure when
          Pharaoh joins them among the dead.  '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CWhich of Eden\u2019s trees could be compared to you in glory
        and greatness? Yet you have been hurled down with the trees of Eden to the
        depths of the underworld. You will lie among the uncircumcised and with those
        who have been slaughtered by the sword. So much for Pharaoh and all his multitudes!
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Parable of the Sea Monster'
      title: Parable of the Sea Monster
      number: 1
      content: 'In the twelfth year of our captivity, on the first day of the twelfth
        month, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 32:1
        content: "  This was probably March 3, 585 BC; however, there are some Hebrew
          manuscripts and ancient translations that read \u201Cin the eleventh year.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give a solemn warning [[COMMENT(0)]] to Pharaoh
        king of Egypt. Say to him:\u201C&nbsp;\u2018You are like a young lion prowling
        among the nations,or like a sea monster lurking in your lagoons! You churn
        up the water with your tramplingand muddy their streams."
      comments:
      - number: 32:2
        content: "  Or \u201Ca lamentation\u201D or \u201Ca doom-song\u201D without
          pity.      See    and footnote.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you:I will throw my net
        over you using a large group of nations.They will drag you to shore in my
        net,and I will leave you high and dry.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: I will fling you onto the open field and abandon you on the ground.I
        will gather all the birds of the air to feast on your flesh,and all the beasts
        of the earth will gorge themselves on you.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: I will scatter bits and pieces of your flesh on the hillsand fill
        the valleys with your rotting corpse.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: I will drench the land with your oozing blooduntil it fills the ravinesand
        spreads to the base of the mountains.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: When I snuff you out, I will hide the skiesand darken the stars.I
        will cover the sun with cloudsand turn off the moonlight.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Heaven\u2019s bright lights above you I will darkenand shroud your
        land in darkness.I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will trouble the hearts of many peoples when
        I spread the news of your destruction to nations and lands unknown to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: What I do to you will stun many nations. When I brandish my sword
        before them all, their kings will shudder with horror at your fate. On the
        day they see you fall, each will tremble in terror, fearing your fate might
        become theirs!
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018For Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to
        Egypt: The king of Babylon is coming to attack you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I will cause your great army to fall by the swords of mighty warriors.
        They are the most barbaric of nations. They will slice the pride of Egypt
        into pieces, and all your people will be destroyed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'I will also slaughter your livestock grazing beside the plentiful
        waters. No person or animal will muddy the water in the watering places with
        their feet and hooves. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Then I will settle their waters and make their rivers flow as smoothly
        as oil. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018When I reduce Egypt to a desolate wasteland and
        strip the land of all it contains, when I annihilate all who live there,
        then they will acknowledge that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>."
      comments: []
    - name: '16: Another Funeral Song for Egypt'
      title: Another Funeral Song for Egypt
      number: 16
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018This is the funeral song that people will sing
        in mourning for Egypt. Women of other nations will sing in lament for it.
        They will utter a lamentation for the land of Egypt and all its many people.
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, decree it!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'In the twelfth year of our captivity, on the fifteenth day of the
        twelfth month, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me,
        saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 32:17
        content: "  The words \u201Cthe twelfth month\u201D are missing from the
          Hebrew text. One ancient translation and the Greek Septuagint read \u201Cthe
          first month,\u201D but that is unlikely since that would mean this prophecy
          came before the previous one (see v.  ).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CSon of man, weep and mourn for the vast population of Egypt,
        and for the other mighty nations. For I will send them down to the world
        below with all who sink into the pit. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 32:18
        content: "  Or \u201CSon of man, weep and mourn for the people of Egypt and
          send them, her and the daughter of majestic nations, to the underworld.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CTell them, \u2018Egypt, are you more favored than the other
        nations? Down with you! Go down and make your bed with the uncircumcised
        dead, "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'with those who have been slaughtered by the sword! I will hand you
        and all your people over to the sword, and they will drag you away. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "From the depths of Sheol, [[COMMENT(0)]] the mightiest heroes,  your
        allies, will shout to you, \u201CNow they have come down. They have joined
        us among the uncircumcised dead, slaughtered by the sword.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 32:21
        content: "  That is, the underworld. See    and first footnote.      Or \u201Cthe
          rams, the mighty ones,\u201D a likely figure of speech for the kings of
          powerful nations who are welcoming Pharaoh to the underworld.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Assyria is there with all her hordes, with the
        graves of her soldiers all around her. They fell on the battlefield, slaughtered
        by the sword. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: They made their graves in the deepest part of the pit. Her hordes
        surround her grave; they were all slaughtered! Those who once spread their
        terror throughout the world of the living now lie silent, slaughtered by
        the sword.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Elam [[COMMENT(0)]] is there, along with the graves
        of all her hordes. They were slaughtered\u2014fallen by the sword. Those
        who once spread their terror throughout the land of the living have now joined
        the uncircumcised dead in the depths of the underworld. They have been disgraced
        and ashamed with those who sink into the pit. "
      comments:
      - number: 32:24
        content: '  Elam existed as a nation as early as 3000 BC. The territory the
          Elamites occupied was east of the Tigris River and is now part of Iran.
          The capital city was Susa, which is where the story of Esther took place.
          The nation was destroyed in 640 BC when the Assyrians captured Susa, which
          ended the Elamite kingdom. See  .    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: They have made a grave for her among her slaughtered multitudes, surrounded
        by all their tombs, all of them uncircumcised, slaughtered by the sword for
        having spread terror throughout the land of the living. They have carried
        their shame with them, with all those who sink into the pit. They have been
        placed among the slaughtered.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Meshech and Tubal [[COMMENT(0)]] are in the graveyard
        with their hordes all around their graves. They are all the uncircumcised
        dead, slaughtered by the sword for having spread their terror throughout
        the land of the living. "
      comments:
      - number: 32:26
        content: '  See    and footnotes.    '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'They were not buried with the great warriors of ancient times. When
        the mighty warriors died, they went into Sheol wearing all their armor. When
        people buried them, they placed their swords under their heads and their
        shields [[COMMENT(0)]] on top of their bodies because these valiant heroes
        once terrorized the land of the living. '
      comments:
      - number: 32:27
        content: "  The Hebrew (Masoretic) text has  , meaning \u201Ctheir iniquities,\u201D
          which makes little or no sense in this context. There is a proposed conjectural
          emendation:  , meaning \u201Ctheir shields,\u201D which makes much better
          sense in that an item of military armor is expected to follow the mention
          of \u201Ctheir swords under their heads.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: And you, Pharaoh, will be broken and lie among the uncircumcised,
        with those slaughtered by the sword.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Edom is there, her kings and all her rulers, who,
        despite their might, have been buried with those slaughtered by the sword.
        They lie with the uncircumcised, with those who sink into the pit."
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018All the princes of the north [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        all the Sidonians are there. They have gone down in disgrace with the slaughtered
        because their powerful armies once terrified their enemies. They lie among
        the uncircumcised dead, those slaughtered by the sword who bear their shame
        with those who sink into the pit."
      comments:
      - number: 32:30
        content: "  The \u201Cprinces [rulers] of the north\u201D likely refers to
          the leaders of the Phoenician city-states to the north of Israel.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018When Pharaoh and all his army see them, it will
        bring him some consolation at the sight of all his hordes killed by the sword.
        I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, decree it! "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Although I made him spread terror throughout the land of the living,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] he and all his hordes will be buried with the uncircumcised
        dead who were slaughtered by the sword. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 32:32
        content: '  The Hebrew text makes God, not Pharaoh, the ultimate cause of
          the terror.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: God Appoints Ezekiel as a Watchman'
      title: God Appoints Ezekiel as a Watchman
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying,   '
      comments:
      - number: 33:1
        content: "    constitutes panel I  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          It deals with the theme of Ezekiel as a \u201Cwatchman\u201D for the house
          of Israel. This chapter serves as a contrasting parallel with ch.  \u2014the
          \u201Ccooking pot\u201D judgment on Jerusalem (i.e., panel I).      Starting
          with this chapter and for the rest of the book, Ezekiel gives prophecies
          that look forward to the restoration of Israel. Although ch.    repeats
          some of the themes of judgment, it remains a pivotal chapter in the book.
          While Jerusalem was still standing, Ezekiel\u2019s message was mostly negative
          and corrective, for the people felt like they were safe as long as the
          temple stood in Jerusalem. But after Jerusalem\u2019s fall and the people\u2019s
          hopes were shattered, Ezekiel began to encourage them and prophesy hope
          for the future. Sinful people and sinful nations must lose their false
          hopes before they (we) are ready to hear the true way of trusting God alone
          for our future.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give your people this message: \u2018If I bring
        war to your nation, [[COMMENT(0)]] you must select a man and post him as
        a watchman. "
      comments:
      - number: 33:2
        content: "  Or \u201CIf I bring a sword against the land.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When he sees the enemy coming to attack, he must sound his shofar
        to warn the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'If people hear the warning but pay no attention and the sword overtakes
        them and kills them, they will bear the responsibility for their own deaths.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 33:4
        content: "  Or \u201Chis blood will be upon his own head.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Because they heard the sound of the shofar and paid no attention to
        the warning, their deaths are their own faults. But if they had listened
        to the warning, they could have saved their lives.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018If, however, the watchman sees the enemy approaching
        but has not blown his shofar to warn the people and the sword overtakes them
        and kills a single one of them, even though that person was a sinner, I will
        still hold the watchman responsible for that person\u2019s death.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 33:6
        content: "  Or \u201CI will require his [the dead person\u2019s] blood at
          the watchman\u2019s hand.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CSon of man, I have appointed you as watchman for the people
        of Israel. When you hear me speak a warning, give them my warning. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "If I say to the wicked, \u2018Evildoers, you are about to die,\u2019
        and you fail to warn them to renounce their evil ways, they will die for
        their guilt, but I will hold you responsible for their deaths. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: Individual Responsibility'
      title: Individual Responsibility
      number: 9
      content: "But if you warn the wicked to change their evil behavior and they
        refuse to change, the wicked will die for their sins, but you will have saved
        your own life.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSon of man, say to the people of Israel, \u2018You continually
        say: Our rebellious acts and our sins have caught up with us, and we are
        wasting away because of them. How then can we live?\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CSay to them, \u2018As surely as I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        exist\u2014I take no delight in the death of the wicked, but I delight in
        seeing them turn from their ways so they can live. So, repent and turn from
        your evil ways. People of Israel, why would you want to die? Turn and come
        back to me!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CSon of man, say to your people, \u2018All the good things a
        good person has done will not be any help if that one decides to turn to
        sin. And all the sins of an evil person will not destroy him if the evildoer
        decides to repent and turn from sin. If the righteous turns to sin, the righteous
        person will not be able to live because of past righteous deeds.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Suppose I say to a righteous person: \u2018You will certainly live,\u2019
        but then he becomes confident in his righteousness and turns away and willfully
        sins; none of the good things he has done in the past will be remembered.
        He will die in his sins. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "If, however, I say to a wicked person: \u2018You will certainly die,\u2019
        but then the wicked turns away from sin and does what is just and right "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "by returning what has been stolen and returning the borrower\u2019s
        pledge and by following the laws that give life and no longer doing wrong,
        that person will live and will not die. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "None of his previous sins will be counted against him, for he has
        done what is just and right\u2014therefore, he will certainly live."
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CYet your people say: \u2018The ways of the Lord are not right.\u2019
        But it is their ways that are not right! "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'When an upright person turns away from what is right and does what
        is evil, that person will die for it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'And when a wicked person turns from being wicked and does what is
        just and right, that person will live. '
      comments: []
    - name: "20: God Restores Ezekiel\u2019s Speech"
      title: "God Restores Ezekiel\u2019s Speech"
      number: 20
      content: "Yet you say: \u2018The ways of the Lord are not right.\u2019 Listen,
        people of Israel, I will judge each of you according to your ways.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "In the eleventh year [[COMMENT(0)]] of our captivity, on the fifth
        day of the tenth month, one who escaped from Jerusalem arrived and informed
        me: \u201CThe city has been taken.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 33:21
        content: "  As translated from a few Hebrew and Greek manuscripts and some
          ancient translations. Although most Hebrew manuscripts read \u201Cthe twelfth
          year,\u201D Jerusalem was captured in the fourth month of the eleventh
          year of Zedekiah. See  ;    and footnote.    "
    - name: '22: The Sins of the People'
      title: The Sins of the People
      number: 22
      content: "Now the evening before the survivor arrived, the mighty hand of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        had rested on me, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u201D resting on him. This indicates
        that</smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and my speech was fully restored
        before he came to me in the morning\u2014I could speak again. "
      comments:
      - number: 33:22
        content: "  Ezekiel was possibly in a trance-like state due to the \u201Cmighty
          hand of    took control over Ezekiel\u2019s body and spirit.      See 
          ;  .    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the people who are living in the ruins in the land
        of Israel are saying, \u2018Abraham was only one man when he took possession
        of the land, but we are many. Certainly, we can possess this land and rebuild.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CNow give the people this message, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Do you really think you can take ownership of the land? You
        are evildoers! You murder others, you eat meat with blood, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and you worship your foul idols. "
      comments:
      - number: 33:25
        content: "  Literally \u201Cyou eat on blood.\u201D See  ;  . Some scholars
          amend this to read \u201Cyou eat on the mountains,\u201D referring to meat
          sacrificed to false gods on pagan altars on the high places of the land.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "You rely on your swords, you engage in despicable pagan practices,
        and you are all adulterers. Do you really think I will give the ownership
        of the land to you?\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CTell them that I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, solemnly
        warn them: As surely as I exist, those living in the ruined towns will fall
        by the sword, those in the countryside I will give to the wild animals for
        them to eat, and those among the crags and in caves will die from disease. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "I will turn the land into a total wasteland, and I will put an end
        to their arrogant power. Israel\u2019s mountains will be so deserted that
        no one will pass that way again. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: The People Do Not Respond'
      title: The People Do Not Respond
      number: 29
      content: "Then they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, when
        I turn the land into a barren desert because of all the filthy things they
        have done.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CAs for you, son of man, your fellow citizens are talking about
        you beside the walls and in the doorways of their homes. They keep saying
        to one another, \u2018Let\u2019s go hear what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has to say.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'They all flock to you [[COMMENT(0)]] to sit at your feet as my people.
        They listen to your words, but they will not act on them. Instead, they express
        genuine devotion to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, but their hearts are set
        on cheating others. '
      comments:
      - number: 33:31
        content: "  Literally \u201CThey come to you like the coming of people.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'As far as they are concerned, you are like an entertainer who sings
        a love song [[COMMENT(0)]] with a beautiful voice to a good musical accompaniment.
        They hear what you say, but no one will do it. '
      comments:
      - number: 33:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cyou [Ezekiel] are like an erotic song.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "When all your prophecies come true [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014and they are
        beginning to be fulfilled now\u2014they will know that there has been a true
        prophet among them.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 33:33
        content: "  Or \u201CWhen all this comes true.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Rulers of Israel'
      title: The Rulers of Israel
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to me, saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 34:1
        content: "    constitutes panel H  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          It deals with the metaphorical theme of shepherds and sheep, with two distinct
          applications. The first of these focuses on the corrupt and godless leaders
          of Israel\u2014the heartless and cruel \u201Cshepherds of Israel\u201D
          who brutalize their \u201Cflock\u201D (vv.  ). The second application of
          the metaphor focuses on  as the quintessential \u201Cgood shepherd,\u201D
          who nurtures and lovingly cares for his people, his \u201Cflock\u201D (vv. 
          ).  will also provide a legacy of godly leaders for the future, via the
          spiritual descendants of King David. This metaphor is taken up by Jesus
          in  , where he declared himself the ultimate \u201CGood Shepherd\u201D
          (), caring for all those followers God, his Father, gives him. This chapter
          serves as a contrasting parallel with    (panel H), a metaphorical allegory
          of the two adulterous sisters, identifying them with the godless and immoral
          kingdoms of Israel and Judah.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy against the leaders [[COMMENT(0)]] of
        Israel; prophesy and say to them, \u2018Listen, you leaders, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has a message for you: Disaster is in store for the shepherds of Israel whose
        only concern is to feed themselves. Aren\u2019t shepherds supposed to feed
        the sheep? "
      comments:
      - number: 34:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cshepherds.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Yet you eat the fat, [[COMMENT(0)]] you shear the sheep to make your
        clothes, you slaughter the fattest sheep for your feasts, but you never feed
        the flock. '
      comments:
      - number: 34:3
        content: "  The fat of a sacrifice, according to the law of Moses, was reserved
          for God (see  ;  ). Some translators change the vocalization of the Hebrew
          to read \u201Cyou eat [drink] the milk.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "You haven\u2019t cared for the weak ones, brought healing to the
        sick, nor bandaged those who are injured. [[COMMENT(0)]] You haven\u2019t
        looked for the strays nor brought the lost back to the fold. Instead, you
        have ruled over them cruelly and treated them harshly. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:4
        content: "  These \u201Csheep\u201D (v.  ) represent followers of God who
          are often found weak, wounded, and needing inner healing. True shepherds
          will care for them and bring them into wholeness. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Because there was no shepherd to care for the sheep, they were scattered
        and were eaten by every wild beast. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: My flock has wandered aimlessly over every hill and mountain over
        the face of the earth, and no one went to look for them or tried to find
        them. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 34:6
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>: "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "As surely as I live, declares Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2014my
        sheep have become the prey of every wild beast. Since there was no shepherd
        to protect my sheep, they have been devoured. My shepherds have not searched
        for my sheep; they have cared for themselves and not the flock. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: , the Good Shepherd'
      title: ', the Good Shepherd'
      number: 10
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: Behold, I am against you
        selfish shepherds! I will hold you accountable for my flock, and I will demand
        that you return my flock to me. [[COMMENT(0)]] No longer will you feed only
        yourselves because I will rescue my sheep from your mouths. You will help
        yourselves to my sheep no longer.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 34:10
        content: "  Or \u201CI will restrain you from tending the flock.\u201D     
          Or \u201CMy flock will no longer be a source of food for you!\u201D This
          prophecy (vv.  ) is an elaboration of Jeremiah\u2019s prophecy in  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CFor Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u2018From now
        on, I will personally search for my sheep and look after them. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 34:11
        content: "  Or \u201CI will inspect them carefully [to see if they are injured].\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'As a good shepherd searches after his scattered sheep, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        so I will look after my sheep and rescue them from wherever they have been
        scattered on the day of disaster.   '
      comments:
      - number: 34:12
        content: "  Or literally \u201CAs a shepherd looks after his flock on the
          day when he is in the middle of his sheep that have been scattered.\u201D     
          Or \u201Con the day of thick clouds and darkness,\u201D likely a metaphor
          for a time of disaster.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'I will bring them back from foreign countries and gather them together
        as my flock and return them to their own land. I will feed them on the mountains
        of Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, the Good Shepherd, will feed them there.</smallcaps>
        in the valley streams and in all the fertile places.   '
      comments:
      - number: 34:13
        content: "  The \u201Cmountains\u201D were where the bad shepherds failed
          to care for the flock.        Or \u201Cin all the inhabited places of the
          country,\u201D that is, the fertile regions where people could live off
          the land.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I will feed them in fair meadows and on the slopes of the mountains
        of Israel. There they will lie down in good grazing grounds and graze in
        green pastures on the mountains of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep, and I will give them rest.
        I will seek out the lost one, bring back the stray, bandage the injured,
        and heal those that are sick. I will watch over [[COMMENT(0)]] the fat and
        healthy of the flock. I will be a true, caring shepherd to them.  I, Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.
      comments:
      - number: "34:15\u201316"
        content: "  As translated from ancient versions, which make a minor change
          to the Hebrew. The Hebrew is \u201CI will destroy.\u201D      Or \u201CI
          will shepherd the flock with justice.\u201D    "
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep, and I will give them rest.
        I will seek out the lost one, bring back the stray, bandage the injured,
        and heal those that are sick. I will watch over [[COMMENT(0)]] the fat and
        healthy of the flock. I will be a true, caring shepherd to them.  I, Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.
      comments:
      - number: "34:15\u201316"
        content: "  As translated from ancient versions, which make a minor change
          to the Hebrew. The Hebrew is \u201CI will destroy.\u201D      Or \u201CI
          will shepherd the flock with justice.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018As for you, my sheep, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: I am the one who judges between one sheep and the other, between
        rams and billy goats. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Since you\u2019re not satisfied with feeding from the best pastures,
        you also trample down the rest of the grass. You\u2019re not satisfied to
        drink the clean water; must you also muddy up the rest of the water with
        your feet? "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Is it right that my sheep have to eat what you have walked all over?
        Is it right that they must drink muddy water because of your trampling feet? '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this: I am the
        one who judges between the strong sheep and the weak. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 34:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe fat sheep and the lean sheep.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Because you shove with your side and your shoulder and thrust your
        horns at all the weak sheep until you scatter them, therefore, '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: I will come and save my sheep and rescue them from being victimized.
        I will judge between one sheep and another.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will raise up one shepherd over them, like my
        servant David, [[COMMENT(0)]] and put him in charge of my flock to feed them.
        He will care for them and be their shepherd. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:23
        content: "  The reference to David cannot be literal since he died nearly
          four hundred years prior to Ezekiel\u2019s ministry in Babylon. However,
          the prophetic context of this section clearly indicates that the reference
          to David is typological. He is one of the greatest Messianic forerunners
          in the Old Testament of the Lord Jesus Christ\u2014the perfect embodiment
          of the Good Shepherd\u2014and he is undoubtedly anticipated by this profound
          metaphorical description (see v.  ).    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, will be their God, and my servant,
        like David, will be their prince taken from among them. [[COMMENT(0)]] I,
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken. '
      comments:
      - number: 34:24
        content: '  This is a prophecy of Jesus, the Son of David, who came as the
          Messiah and King of Israel.    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'I will make a covenant of peace with them and rid the land of its
        wild beasts. Then they will be able to live securely in the wilderness and
        sleep soundly in the forest. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "And I will make them [[COMMENT(0)]] and the places all around my
        sacred hill a blessing. And I will send showers of blessing \u2014showers
        will come down in their season. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:26
        content: "  In the context, \u201Cthem\u201D takes us back to vv.  . It is
          the \u201Cweak [persecuted]\u201D sheep that God will make a blessing.
          The strong sheep have exploited them, but God takes note of it all and
          promises to \u201Cbless\u201D the weak sheep. Then he will cause showers
          of blessings, which likely represent prosperity. This is associated with
          actual rains coming in their seasons to bring blessing to the land and
          the growth of abundant crops. This will come after the \u201Cweak\u201D
          suffer at the hands of the strong, powerful sheep with horns (authority),
          the ones who get rich by making others poor.      See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'And the tree of the field [[COMMENT(0)]] will yield its luscious
        fruit, the earth will yield its harvest, and they will live safely in their
        own land. When I set them free from slavery  and rescue them from the hands
        of those who enslaved them, then they will acknowledge that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: 34:27
        content: "  Jesus is that \u201Ctree of the field\u201D that stands above
          all others. See  ;  .      Or \u201CWhen I break the bars of their yoke.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Foreign powers will no longer plunder them; the wild beasts of the
        land will no longer feast on them. They will live safe and secure, with no
        one to frighten them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'I will establish for them a planting of renown [[COMMENT(0)]] so
        that they will no longer suffer from famine.  And they will no longer have
        to endure the insults of other nations. '
      comments:
      - number: 34:29
        content: "  Or \u201Ca famous planting.\u201D Jesus Christ is that \u201Cfamous
          planting\u201D or \u201Cplanting of renown\u201D that was planted into
          our hearts as the Seed of God ().      See  .    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "So they will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, am with
        them as their God. [[COMMENT(0)]] And they, the people of Israel, will know
        that they are my people\u2014declares the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:30
        content: '  Today, we know that God is with us at all times. See  .  '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "And you, my people, are my sheep, the flock of my pasture are people,
        and I am your God. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Judgment of Edom'
      title: Judgment of Edom
      number: 1
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s judgment against Israel.</smallcaps><smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to me, saying, "
      comments:
      - number: 35:1
        content: '    constitutes panel G  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          It deals with the theme of judgment against Edom for their attacks against
          Israel and for their rejoicing over the destruction of Jerusalem at the
          hands of the Babylonians. This chapter serves as a contrasting parallel
          with ch.    (panel G), an oracle identifying Babylon as the instrument
          of      '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, set your face toward Mount Seir [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and prophesy against it. "
      comments:
      - number: 35:2
        content: '  That is, the land of Edom.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Tell the people what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, say to
        them: \u2018Behold! I am against you, Mount Seir! I will punish you severely.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 35:3
        content: "  Or \u201CI will stretch out my hand against you.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I will level your cities and make your land an empty desert. There
        will be no one left in your land. And then you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'You have been an enemy of Israel for a very long time. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        You betrayed the Israelites and gave them over to be slaughtered at the time
        of their calamity, the crucial moment of their final punishment. '
      comments:
      - number: 35:5
        content: "  Edom\u2019s (Seir\u2019s) hatred of Israel dates back to Jacob
          stealing his brother Esau\u2019s birthright. The Edomites were descendants
          of Esau and viewed the Israelites as illegitimate usurpers who took over
          the land. The Edomites frequently sought revenge against Israel and hated
          the Israelites. Isaiah, Jeremiah, and Obadiah likewise denounced Edom.
          Symbolically, Edom represents the old nature of Adam that must be removed,
          crucified with Christ, before the glories of the new covenant can be manifested.
          See  ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Therefore, as surely as I live\u2014declares Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2014I
        will let you be murdered. Murder will chase you down. Because you did not
        despise bloodshed, bloodshed will hunt you down!"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will make Mount Seir a desolate waste, and I
        will kill anyone who travels through it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'I will cover its mountains with the corpses of those who die in war.
        Yes, the bodies of those killed in battle will lie scattered over all your
        hills, valleys, and ravines. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: Your entire land will lie in ruins; your towns will never be inhabited
        again. And then you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018You said: \u201CLet\u2019s take possession of these
        two countries, Judah and Israel. They are ours for the taking,\u201D even
        though the land belongs to me, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 35:10
        content: "  Or \u201Ceven though  was there!\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Therefore, as surely as I live\u2014declares the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2014I
        will treat you with the same anger and jealousy as you treated them in your
        hatred. I will show the Israelites who I really am when I punish you severely. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "And you will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have heard
        all the vile insults that you have uttered against the mountains of Israel,
        saying, \u201CLook! They have been ruined and left desolate. Let\u2019s wipe
        them out!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 35:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey are given us [as food] to devour.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "I\u2019ve heard all your boasting, arrogant words. Your many speeches
        that opposed me relentlessly, I have heard them all. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: I will destroy you and leave
        your land empty as everyone applauds your downfall. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Just as you rejoiced when the heritage of the land of Israel [[COMMENT(0)]]
        had been laid waste, so I will do to you, Mount Seir. You will become an
        empty desert, along with all the land of Edom. And then the Israelites will
        know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 35:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe house of Israel.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Restoration of Israel'
      title: Restoration of Israel
      number: 1
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s judgment against Israel, followed
        by the promise of new covenant blessing and restoration.</smallcaps>\u201CSon
        of man, prophesy to the mountains of Israel  and tell them, \u2018Mountains
        of Israel, hear the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: 36:1
        content: '    constitutes panel F  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          It deals with the themes of both judgment against Israel and the promise
          of new covenant blessing. This chapter serves as a direct parallel with
          ch.    (panel F), which also deals with        A theme of    is the restoration
          of the land of Israel. The sins of the people had so polluted the land
          (see chs.  ) that it had to be cleansed before God could bring the people
          back to the land.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: Your enemies have
        gloated over you by saying: \u201CAt last! Now we own these ancient high
        places!\u201D&nbsp;\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CSo prophesy to them what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have to say: \u2018Your enemies have attacked you from all directions and
        turned your land into an empty ruin. This enabled other nations to take possession
        of your land. You also became the subject of people\u2019s malicious talk
        and evil slander. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Therefore, hear the word of Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, you
        Mountains of Israel! Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has a message for
        the mountains and hills, the ravines and valleys, the devastated ruins and
        abandoned cities that have been ransacked by your enemies and ridiculed by
        all the nations around you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: Truly,
        I speak in my jealous anger against the rest of the nations and to the entire
        land of Edom. You gleefully and maliciously took possession of my land so
        that you could plunder its fertile pasturelands.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CTherefore Ezekiel, prophesy over the land of Israel, its mountains
        and hills, its ravines and valleys. Prophesy to them what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have to say: \u2018Behold, I speak in my fiery passion because you have endured
        the vile insults of the nations. "
      comments: []
    - name: "7: God\u2019s Heart for Israel"
      title: "God\u2019s Heart for Israel"
      number: 7
      content: "Therefore, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: I raise my hand
        and solemnly swear that the nations all around you will have their own insults
        to bear!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Mountains of Israel, your trees will once again
        grow branches and bear fruit for my people the Israelites. For they will
        soon return home. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Yes, I am for you and on your side; I will turn my heart toward you.
        Farmers will plow your ground and plant their seeds. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Israel, I will make the population of all your tribes to increase,
        yes, throughout the land. Your ruined cities will be rebuilt and people will
        live in them again. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I will increase your population, both human and animal, and they
        will increase and prosper. I will bring people to settle on you as in the
        past, and I will bless you more than ever before. [[COMMENT(0)]] And then
        you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:11
        content: "  Or \u201CI will do more good to you than ever before.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: O&nbsp;land of Israel, I will again settle my people on you. They
        will possess you as their inheritance, and never again will you deprive them
        of their children.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018This is what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say: People say about you, \u201CYou devour people and have robbed your nation
        of its children.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'But you will devour people no longer nor make your nation childless
        again, [[COMMENT(0)]] says Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:14
        content: "  Or \u201Ccause your people [nation] to stumble.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: Restoring the People'
      title: Restoring the People
      number: 15
      content: "I will silence the insults of the nations. You will never again have
        to hear the mocking of the peoples, and you will never again cause your nation
        to stumble. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me this message: '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the Israelites defiled their own land when they
        lived there. In my eyes, their conduct was as unclean as a woman\u2019s menstruation. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'So I vented my fury on them because of the violence and murders they
        had committed in the land and because of their worship of idols, which defiled
        the land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I dispersed them among the nations, and they were scattered throughout
        different countries. I judged them as their actions and conduct deserved. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When my people were scattered to other lands, they dishonored my
        holy name in front of those nations. The people said of them, \u2018Look!
        These are the people of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> who have been forced
        out of his land.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'But I have been greatly concerned about my holy name, which the people
        of Israel have dishonored among the nations where they have gone. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Therefore, say to the people of Israel what I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say: \u2018I will not take action for your sake, people of Israel, but for
        the sake of the honor of my holy name, which you have caused to be slandered
        among the nations wherever you have gone. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: A New Heart for a New Day'
      title: A New Heart for a New Day
      number: 23
      content: "I am going to magnify the holiness of my great name, which you have
        greatly dishonored before the eyes of foreign nations. And when I magnify
        my holiness in you before their eyes, the nations will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will take you from every nation and country and
        bring you back home to your own land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'I will sprinkle purifying water over you, and you will be cleansed
        [[COMMENT(0)]] from all the filth of your past. I will wash you clean from
        the defilement of worshiping false gods. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:25
        content: '  See  ,  .    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'I will graciously give you a new, tender heart and put a new, willing
        spirit [[COMMENT(0)]] inside you. I will remove your hard heart of stone
        and give you an obedient, responsive heart instead. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:26
        content: "  This is more than a \u201Cgood attitude.\u201D God promises to
          give us a new spirit, his own Spirit, placed within us so we can take part
          in God\u2019s gracious new covenant. See v.  . See also  ;  .    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'I will put my Holy Spirit in you to empower you to keep my laws and
        to live by them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'You will live in the land that I gave your ancestors. You will be
        my people, and I will be your God. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 36:28
        content: '  Verses    describe the new covenant the Lord Jesus has established
          with us. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'I will save you from everything impure within you. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I will call for the grain of the field to become plentiful and not allow
        famine to afflict you. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:29
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'I will increase the produce of fruit and field so that you will never
        again bear the disgrace of famine among the nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Then you will remember your evil ways and the wrongs you have done.
        Your guilt and evil deeds will cause you to be disgusted with yourselves. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "People of Israel, I assure you that it is not because you are good
        [[COMMENT(0)]] that I am going to do all this. You should be utterly ashamed
        over your conduct! I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 36:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cfor your [goodness] sake.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u2018When I cleanse
        you from all your guilt and shame, I will cause your ruined cities to be
        rebuilt and repopulated again. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'You will once more farm your barren land. It will not be abandoned
        anymore, and everyone who passes by will notice it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "And they will say: \u201CLook how this once barren land is now like
        the garden of Eden! All those empty, abandoned cities left in ruins are now
        strongholds, restored cities with people living in them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "And the nations around you will know that I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have rebuilt the ruined places and replanted what was once desolate. I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        make this promise and will do it.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "\u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u2018People of Israel,
        as a sign of my favor, I will once again answer your prayers. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I will cause your population to increase until you are like a large flock
        of sheep. "
      comments:
      - number: 36:37
        content: "  Or \u201CI will once more allow myself to be approached by you
          in prayer, house of Israel, to do this for you.\u201D    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "You will be as numerous as the huge flock of sacrificial animals
        [[COMMENT(0)]] in Jerusalem during her solemn feasts. Your cities that were
        once filled with rubble will be filled with flocks of people. And then you
        will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D <smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 36:38
        content: "  Or \u201Cflock of holy things [animals].\u201D God is giving
          Ezekiel the image of the vast numbers of returning exiles becoming as numerous
          as the large flocks of sheep brought into Jerusalem for the feast days.
          During the solemn feast days, as many as 37,600 sheep and goats were sacrificed,
          as well as 3,800 bulls (see  ).      This sentence (and variations) is
          repeated over sixty times in Ezekiel: \u201CAnd they [you] will know that
          I am    "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Valley of Dry Bones'
      title: The Valley of Dry Bones
      number: 1
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s powerful presence
        was upon me, <smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and his Spirit lifted me up and carried
        me away. He set me down in the middle of a valley <smallcaps>. It was the
        Valley of Vision. See</smallcaps> floor that was covered with countless bones.   "
      comments:
      - number: 37:1
        content: "    constitutes panel E  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          It deals with the allegorical vision of a valley of dry bones, with the
          theme of new life and the promise of covenant renewal. This chapter serves
          as a contrasting parallel with chs.    (panel E), which deal with the covenant
          curse against Israel and the divine exhortation to new life and heart renewal.     
          Or \u201Cthe [mighty] hand of  was upon me.\u201D      See  ;  . This was
          the valley where Ezekiel saw the glory of    .      This section of the
          book of Ezekiel focuses on the restoration of Israel. The valley of dry
          bones was likely an ecstatic vision that showed the prophet the utter devastation
          of Israel. The nation was lifeless, dead as dry bones. Nevertheless, God\u2019s
          promise is that he will revive his people and bring them back to life.
          The Hebrew word  , meaning \u201Cbones,\u201D is derived from the verb 
          , a word that means \u201Cto be strong, mighty, and great.\u201D So,   
          are something that can be made strong again with God\u2019s breath. Your
          dry bones speak of hope, not defeat. The \u201Cskeletons in your closet\u201D
          that bring you shame God sees as the beginning of a new life that he will
          build within you.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: He made me walk all around the valley among all the vast piles of
        bones. There in the valley there were very many, very dry bones. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 37:2
        content: "  The \u201Cvery dry\u201D bones meant that the people had been
          dead for a long time.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> asked me, \u201CSon of man, can these
        bones come back to life again?\u201DAnd I replied, \u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        you are the only one who knows.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CProphesy over these dry bones these words,
        \u2018Dry bones, hear what <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I
        am now going to breathe into you,and you will live again!"
      comments:
      - number: 37:5
        content: '  Prophetic Scriptures often have multiple meanings and interpretations.
          The Talmud teaches that these scattered bones were the bones of the young
          Hebrew men that King Nebuchadnezzar had executed. Apparently, the Jewish
          young men taken into captivity were so handsome that the Babylonian women
          were falling head over heels for them. So, Nebuchadnezzar had them executed,
          their bodies mutilated, and their bones scattered. The Talmud also teaches
          that this was not only a vision but reality as well. God instructed Ezekiel
          to speak to these dry bones and they would come together and live again.
          Not only was this a prophetic sign, but, according to Talmudic literature,
          it actually took place as these now resurrected men went on to marry and
          live out a full life. See  .    '
    - name: '6: The Bones Come Together'
      title: The Bones Come Together
      number: 6
      content: "I will attach muscles and sinews to you.I will make flesh grow on
        you.I will cover you with skin.I am going to breathe into you,and you will
        live again.And you will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'So I prophesied as I had been told. And as I was prophesying, I began
        to hear a commotion. Behold! It was the clattering [[COMMENT(0)]] of these
        many skeletons coming together, bone to bone! '
      comments:
      - number: 37:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cearthquake.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: And as I kept watching, muscles and sinews miraculously appeared!
        Flesh grew on the bones, and then skin wrapped completely around them, yet
        there was still no life-breath [[COMMENT(0)]] in them.
      comments:
      - number: 37:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cspirit,\u201D \u201Cwind,\u201D or \u201Cbreath of life.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CProphesy to
        the breath. Yes, prophesy, son of man. Say to the breath, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says: Divine breath, come now from the four winds. Breathe on these lifeless
        bodies, so that they can live again.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So I prophesied as he had told me, and the breath entered their bodies.
        They came alive, [[COMMENT(0)]]  got up from the ground, and stood to their
        feet\u2014a very great, immense army."
      comments:
      - number: 37:10
        content: '  See  ;  ;  . The Valley of Death became the Valley of Life.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CSon of man, these bones represent the entire
        house of Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]] They keep saying, \u2018We are as dry as
        these dead bones. Our nation has been completely destroyed, and we have lost
        all hope.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 37:11
        content: "  Although the direct fulfillment of this prophecy involves the
          regathered nation of Israel, believers today can find in this prophecy
          a promise for us as well (see  ). We may be disjointed and unconnected
          in differing ministries, yet God\u2019s plan is to unite us under our Prince
          (see  ;  ). The dry bones will rise again as a mighty end-time army (see 
          ). Every joint will supply a resource for the body of Christ as we move
          into maturity. See  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CSo, prophesy to them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Behold! I am now going to open your graves! [[COMMENT(0)]] My
        people, I will resurrect you out of your graves and lead you home to the
        land of Israel. "
      comments:
      - number: 37:12
        content: '  Figuratively, the graves could represent the many nations in
          which the Jews had been exiled and kept from their own land.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'And when I open your graves and raise you up, then, my people, you
        will be convinced that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Two Become One'
      title: Two Become One
      number: 14
      content: "And I will put my Holy Spirit within you, and you will live again.
        I will resettle you on your own soil. Then you will know that it is I, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        who spoke to you, and I do what I say. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 37:15
        content: '  In this section of Ezekiel, God promises to reunite the Northern
          Kingdom of Israel with the Southern Kingdom of Israel, known as Judah.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CSon of man, take a stick and carve on it the words, \u2018For
        Judah and all the Israelites with him.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]] Then take another
        stick and carve on it the words, \u2018The stick of Ephraim,  for Joseph
        and all the Israelites with him.\u2019   "
      comments:
      - number: 37:16
        content: "  That is, the Benjamites, who were part of the Southern Kingdom
          of Judah.      That is, the northern tribes of Israel, also called \u201CJoseph,\u201D
          or the name of his son, \u201CEphraim.\u201D Ephraim was the most powerful
          of the northern tribes; Judah was the leader of the southern tribes.     
          This refers to the other nine tribes that, along with Ephraim, comprised
          the Northern Kingdom of Israel.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Now join them together to make a single piece of wood to become one
        stick in your hand. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "And when your fellow exiles ask, \u2018Won\u2019t you tell us what
        you mean by this?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "answer them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: Behold,
        I will take the stick of Joseph that belongs to Ephraim and those tribes
        loyal to him and join them to the stick of Judah. I will make two sticks
        into one, a single stick in my hand.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 37:19
        content: "  This is a hint of two offices coming together in the church\u2014the
          king and the priest. Caleb was from the tribe of Judah, and Joshua was
          from the tribe of Ephraim. Judah was the tribe that gave us the King, Jesus.
          Ephraim (  means \u201Cdoubly fruitful\u201D) reveals the fruitfulness
          of priestly ministry. Joseph was a \u201Cfruitful vine [branch]\u201D ().
          Furthermore, the two kingdoms becoming one also points to the church being
          made up of Jews and gentiles in unity\u2014a new humanity (see  ).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CNow, show the people the pieces of wood you have written on, "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "and tell them, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this:
        I will gather the Israelites from the nations where they have gone. I will
        gather them together from everywhere and bring them to their homeland. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'And I will make them into a single nation in the mountainous land
        of Israel [[COMMENT(0)]] and give them one king to be king over them all.
        They will never again be divided into two nations nor split into two separate
        kingdoms. '
      comments:
      - number: 37:22
        content: "  For over 350 years, from the end of Solomon\u2019s reign, Israel
          was divided into two kingdoms, two nations. Here God promises not only
          to raise them from their graves and resettle them in their land but also
          that the divisions between the Northern and Southern Kingdoms would be
          removed. When God brings back the exiles to the land, they will form one
          nation.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Never again will they defile themselves with their disgusting idols,
        their detestable things, and rebellions. I will save them from always turning
        back and repeating their old sins. [[COMMENT(0)]] I will cleanse and purify
        them. They will be my people, and I shall be their God.
      comments:
      - number: 37:23
        content: "  As translated from a few Hebrew manuscripts. The Masoretic Text
          reads \u201CI will save them from their dwelling [places] in which they
          have sinned.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018My beloved servant David [[COMMENT(0)]] will reign
        over them, and he will be one faithful shepherd for them all. They will walk
        in my ways, respect my laws, and practice them. "
      comments:
      - number: 37:24
        content: "  This cannot be understood literally, for David had died nearly
          four hundred years earlier. This is a prophecy of one like David, a Son
          of David, who would take the throne and rule over Israel and all the nations.
          It is clearly a Messianic prophecy of the coming of King Jesus to take
          David\u2019s throne. Jesus is the Prince of Peace (see v.  ).    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'They will live in the land that I gave to my servant Jacob, where
        your ancestors once lived. They and their children and grandchildren will
        live in it forever, and David my servant will be their prince forever. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'I will make my eternal covenant of peace with them. I will resettle
        them, and I will bless them  [[COMMENT(0)]] and multiply them. I will establish
        my sanctuary among them forever. '
      comments:
      - number: 37:26
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic Targum.    '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'I will make my home above them. I will be their God, and they will
        be my beloved people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "When my sanctuary is with them forever, then the nations will realize
        that I set Israel apart as my own.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 37:28
        content: "  Or \u201CI am the Sanctifier of Israel.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Attack by Gog'
      title: Attack by Gog
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to me, saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 38:1
        content: "    constitutes panel D  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          These chapters deal, first of all, with the allegorical judgment against
          Gog and Magog\u2014a symbolic judgment against all godless nations. And
          second, they also contain the promise of renewal and new covenant blessing
          for Israel. These chapters then serve as a parallel with chs.    (panel
          D\u2014specifically,  ), which deal with allegorical judgments against
          Israel and the foretelling of new covenant blessing. Chapters    constitute
          one prophecy against Gog. If interpreted literally, the chapters speak
          of the confederacy of nations around the Black and Caspian Seas, with Persia
          (Iran) and North Africa, who will invade Israel after her restoration to
          the land.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn toward Gog, [[COMMENT(0)]] of the land of
        Magog,  and prophesy against him. Yes, set your face against Gog, that supreme
        prince of the lands of Meshech and Tubal,  in the land of Magog. "
      comments:
      - number: 38:2
        content: "  We know little about Gog, the ruler of Magog. He is only mentioned
          here in the Old Testament (the Gog of    is a different person) and only
          once in the New Testament (see  ).    means \u201C[flat] mountain.\u201D
          Various theories have been proposed over the identity of Gog. Some identify
          him with Gyges, king of Lydia in Asia Minor from 690 to 657 BC. Others
          view Gog as a symbol for the Babylonian monarch, whose destruction was
          foretold. Still others presume him to be Alexander the Great. But Gog more
          likely represents every force of spiritual darkness that opposes God. The
          traditional view is that a confederation of nations including Russia and
          Iran and Turkey will invade Israel on horseback sometime during the \u201Ctribulation.\u201D
          See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . Gog would then be the leader of this coalition of invaders.
          Many forget that the text shows that it is God who brings Gog into the
          land to destroy him. There is little agreement among scholars that the
          Gog and Magog of    are the same Gog and Magog of    that come up against
          the camp of the saints. However, there is also another \u201Csupreme prince\u201D
          (), known as \u201Cthe dark ruler [prince] of the earthly realm who fills
          the atmosphere with his authority, and works diligently in the hearts of
          those who are disobedient to the truth of God\u201D ().        means \u201Cland
          of Gog.\u201D Magog is also the name of the son of Japheth and grandson
          of Noah. See  ;  .      Meshech and Tubal were countries in Asia Minor
          (see    and fourth and fifth footnotes there; second and third footnotes
          on  ).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Prophesy: \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you, Gog,
        supreme prince of Meshech and Tubal: Beware, I am against you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I will insert hooks in your jaws and turn you around. I will drag
        you and all your army out of your land\u2014all your horses and horsemen,
        all perfectly equipped, many warriors armed with shields large and small,
        and all carrying swords. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Allied armies from Persia, Cush, and Put are with them, all with
        shield and helmet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Gomer and all its troops, Beth Togarmah in the distant north and
        all its troops\u2014armies of many nations are part of your coalition. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Get ready, Gog! Be well prepared, you and all your armies and those
        assembled with you, and take command of them.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018A long time from now I will gather you together
        to fight. In the latter years, you will invade this country that has recovered
        from war. A land where the people had been brought together from other nations
        to live on the mountains of Israel. Although the land was deserted for a
        long time, I led its people out from other nations, and now they all live
        safe and secure. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "You and your vast armies and those allied with you will invade the
        land like a great storm and advance throughout the country and cover it like
        a cloud.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CThis is what Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to Gog:
        \u2018On that day, an idea will occur to you, and you will devise a sinister
        plan. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'You will say: I am going to attack this undefended country and march
        on the peaceful people who fear no danger. They are all living in unwalled
        towns without bars or gates. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I will attack those living among their once ruined cities. I will
        turn my might against these people gathered from the nations, who acquired
        livestock and goods, who live in the strategic center of the land. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I will plunder them and carry off the spoils. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe center [crossroads] of the world.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "The people of Sheba and Dedan, the merchants and all the tycoons
        [[COMMENT(0)]] of Tarshish will ask you: Have you come for plunder? Are you
        massing your troops to seize spoil? Have you come to carry off gold and silver,
        cattle and goods, and seize unlimited spoil?\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 38:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cyoung lions,\u201D likely a metaphor for wealthy merchant
          tycoons. The Hebrew word    may also yield the meanings \u201Cyoung warriors\u201D
          or even \u201Cvillages.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CTherefore, son of man, prophesy, and say to Gog, \u2018Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to you: Sometime in the future, when my
        people the Israelites are living safe and secure, will you not take notice
        of it? "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'You will leave your home country in the distant north, you and many
        nations with you, and with an enormous, mighty army of countless troops on
        horseback. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: God Will Punish Gog'
      title: God Will Punish Gog
      number: 16
      content: "You will invade Israel, my people, like a cloud covering the countryside.
        In the latter days, I will bring you against my land so that the nations
        will know who I am when, through you, Gog, I display my holiness to them.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "This is what Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says to Gog: \u201CAre
        you not the one I spoke about in days gone by through my servants the prophets
        of Israel? They prophesied for years of your invasion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'But I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, declare that on the day
        when you, Gog, attack the land of Israel, my furious wrath will boil over! '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'For in my passion [[COMMENT(0)]] for my people, in the heat of my
        anger, I have decreed that on that day, there will be a massive earthquake
        in the land of Israel! '
      comments:
      - number: 38:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cjealousy.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The fish in the sea and the birds of heaven, animals large and small,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and all people on earth will be terrified and tremble at my
        presence. Mountains will tumble, cliffs crumble, and all the walls will collapse. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cwild beasts and creeping things [reptiles].\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'I will bring the sword against you, Gog, in the mountains of Israel,
        declares Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. Your troops will turn their
        swords against one another. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'I will punish him [[COMMENT(0)]] and his hordes and his many allies
        with plague and bloodshed and pour down torrential rain, hailstones, fire,
        and brimstone. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:22
        content: "  Or \u201CI will enter into judgment against him.\u201D  "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "In this way I will display my greatness and holiness and make myself
        known before many nations. Then they will acknowledge that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Destruction of Gog'
      title: Destruction of Gog
      number: 1
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy against Gog. Prophesy this message that
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, give to you: \u2018Behold I am against
        you, Gog, the supreme prince of Meshech and Tubal. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'I will turn you around, drive you out, and bring you from the distant
        north to fight against the mountains of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'I will knock the bow from your left hand and rip the arrows out of
        your right. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'You will fall on the mountains of Israel, you and all your hordes
        and your coalition with you. I will feed your flesh to every kind of bird
        of prey and wild animal. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Your corpses will lie unburied in the open fields, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.
      comments:
      - number: 39:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cyou will [also] fall in the open fields.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I will send down fire on Magog and on those living
        securely on the coastlands, and they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: I will make sure that my holy name is acknowledged among my people
        Israel, and I will make sure that my holy name is no longer allowed to be
        profaned. Then the nations will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the Holy One of Israel.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Behold, these things I have prophesied will happen
        very soon. It will all be fulfilled, for this is the day I have spoken about.
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, declare it."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018Then those living in the towns of Israel will go
        out and gather up all the abandoned weapons of the dead soldiers, make a
        bonfire with them, and burn them all up\u2014the shields large and small,
        bows and arrows, javelins and spears. It will take seven [[COMMENT(0)]] years
        to burn them all. "
      comments:
      - number: 39:9
        content: "  The number seven is predominant in this chapter. It takes seven
          years to burn all the weapons and seven months to bury the dead (see v. 
          ). The root word for \u201Cbury\u201D is also found seven times in this
          chapter. To take seven years to burn the weapons can be seen as denoting
          a complete end to the warfare of the enemy.    "
    - name: '10: Cleansing of the Land'
      title: Cleansing of the Land
      number: 10
      content: "They will not have to gather firewood from the countryside or cut
        it in the forests since they will be burning all the weapons. They will plunder
        those who plundered them and take spoils from those who took their spoils.
        I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201COn that day, I will provide Gog a famous burial spot in Israel.
        It will be the Valley of Travelers [[COMMENT(0)]] east of the sea, a graveyard
        so large that it blocks the way of the travelers. For there they will bury
        Gog and his entire horde, and it will be called the Valley of Gog\u2019s
        Army.   "
      comments:
      - number: 39:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe valley of those who travel east of the sea.\u201D
          This is possibly the Arnon Valley, which is a steep, rocky gorge.     
          Or \u201CHamon-Gog.\u201D    means the \u201CValley of Gog\u2019s Multitude
          [warriors].\u201D See v.  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'It will take the Israelites seven months to bury them all in order
        to cleanse the land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Everyone in Israel will dig their graves, and for this, they will
        be honored on the day I display my glory, says Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'And after the seven months are over, men will be appointed to search
        full time throughout the country to find and bury any remaining corpse of
        the invaders [[COMMENT(0)]] so that the land will be ritually clean again. '
      comments:
      - number: 39:14
        content: "  Or \u201Ctravelers.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "And as they go throughout the country, if one of them finds any human
        bones, he will set up a marker beside them so that the gravediggers can come
        and bury them in the Valley of Gog\u2019s Army, "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "near the town of Gog\u2019s Army. [[COMMENT(0)]] After that, the
        land will be ritually clean again.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 39:16
        content: "  Or \u201CHamonah,\u201D a feminine noun for \u201Cmultitude\u201D
          or \u201Chorde.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man,
        call for the birds of every kind and for all the wild animals to assemble
        and come. Say to them, \u2018Gather from everywhere for the sacrificial feast
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> prepares for you, a huge sacrificial feast
        on the mountains of Israel. Come and feast on the bodies of those who died
        and drink their blood. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "You will eat the flesh of mighty warriors and drink the blood of
        the princes of the earth as if they were the best fattened animals from Bashan
        [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014rams and lambs, goats and bulls. "
      comments:
      - number: 39:18
        content: '  Bashan was the fertile land north and east of the Jordan Valley,
          known for its livestock. So the animals of Bashan would represent the best
          animals in the land.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'You will gorge yourselves on fat and drink yourselves drunk on the
        blood of this sacrifice I am making for you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: God Will Restore Israel'
      title: God Will Restore Israel
      number: 20
      content: "You will be filled at my table, feasting on horses and riders, on
        mighty warriors of every rank. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have
        spoken.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CI will reveal my glory to the nations. They will witness the
        way I judge Gog and the display of my power when I punish Gog and his great
        army. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 39:21
        content: "  Or \u201CAll the nations will see the punishment I inflict and
          the power of my might that I display against them.\u201D The point is clearly
          made here that the nations will all bear witness to the terrifying judgment
          that  brings against the armies of Gog and his allies.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The people of Israel will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        their God from that day forward and forever. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The nations will also realize that the people of Israel went into
        captivity because of their guilt, for they were unfaithful [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to me. So, I hid my face from them and gave them over to the power of their
        enemies, whereby they were all killed in war. '
      comments:
      - number: 39:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cdealt treacherously.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "I treated them as their despicable deeds of infidelity deserved and
        hid my face from them.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "So, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this: \u201CNow I will
        be merciful and bring Jacob\u2019s captives back and show pity on all the
        people of Israel. I will be zealous to not let them dishonor my holy name. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'They will forget [[COMMENT(0)]] their shame and all their acts of
        unfaithfulness that they committed against me when they were living safely
        in their own land with none to make them afraid. '
      comments:
      - number: 39:26
        content: "  The Hebrew text (MT) reads  , meaning \u201Cwill bear,\u201D
          which, in reference to Israel\u2019s shame, makes little or no sense in
          this context. However, a number of other versions adopt the alternative
          reading  , meaning \u201Cwill forget,\u201D which is ideally suited to
          this context.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When I have brought them back from the lands of their enemies, many
        nations will see the display of my holiness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'And they will know that I am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel. Yes, I sent them into exile among the nations, but I will then
        reunite them in their own land, not leaving a single one behind. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "I will pour out my Spirit on the people of Israel, and my divine
        presence will never again leave them. [[COMMENT(0)]] I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 39:29
        content: "  It is hard not to see the fulfillment of this with God\u2019s
          people today. The Lord promises never to leave us or forsake us. See  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Shining Measuring Man'
      title: The Shining Measuring Man
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]In the first month of the twenty-fifth year of our
        captivity, on the tenth day of the month, and nearly fourteen years after
        the Babylonians captured Jerusalem,  on that day <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        overpowered me <smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and carried me away to Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:1
        content: "    constitutes panel C  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          These chapters contain the visionary plans for the ideal temple, providing
          the perfect environment for Israel\u2019s godly leaders in the new covenant
          age. These chapters then serve as a striking contrasting parallel with
          chs.    (panel C\u2014specifically,  ), which deal with the corruption
          of Israel\u2019s leaders and their condemnation and judgment. There is
          also here the implied desecration and destruction of the Jerusalem temple,
          along with the promised destruction of all cities and towns in the land
          (see  ). The final nine chapters are truly the culmination of the entire
          book. They detail the final restoration of Israel and the restored temple
          that brings blessing and life to the nations. To read Ezekiel without these
          last chapters is to miss the overarching message of hope, not judgment.
          Chapters    give us the details of the new temple and its courtyards. Chapter   
          shows God returning to dwell within his new temple, in the same way he
          left the old temple in ch.  . Ezekiel begins and ends with a vision of
          God\u2019s glory. For more on Ezekiel\u2019s Temple, see \u201CInterpreting
          Ezekiel\u2019s Temple\u201D in the introduction.      The date of this
          chapter is probably September\u2013October 573 BC. Some Jewish scholars
          believe that this was a Jubilee year (see  ), when the enslaved were given
          freedom and debts were canceled. Perhaps as it was \u201Cthe tenth day
          of the month\u201D this was also the Day of Atonement (see  ).      Or
          \u201Cthe hand of  was upon me,\u201D a figure of speech for the overwhelming
          power of God coming upon Ezekiel.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'In an ecstatic vision from God, he carried me away to the land of
        Israel and put me down on a very high mountain. As I looked toward the south,
        there was a group of buildings that seemed to be a city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'And when he brought me closer to the buildings, behold, I saw a man
        standing in the gateway. His appearance was shining and glistening like polished
        bronze. He held a linen cord and a measuring rod in his hand. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 40:3
        content: '  This was possibly a Christophany, a pre-incarnate appearing of
          the Lord Jesus Christ. He is the Measuring Man, who brings all into the
          full dimensions of his likeness (see  ). Bronze is a frequent biblical
          symbol for judgment, while linen (flax) is a symbol of righteousness. Jesus
          is coming to measure his temple. The measurements of his temple are exact
          (to show that the promise is certain), equal (to denote unity and harmony),
          and vast (to speak of majesty and grandeur).    '
    - name: '4: The Outer Wall'
      title: The Outer Wall
      number: 4
      content: "The shining man said to me, \u201CSon of man, look closely and listen
        carefully. Pay close attention to everything I show you, for I have brought
        you here to reveal these things to you. You must tell the people of Israel
        everything you see.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: The East Gate'
      title: The East Gate
      number: 5
      content: Behold, I saw an outer wall surrounding the whole area where the temple
        stood. And the shining man was holding a measuring reed, and its length was
        six long cubits, each cubit a forearm and a handbreadth. [[COMMENT(0)]] He
        measured the wall with the reed, and it was one reed high and one reed thick.
      comments:
      - number: 40:5
        content: "  The word    finds its origin in the Latin word  , the word for
          the lower arm. A long cubit begins at the elbow and extends to the tip
          of the longest finger. The Hebrew word for cubit is    and literally means
          \u201Cmother of the arm.\u201D These closing chapters of Ezekiel pose numerous
          difficulties including discrepancies and contradictions to the law found
          in the Pentateuch. The Rabbis of the Talmud (Menahot 45a) have stated that
          only Elijah himself would be able to decipher these difficulties when he
          comes. Additionally, it is difficult to be precise in the length of a cubit.
          Generally, a standard cubit is believed to be about 17.5 inches or 0.44
          meters. A long cubit was a cubit plus a handbreadth (3.5 inches or 90 millimeters);
          in total about 21 inches or 0.53 meters. Unless otherwise noted, conversions
          from cubits to modern units in this translation will be calculated using
          the long cubit measurement. Based on this, the length of the measuring
          reed would be about 10.5 feet (3.2 meters).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He went into the opening of the gateway facing east, climbed the
        steps, [[COMMENT(0)]] and measured its threshold as one reed deep. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:6
        content: "  Apparently, there were seven steps (see vv.  ,  ).      About
          10.5 feet (3.2 meters). The Hebrew is literally \u201Cdeep, and one threshold,
          one reed deep.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Beyond the threshold was a corridor, which had rooms on each side
        for the guards. Each of the side rooms was square and measured one reed on
        each side. The space between the side rooms was five cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        And the inside threshold of the gate leading to the portico facing the temple
        was one reed deep.
      comments:
      - number: 40:7
        content: '  About 8.75 feet (2.65 meters). Also vv.  ,  .    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then he measured the porch of the gate on the inside. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'It was eight cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] deep, flanked by pillars  two
        cubits  thick. The porch opened onto the temple courtyard. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:9
        content: "  About 14 feet (4.26 meters).      Or \u201Cjambs\u201D\u2014either
          for windows or doors. Also vv.  ,  ,  .      About 3.5 feet (1.06 meters).    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'On each side of the east gate there were three guardrooms, all three
        the same size, and the walls that separated them were the same size. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'He measured the width of the entrance as ten cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and its length, thirteen cubits.   '
      comments:
      - number: 40:11
        content: '  About 17.5 feet (5.3 meters).      About 22.75 feet (6.9 meters).    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: And there was a low wall one cubit high in front of the guardrooms.
        Each of the guardrooms was six cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] square.
      comments:
      - number: 40:12
        content: '  About 10.5 feet (3.2 meters).    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then he measured the width of the gate from the top back wall of
        one guardroom to the top back wall of the opposite one. It was twenty-five
        cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] straight across. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:13
        content: '  About 43.75 feet (13.3 meters). Also vv.  ,  ,  ,  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'He calculated the height of the porch, which led out to a courtyard,
        as sixty cubits high. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 40:14
        content: '  About 105 feet (32 meters). There are details here that may suggest
          an internal linear measurement, rather than a height dimension. However,
          these details are difficult to translate with precision, and there is common
          agreement that the Hebrew text of this verse is uncertain.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: From the outside wall of the gate to the far side of the porch, he
        measured as fifty cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 40:15
        content: '  About 87.5 feet (26.5 meters). Also vv.  ,  ,  ,  ,  .    '
    - name: "16: The Temple\u2019s Outer Courtyard"
      title: "The Temple\u2019s Outer Courtyard"
      number: 16
      content: On all the inside walls of the gateway were windows with narrow recesses
        all around. The walls of the guardrooms, the walls between them, and the
        walls of the porch likewise had windows all around. And there were palm trees
        [[COMMENT(0)]] carved on the inner walls of the corridor and on the doorways.
      comments:
      - number: 40:16
        content: '  The palm tree is a symbol of praise and victory. They waved palm
          branches before King Jesus as he entered Jerusalem (see  ), and the overcoming
          saints in glory also celebrate with palm branches (see  ).    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then the shining man brought me into the outer court, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and behold, there was a spacious terrace paved with stones, and thirty chambers
        were built against the outer wall.   '
      comments:
      - number: 40:17
        content: "  In Talmudic literature, this was known as the \u201CCourtyard
          of the Women,\u201D or the outer courtyard, where all could assemble.     
          See  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'This paved terrace, or Lower Terrace, [[COMMENT(0)]] was as wide
        as the gateways were long and extended throughout the courtyard. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:18
        content: '  The lower level of the courtyard had steps going up to the inner
          (upper) courtyard, which surrounded the temple proper (sanctuary).    '
    - name: '19: The North Gate'
      title: The North Gate
      number: 19
      content: Then he measured the width of the courtyard, from the inside of the
        lower gateway to the outside of the inner court; it was one hundred cubits
        [[COMMENT(0)]] on the east side. Then he went to measure the north side.
      comments:
      - number: 40:19
        content: '  About 175 feet (53 meters). Also vv.  ,  ,  .    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Behold, there was a gate in the outer courtyard that faced to the
        north. He measured its length and width. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The length of the gateway was fifty cubits, and its width was twenty-five
        cubits. Its pillars and porch were of the same size as those of the first
        gate. It also had three guardrooms on each side. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Its windows, its porch, and its palm trees were of the same measurement
        as those of the east gate. There were also seven steps leading up to it,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and its porch was at the end facing the courtyard. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:22
        content: "  These seven steps leading up into the outer courtyard point to
          a progressive ascent into God\u2019s presence. Additionally, there were
          eight more steps going from the outer courtyard up to the inner courtyard
          (see v.  ). The total of fifteen steps to ascend into God\u2019s presence
          is seen in the Songs of Ascent (see    and first footnote on  ).    "
    - name: '23: The South Gate'
      title: The South Gate
      number: 23
      content: In the inner court across from the north gate there was another gateway
        leading into the inner courtyard, just as there was opposite the east gate.
        He measured the distance from one gate to the other, and it was one hundred
        cubits.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Next, the shining man took me to the south side, and behold, there
        was another gate. He measured its pillars and porch; they were of the same
        dimensions as the others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The gateway, as well as its porch, had narrow windows all around,
        like the windows of the others; it was fifty cubits long and twenty-five
        wide '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'and had seven steps leading up to it. Its porch was at the inner
        end and had palm trees carved on its pillars, one on either side. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: The Inner Courtyard'
      title: The Inner Courtyard
      number: 27
      content: There was also a lower gate on the south side of the inner court.
        He measured the distance southward from one gate to the other as one hundred
        cubits.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'He then took me into the inner court by the south gate. He measured
        the south gate, and its dimensions were the same as the others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Its guardrooms, pillars, and porch were also the same size as the
        others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'There were porches [[COMMENT(0)]] all around the gateway and each
        porch was fifty cubits long and five cubits wide.   '
      comments:
      - number: 40:30
        content: "  Or \u201Cvestibules,\u201D which are narrow verandas or covered
          walkways on the inside of the wall of the inner courtyard.      A number
          of translations omit this verse as it is not found in the Septuagint and
          some Hebrew manuscripts.    "
    - name: '31: The East Gate'
      title: The East Gate
      number: 31
      content: The porches all faced the outer court with eight steps leading up
        to them. And palm trees were carved on the pillars of the corridor.
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Then he took me into the inner court on the east side and measured
        the gateway. It was identical in size to the others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Its guardrooms, pillars, and porches were of the same dimensions
        as the others. The gateway, as well as its porch, had windows all around.
        It was fifty cubits long and twenty-five cubits wide. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: The North Gate'
      title: The North Gate
      number: 34
      content: Its porch faced the outer court with eight steps leading up to it,
        and there were palm trees carved on its pillars.
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Then the shining man brought me to the north gate and measured it,
        and it had the same dimensions as the others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Its guardrooms, pillars, and porches were of the same dimension as
        the others. The gateway had narrow windows all around. It was fifty cubits
        long and twenty-five cubits wide. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: Buildings near the Inner Gates'
      title: Buildings near the Inner Gates
      number: 37
      content: Its porch [[COMMENT(0)]] faced the outer court, and there were eight
        steps leading up to it, and there were palm trees carved on its pillars on
        either side.
      comments:
      - number: 40:37
        content: "  The term \u201Cporch\u201D (Hb.  ) comes from the Septuagint
          (LXX) and is the preferred reading. The Hebrew (MT) has the related term 
          , which means \u201Cjamb\u201D\u2014an apparent scribal error, as \u201Cjamb\u201D
          makes little sense in the context.    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'In each of the inner gateways there was a chamber with a doorway
        by the porch, where they washed the burnt offerings. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 40:38
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'And inside the porches of the gates there were two tables placed
        on each side, on which the burnt offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings
        were slaughtered. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "Outside the north gate, near the steps to the entrance, two tables
        were placed against both outside walls of the porches\u2014"
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'four tables inside and four tables outside, eight tables in all [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for slaughtering the animals for sacrifice. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:41
        content: "  These eight tables represent our feast at the Lord\u2019s Table
          and speak of the new covenant made by the one sacrifice of Jesus Christ.
          Eight is the number of a new beginning.    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'There were also four slabs of hewn stone used for the burnt offerings
        that were each a cubit and a half long, [[COMMENT(0)]] a cubit and a half
        wide, and one cubit high. The instruments used for slaughtering the burnt
        offerings and sacrificial animals were placed on these slabs. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:42
        content: '  About 2.63 feet (0.8 meters).    '
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: And four-inch-long [[COMMENT(0)]] double-pronged hooks were fastened
        to the wall all around   the stone tables. And the carcasses of the sacrificial
        animals were prepared on the tables.
      comments:
      - number: 40:43
        content: "  About 10 centimeters.      Or possibly \u201Cledges [shelves]
          a handbreadth long were attached to the wall all around.\u201D    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'Then he brought me  [[COMMENT(0)]] into the inner courtyard just
        outside the north gate. Behold, I saw chambers for the singers  of the inner
        court, one on the side of the north gate, facing south, the other on the
        side of the south gate,  facing north. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:44
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint.      Although a reference
          to temple singers seems out of place, these \u201Csingers\u201D were likely
          a choir of Levites (priests) who sang and provided musical accompaniment
          during the times of prayer and offering of sacrifices.      As translated
          from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Ceast gate.\u201D    "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "The shining man told me, \u201CThe chamber facing south is for the
        priests responsible for the service of the temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: The Inner Court'
      title: The Inner Court
      number: 46
      content: "And the chamber facing north is for the priests responsible for the
        sacrifices of the altar. These are the sons of Zadok, [[COMMENT(0)]] for
        only the sons of Levi are permitted to go into <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence to serve him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 40:46
        content: "  Zadok was the faithful priest of David (see  ), who separated
          himself from King Saul (a picture of the traditions of an old order that
          God has left) and was the high priest when Solomon\u2019s Temple was built
          (see  ;  ).    means \u201Crighteous\u201D or \u201Cjustified.\u201D The
          name Zadok can also be found in the name Melchizedek (  means \u201Cking
          of righteousness\u201D). His lineage can be traced back to Phineas, a descendant
          of Eleazar, the son of Aaron (see  ). God entered into a covenant with
          Phineas and promised him that he would have an everlasting priesthood (see 
          ). All the priests had a ministry, but only the Zadokite priesthood could
          enter the Holy Place. Zadok\u2019s descendants were the high priests in
          Jerusalem until the Babylonians destroyed the city and the temple during
          the days of Ezekiel.    "
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: Then he measured the inner courtyard. It was one hundred cubits long
        and one hundred cubits wide, a square with the altar standing in front of
        the temple.
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Then he brought me to the entrance porch of the temple building,
        and he measured the gateposts of the porch. They were five cubits thick on
        either side, and the width of the gate was fourteen cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        The sidewalls of the gate were three cubits  on either side. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:48
        content: "  About 24.5 feet (7.42 meters). The Hebrew (MT) omits the words
          \u201Cthe width of the gate was fourteen cubits,\u201D most likely by the
          occurrence of homoeoteleuton\u2014a scribal error (homoeoteleuton occurs
          when two separate phrases or lines have identical endings, and the eye
          of the scribe slips from one to the other and omits the words in between).
          This reading is preserved in the Septuagint (LXX).      About 5.25 feet
          (1.6 meters).    "
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: 'The entrance porch itself was twenty cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] long 
        and twelve cubits  wide. There were ten steps leading up to it, and there
        were pillars by the gateposts, one on either side. '
      comments:
      - number: 40:49
        content: '  About 35 feet (10.6 meters).      See  .      About 21 feet (6.36
          meters).      See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Holy Place'
      title: The Holy Place
      number: 1
      content: 'The shining man brought me to the Holy Place [[COMMENT(0)]] and measured
        its doorframes; each was six cubits  wide.   '
      comments:
      - number: 41:1
        content: "  The temple proper was divided into three sections: (1) a portico
          or porch, (2) an outer sanctuary known as the Holy Place, and (3) an inner
          sanctuary known as the Holy of Holies, or the Most Holy Place.      About
          10.5 feet (3.2 meters). Also vv.  ,  ,  .      There are two Hebrew words
          at the end of v.    whose meaning is difficult to understand. Most translations
          omit them. The words are \u201Cwidth of the tent [tabernacle].\u201D    "
    - name: '2: The Holy of Holies'
      title: The Holy of Holies
      number: 2
      content: 'The width of the entrance was ten cubits, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the
        sides of the entrance were five cubits  on each side, its length was forty
        cubits,  and its width twenty cubits. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:2
        content: '  About 17.5 feet (5.3 meters).      About 8.75 feet (2.65 meters).
          Also vv.  ,  ,  .      About 70 feet (21.3 meters).      About 35 feet
          (10.6 meters). Also vv.  ,  .    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then he went inside the innermost chamber [[COMMENT(0)]] and measured
        the doorframes at the entrance as two cubits, then the entrance as six cubits,
        and the width of the entrance as seven cubits.   '
      comments:
      - number: 41:3
        content: "  The fact that this \u201Cshining man\u201D went into the Holy
          of Holies where only the high priest was allowed to enter is more than
          a hint of his identity. The shining man is a pre-incarnate manifestation
          of our High Priest, the Lord Jesus Christ (see  ).      About 12.25 feet
          (3.73 meters).    "
    - name: '4: Side Room of the Temple'
      title: Side Room of the Temple
      number: 4
      content: "He measured its length and width as twenty cubits, at the end of
        the outer sanctuary. Then he said to me, \u201CThis is the Holy of Holies.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He then measured the wall of the temple as six cubits thick. There
        were side rooms all around the temple that were each four cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:5
        content: '  About 7 feet (2.12 meters).    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'And there were three levels of the side rooms, [[COMMENT(0)]] with
        thirty rooms on each floor. All around the wall of the temple were ledges 
        that served as supports for the side rooms so that they did not have to be
        attached to the temple wall for support. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:6
        content: "  There were three stories of side chambers for the priests. Noah\u2019s
          ark likewise had three stories (see  ). See also the three pilgrim festivals
          in    and the mention of three dimensions of spiritual maturity in  ; 
          ;    (see especially the footnote on  ).      The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: The rooms were right up to the temple walls. The width of the side
        rooms increased, floor by floor, because the width of the temple increased
        as it got higher, from the lowest level through the middle level to the top
        level. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 41:7
        content: "  Some translations and commentaries see in the Hebrew of this
          verse a winding staircase. Indeed, Solomon\u2019s Temple had steps leading
          up to the upper levels of the side rooms (see  ); however, reasonable sense
          can be made of the Hebrew without including a stairway.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then I looked down and saw that the temple stood on a raised platform
        that surrounded it. The platform was a full measuring reed high (six cubits)
        and provided a foundation for the side rooms. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'The outer wall of the side rooms was five cubits thick. On the raised
        platform there was a terrace all around the side rooms of the temple. It
        was twenty cubits between the edge of the platform and the rooms for the
        priests. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'The outer wall of the side rooms was five cubits thick. On the raised
        platform there was a terrace all around the side rooms of the temple. It
        was twenty cubits between the edge of the platform and the rooms for the
        priests. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Building on the West Side'
      title: The Building on the West Side
      number: 11
      content: And the doors of the side rooms faced an open area, one door toward
        the north and one door toward the south. The width of the open area was five
        cubits wide all around.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: The Size of the Entire Temple'
      title: The Size of the Entire Temple
      number: 12
      content: 'The building on the west side of the courtyard was seventy cubits
        [[COMMENT(0)]] wide. The wall of the building was five cubits thick all around,
        and its length was ninety cubits. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:12
        content: '  About 122.5 feet (37.3 meters).      About 157.5 feet (48 meters).
          Apart from the dimensions, we know nothing more about this building and
          its possible use.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then the shining man measured the length of the temple as one hundred
        cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]] The length of the courtyard plus the building and
        its walls was also one hundred cubits. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:13
        content: '  About 175 feet (53 meters). Also vv.  ,  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The width of the courtyard on the east, including the front of the
        temple, was likewise one hundred cubits. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: Additional Details of the Temple Building'
      title: Additional Details of the Temple Building
      number: 15
      content: 'Then he measured the length of the building west of the courtyard,
        including its balconies on either side, which was also one hundred cubits.The
        entire inside of the Holy Place, [[COMMENT(0)]] the porches of the courtyard, '
      comments:
      - number: 41:15
        content: '  See v.  .    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'the thresholds, the windows, and the galleries [[COMMENT(0)]] on
        three sides that faced the threshold were paneled with wood all around, from
        the floor up to the windows. And the windows were screened with latticework. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cledges\u201D or \u201Cbalconies.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'On the door to the inner part of the temple and on all the walls
        all around, both inside and outside, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 41:17
        content: '  The Hebrew text adds an untranslatable word that may be a technical
          carpentry term referring to a construction technique or pattern.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'were carved alternating cherubim and palm trees. [[COMMENT(0)]] Each
        of the cherubim had two faces, '
      comments:
      - number: 41:18
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'a human face that gazed toward the palm tree on one side and the
        face of a young lion turned toward the palm tree on the other side. They
        were carved throughout the temple everywhere. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The Holy Place had the same pattern of cherubim and palm trees carved
        on the wall from the floor to the space above the doors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: The Wooden Altar'
      title: The Wooden Altar
      number: 21
      content: The columns of the doorway to the Holy Place were square, and the
        columns at the entrance to the Holy of Holies were similar.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: The Doors in the Temple'
      title: The Doors in the Temple
      number: 22
      content: "A wooden altar was there, three cubits high, two cubits long, and
        two cubits wide. [[COMMENT(0)]] Its corners, base, and sides were of wood. 
        The shining man said to me, \u201CThis is the table that always stands in
        the presence of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 41:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cthree cubits high and two cubits long.\u201D The Hebrew
          text only gives the altar\u2019s height and length, omitting its width.
          The Septuagint includes its width, which most translations have also done.     
          It is remarkable that silver and gold, which were prominent in Solomon\u2019s
          Temple and the tabernacle of Moses, are not even mentioned in  . Neither
          is there any mention of the ark of the covenant, the mercy seat, or a high
          priest. Ezekiel\u2019s vision of the new temple omits many items from the
          temple because, in the ultimate heavenly dwelling place of God, there is
          no longer any need for a physical symbol of God\u2019s residence (viz.,
          the ark of the covenant), nor the symbolic throne of God (viz., the mercy
          seat). And the role of the high priest has been consummated in the person
          of Jesus Christ, our eternal High Priest\u2014the Lamb of God.      Most
          scholars believe this was the altar of incense within the Holy Place.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The Holy Place and the Holy of Holies had double doors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Each of the doors had two hinged leaves that swung open in the middle. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'On the doors of the Holy Place were carved cherubim and palm trees
        just like those carved on the walls. There was a wooden roof [[COMMENT(0)]]
        over the outside of the doorway to the Holy Place. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:25
        content: "  Or \u201Ccanopy.\u201D The Hebrew is uncertain. Whatever this
          covering or roof was, it no doubt served both as a barrier to prevent people
          from looking into the temple and as a shelter from the rain, sun, and wind
          for the priests as they entered the temple for their service.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: And there were niches [[COMMENT(0)]] with palm trees on either side
        in the front walls of the temple porch. And the side rooms of the temple
        also had canopies.
      comments:
      - number: 41:26
        content: "  Or \u201Crecessed windows.\u201D See  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Sacred Rooms for the Priests'
      title: The Sacred Rooms for the Priests
      number: 1
      content: 'Then the shining man brought me northward into the outer court and
        brought me to the rooms opposite the temple courtyard and opposite the outer
        wall on the north side. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Along the front, the building was one hundred cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        long on the north side and fifty cubits  wide. '
      comments:
      - number: 42:2
        content: '  About 175 feet (53 meters). Also vv.  ,  .      About 87.5 feet
          (26.5 meters). Also vv.  ,  .    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'On one side of the building was the twenty-cubit-wide [[COMMENT(0)]]
        plaza of the inner courtyard. On the other side was the paved walkway of
        the outer courtyard. The building itself was three stories high and had balconies. '
      comments:
      - number: 42:3
        content: '  About 35 feet (10.6 meters).    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'And in front of the rooms was an inner passageway, ten cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide and one hundred cubits long,  and all their doors faced north. '
      comments:
      - number: 42:4
        content: "  About 17.5 feet (5.3 meters).      According to the Septuagint
          and Syriac. However, the Hebrew text reads \u201Cby way of a cubit.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The top-floor rooms were narrower than those on the middle and bottom
        stories of the building because the balconies took up some of the space of
        the lower stories. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: The rooms on the third floor had no columns like the pillars of the
        outer courtyard. That is why the top story was narrower than the middle and
        bottom stories. The rooms became smaller the higher they went.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'There was a wall in the outer courtyard, parallel to the rooms, that
        was fifty cubits long. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The wall was like this because the row of rooms along the outer courtyard
        was fifty cubits long, while the row of rooms that faced the temple was one
        hundred cubits long. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'Beneath the rooms there was an entrance facing east so that a person
        could enter them from the outer court.On the south side [[COMMENT(0)]] of
        the temple, along the broad wall of the outer court, adjoining the temple
        courtyard, facing the outer wall there was a building containing rooms, with
        a passageway in front of them. '
      comments:
      - number: "42:9\u201310"
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cin the
          direction toward the east,\u201D which is believed to be a scribal error.    "
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: 'Beneath the rooms there was an entrance facing east so that a person
        could enter them from the outer court.On the south side [[COMMENT(0)]] of
        the temple, along the broad wall of the outer court, adjoining the temple
        courtyard, facing the outer wall there was a building containing rooms, with
        a passageway in front of them. '
      comments:
      - number: "42:9\u201310"
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cin the
          direction toward the east,\u201D which is believed to be a scribal error.    "
    - name: '11-12: '
      title: 
      number: 11-12
      content: "These south side rooms were like those rooms on the north side, with
        the same entry and exit doors and the same dimensions. There was also an
        entrance to the rooms at the beginning of the walkway\u2014the walkway before
        the corresponding wall that faced east."
      comments: []
    - name: '11-12: '
      title: 
      number: 11-12
      content: "These south side rooms were like those rooms on the north side, with
        the same entry and exit doors and the same dimensions. There was also an
        entrance to the rooms at the beginning of the walkway\u2014the walkway before
        the corresponding wall that faced east."
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "The shining man said to me, \u201CThe northern and southern rooms
        facing the courtyard are holy chambers, the place where the priests who approach
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> will eat the most holy offerings. Because this
        is a holy place, the most holy offerings will be stored there: the grain
        offering, [[COMMENT(0)]] the sacrifice for sin, and the guilt offering. "
      comments:
      - number: 42:13
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '14: Measurements of the Temple Compound'
      title: Measurements of the Temple Compound
      number: 14
      content: "When the priests have served inside the temple, they must first take
        off their priestly garments and leave them in the rooms before going out
        into the courtyard. Their priestly garments are holy, so they must change
        their clothes before going near other people.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 42:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cbefore going near the places reserved for the common
          people.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'When the shining man had finished measuring the inner temple area,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] he took me out through the east gate and measured the outside
        wall of the temple compound. '
      comments:
      - number: 42:15
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cthe inner house.\u201D The Hebrew term used
          here is one sometimes used for the Holy of Holies (see  ).    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Using his measuring rod, he measured all the east side as five hundred
        cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] total. '
      comments:
      - number: 42:16
        content: '  About 875 feet (265 meters). Also vv.  ,  ,  ,  .  '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'He measured all the north side as five hundred cubits by the measuring
        rod. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He measured all the south side as five hundred cubits by the measuring
        rod. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Then he turned to the west side and measured it as five hundred cubits
        by the measuring rod. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: And so he measured the temple compound on all four sides. The wall
        of the temple compound was five hundred cubits square, to mark the boundary
        between what was holy and what was common.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Returns to His Temple'
      title: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Returns to His Temple
      number: 1
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>Afterward, the shining man
        led me to the gate facing east. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:1
        content: '    constitutes panel B  in the chiastic structure of the book.
          These chapters contain the vision of the glory cloud returning to the temple
          (ch.  ) followed by the promise of the renewal of worship reserved exclusively
          for the priestly ministry of the Zadokites (ch.  ). These chapters then
          serve as a striking contrasting parallel with chs.    (panel B), which
          record oracles of condemnation against Israel for her idolatrous worship
          in the temple (see chs.  ), leading to the departure of the glory cloud
          from the temple (see chs.  ). Note particularly the vision of the glory
          of  at the north gate in  .    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'And behold, I saw the glory of the God of Israel storming from the
        east with a roar! A thunderous sound came with him like the sound of a great
        waterfall. [[COMMENT(0)]] All the ground was glowing brightly, illuminated
        by his glorious presence. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:2
        content: "  Or \u201CThe voice of his coming was like the sound of many waters.\u201D
          The Targum translates this as \u201CHis voice was like those who praise
          his name.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: This vision was like the one I had seen when he [[COMMENT(0)]] came
        to destroy the city  and like those visions I had experienced by the River
        Chebar.  Then I fell facedown to the ground.
      comments:
      - number: 43:3
        content: "  As translated from a few Hebrew manuscripts and the Latin Vulgate.
          Most Hebrew manuscripts have \u201Cwhen I came to destroy the city.\u201D     
          See chs.  .      See chs.  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The awesome glory of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> entered the temple
        through the eastern gate. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s Spirit lifted me into the
        air and set me down in the inner courtyard; and behold, I watched the glory
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  like a cloud  [[COMMENT(0)]] fill the temple. "
      comments:
      - number: 43:5
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'While the shining man stood beside me, I heard the voice of one speaking
        to me from inside the temple. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 43:6
        content: '  God still speaks to his people today, from inside us, his temples
          (see  ).    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "And he said to me, \u201CSon of man, this is the place of my throne,
        the place on which I will rest my feet, where I will live among the Israelites
        forever. And the people of Israel and their kings will never again drag my
        holy name through the mud. They will never disgrace me again by their spiritual
        prostitution [[COMMENT(0)]] or memorials to their dead kings   "
      comments:
      - number: 43:7
        content: "  That is, by their infidelity to God\u2019s covenant in worshiping
          other gods.      Or literally \u201Cby their corpses in their death.\u201D
          Some interpret the Hebrew as referring to the deaths of Israel\u2019s kings
          close to the temple area.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'or by putting their threshold beside my threshold and their doorposts
        beside my doorposts, with only a wall between us. [[COMMENT(0)]] They have
        defiled my holy name by their despicable practices, so in my anger I put
        an end to them. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:8
        content: "  There are two ways to understand the Hebrew text. (1) The royal
          palace had been built right next to the southern wall of the temple compound,
          which meant the doorways to both buildings were shared with only a wall
          between the sacred compound and the living quarters of the kings. (2) \u201CTheir
          threshold\u201D and \u201Ctheir doorposts\u201D could refer to the entrance
          of shrines built in or near the temple compound to worship other gods with
          only a wall between what was sacred and what was blasphemous.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: Now they must put away their unfaithfulness of worshiping other gods
        and put away the corpses of their kings from my presence, and I will make
        my home with them forever.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSon of man, describe this temple in detail to the people of
        Israel so that they will be ashamed of their despicable deeds. Let them carefully
        study the perfect structure of the temple. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 43:10
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cand they will measure the perfection.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: The Law of the Temple'
      title: The Law of the Temple
      number: 11
      content: "Then, if they truly express sorrow over their sins, explain to them
        the design and plan of the temple\u2014its exits and entrances, its shape,
        its arrangement, the entire design, and all its rules for operation. Sketch
        it out for them so that they can observe and understand the entire plan and
        follow all its rules.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Description of the Altar for Burning Sacrifices'
      title: Description of the Altar for Burning Sacrifices
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CThis is the law of the temple: the mountaintop radiates his
        glory, therefore, all around the Temple Mount will be a most holy area. Behold,
        this is the most important law of the temple.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CThis is the measurement of the altar using the same unit of
        measurement as the rest of the temple: [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        The base  is one cubit high and one cubit wide, with a rim of one span  around
        its edge. The altar itself is to be this high: "
      comments:
      - number: 43:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cthese are the measurements of the altar by cubits, the
          cubit being a cubit and a handbreadth,\u201D that is, a long cubit. A long
          cubit was approximately 21 inches (0.53 meters). It should be noted that
          there are differing views as to who is speaking in this subsection, Ezekiel
          or God. The translation team assumes that  is speaking, since he is the
          one speaking before and after vv.  . Additionally, there are no verbs in
          the Hebrew text in this subsection.      Or \u201Cgutter\u201D or \u201Ctrench,\u201D
          presumably to catch the blood from the animals sacrificed.      A span
          was a unit of measurement that was approximately 9 inches (22 centimeters).    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'from the base on the ground to the lower ledge, two cubits, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        with a width of one cubit. And from the smaller ledge to the larger ledge,
        four cubits  high and one cubit wide. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:14
        content: '  About 3.5 feet (1.06 meters).      About 7 feet (2.13 meters).
          Also v.  .    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The altar hearth is to be four cubits high, with four horns projecting
        upward from the hearth, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 43:15
        content: "  See  . The Septuagint states that altar horns were \u201Cone
          cubit high [or long].\u201D The altar hearth was the fireplace at the top
          of the altar.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'and the hearth a perfect square: twelve cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] long
        by twelve cubits wide. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:16
        content: '  About 21 feet (6.4 meters).    '
    - name: '17: The Dedication of the Altar'
      title: The Dedication of the Altar
      number: 17
      content: "The ledge is also to be a square: fourteen cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        long and fourteen cubits wide on four sides with a rim around it of half
        a cubit,  and its surrounding base one cubit. Its steps are on the east side
        of the altar.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 43:17
        content: '  About 24.5 feet (7.46 meters).      About 10.5 inches (0.27 meters).    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man,
        here are the rules you must follow when the altar [[COMMENT(0)]] is built
        to offer burnt offerings and to splash on it the blood of the animals they
        sacrifice. "
      comments:
      - number: 43:18
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Caltar\u201D is    and means \u201Cthe
          mount of El.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'You must give a young bull to the Levitical priests, the descendants
        of Zadok. They are the ones who may come before me to serve me and offer
        the bull as a sacrifice for sin, declares Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'You must take some of its blood and smear it on the four horns, on
        the four corners of the ledge, and on its surrounding rim. In this way you
        will purify it and make atonement for it. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 43:20
        content: "  To smear the blood on the altar would make it ritually clean
          and consecrated for sacred use. The Hebrew verb    means \u201Cto make
          atonement\u201D and comes from a root meaning either \u201Cto cover\u201D
          or \u201Cto wipe away.\u201D The rest of the bull was to be burned outside
          the sacred area or outside the temple compound (see v.  ) or outside the
          camp (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Then take the bull offered as the sacrifice for sin and burn its
        carcass in the appointed place outside the sacred area. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'On the second day, you must offer an unblemished male goat as the
        sin offering, and the priests must purify the altar again as they did on
        the first day with the bull. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'When you have finished purifying the altar, you must offer a young,
        unblemished bull and a young, unblemished ram. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'You must present them before me, and the Zadokite priests will sprinkle
        salt on them [[COMMENT(0)]] and offer them as burnt offerings to me.   '
      comments:
      - number: 43:24
        content: '  See  ;  .      The implication is that the priests were not allowed
          to eat any portion of it themselves.    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Each day for seven days you must sacrifice to me a young male goat,
        a young bull, and a young ram as a sin offering. All of them must be unblemished
        animals. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'In this way the altar will be purified, cleansed, and consecrated
        for seven days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "When the seven days [[COMMENT(0)]]  of consecration are over, on
        the eighth day and each day afterward, the priest will offer burnt offerings 
        and communion sacrifices  on the altar on behalf of the people. And I will
        accept you and be pleased with you. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 43:27
        content: "  See  .      Under the sacrificial system of the law, burnt offerings
          were very important. They were offered twice a day, in the morning and
          in the evening, as a sacrifice for the sins of the people.      Or \u201Cpeace
          offerings.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Access to the Temple'
      title: Access to the Temple
      number: 1
      content: 'Then the shining man brought me back to the outer gate of the sanctuary,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] which faces east, but it was shut. '
      comments:
      - number: 44:1
        content: "  That is, the outer gate of the temple area, today known as the
          \u201CGolden Gate.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CThis gate must be
        kept shut. No one may open it or enter through it, since <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, has passed through it. Therefore, it must remain shut. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: Rules for Admission to the Temple'
      title: Rules for Admission to the Temple
      number: 3
      content: "The prince, and only the prince, [[COMMENT(0)]] may sit inside the
        gateway to eat his sacred meal   in the presence of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        He must enter and leave through the porch of the gate of the outer courtyard.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 44:3
        content: "  Who is this \u201Cprince\u201D? Jewish scholars teach that it
          is the Messiah. Some think it is David himself. Jesus Christ, the Messiah,
          is called the Prince of Peace in  .      See  . Jesus eats his sacred meal
          with his disciples and with us. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then the shining man led me through the north gate to the front of
        the temple. And I looked and behold, I saw <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        glory cloud filling the temple. And I was awestruck and fell facedown to
        the ground."
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man, set
        your heart on what I am about to tell you. Look closely and listen carefully
        to everything I explain regarding all the laws and instructions about my
        temple. Pay careful attention to the entrance to the temple and all the exits
        from the sanctuary. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "And tell the rebels among the people of Israel, \u2018Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        says to you: Enough of all your despicable deeds, you people of Israel! "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'You have desecrated my temple by admitting gentiles into my sanctuary
        who are uncircumcised in heart and body, allowing them into my presence while
        you offer the fat and blood of sacrifices to me. [[COMMENT(0)]] You have
        broken my covenant in addition to all the wicked things you have done. '
      comments:
      - number: 44:7
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '8: The Levites'
      title: The Levites
      number: 8
      content: "Instead of keeping charge of my holy things yourselves, you have
        placed these gentiles in charge of my sanctuary.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says, \u201CNo gentile, uncircumcised
        in heart and body, may enter my sanctuary, even the foreigners living among
        the Israelites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'For the Levites who abandoned me when Israel turned their backs on
        me to worship their false gods must bear the consequences of their own sin. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'They may serve me in my sanctuary by being temple gatekeepers and
        temple servants. They may kill the animals the people bring to offer as burnt
        offerings and sacrifices for the people and by serving the worshipers in
        the temple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But because they assisted the people of Israel in the worship of
        their idols and thereby caused them to sin, I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        solemnly swear [[COMMENT(0)]] that they will suffer for their sin. '
      comments:
      - number: 44:12
        content: "  Or \u201Chave raised my hand against them,\u201D a figure of
          speech for taking an oath.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "They will never draw near to me again to fulfill the priestly office
        in my presence, nor will they ever again touch my holy things\u2014my very,
        very holy things! They must bear the shame and disgrace of their despicable
        deeds. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Rules for the Priests'
      title: Rules for the Priests
      number: 14
      content: "I will, however, assign them the responsibility of performing temple
        duties in the outer court. I will make them responsible for serving the temple
        and the work to be done in it.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  says, \u201CThe Levitical priests,
        the sons of Zadok, [[COMMENT(0)]] who faithfully served in my sanctuary when
        the rest of the Israelites strayed far from me, they will come near to me
        to minister to me. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, declare that they
        will stand in my presence to offer the sacrifices of fat and blood. "
      comments:
      - number: 44:15
        content: '  See    and footnote.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: They will enter my sanctuary and approach my table to minister to
        me and to oversee the temple worship.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CWhen the Zadokite priests enter the gates of the inner court,
        they must be wearing linen garments. They are not allowed to wear any wool
        [[COMMENT(0)]] clothing when they are on duty inside the inner court or in
        the temple. "
      comments:
      - number: 44:17
        content: "  The prohibition of the priests wearing wool seems to suggest
          that God doesn\u2019t want us to sweat in his presence (see v.  ). Linen
          vestments would be more comfortable and cooler to wear. Wool is a part
          of the beast (animal) realm. Wool is a symbol of the flesh and fleshly
          efforts to please God. Gideon offered his wool fleece to God on a threshing
          floor (see  ). Linen is a symbol of righteousness (see  ).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Their turbans and undergarments must all likewise be of linen. They
        are not to wear anything that makes them perspire. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 44:18
        content: "  Or literally \u201Cnot to belt themselves with sweat.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: When they finish their sacred duties, before they go out to mingle
        with the people in the outer court, they must remove their priestly garments
        they ministered in and leave them in the holy chamber rooms. They then must
        put on regular clothes so that they will not transmit holiness to the people
        through their sacred garments.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CThe priests must not shave their heads nor let their hair grow
        long, but must keep it properly trimmed. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 44:20
        content: '  To have long, unkempt hair was improper for the priests. Long
          hair was considered a sign of one in mourning (see  ,  ).    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CPriests must not drink wine before they enter the inner court."
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CThey may not marry a widow or a divorced woman but only an
        Israelite virgin. They may, however, marry a widow if she is the widow of
        a priest."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CThey must teach my people the difference between what is holy
        and what is ordinary and make them understand the difference between what
        is ritually clean for God\u2019s service and what is ritually unacceptable."
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CIf a dispute arises, the priests will judge it consistent with
        my laws. They must follow my instructions and regulations for all my appointed
        feasts and honor my holy Sabbaths."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CA priest must not defile himself by going near a dead person;
        however, if the dead person was his father or mother, son or daughter, brother,
        or unmarried sister, then he may defile himself. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'After his purification, he must wait seven days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: God, the Inheritance of the Priests'
      title: God, the Inheritance of the Priests
      number: 27
      content: "And the first day he goes back into the inner court to minister in
        the Holy Place, he must offer his sin offering. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says of the priests, \u201CI will be
        their sole inheritance. [[COMMENT(0)]] You are not to give them any possession
        in Israel, for I alone am their sole possession."
      comments:
      - number: 44:28
        content: "  The Hebrew is \u201CAnd it will be their inheritance.\u201D Scholars
          are divided over what \u201Cit\u201D refers to. The Latin Vulgate reads,
          \u201CThe priests have no inheritance.\u201D However, the pronoun more
          likely refers to the office of the priesthood.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CTheir food will be the grain offering, the sin offerings, and
        the guilt offerings. Everything dedicated by vow to God in Israel will be
        theirs. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'All the best fruits of every kind and all the offerings that the
        people give to God must go to the priests. And you must also give the first
        portion of the grain you grind into flour to the priests so that a blessing
        may rest on your house. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 44:30
        content: '  See  ;  .  '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Priests must not eat any bird or animal that has died a natural death
        or that wild animals have killed.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Sacred Arrangements'
      title: Sacred Arrangements
      number: 1
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>: \u201C</smallcaps><smallcaps>-Lives-There\u201D).
        These chapters then serve as the climactic, consummate contrasting parallel
        with chs.</smallcaps>\u201CWhen you apportion the land as an inheritance
        to each tribe, you must set aside a sacred portion for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
        It is to be 25,000 cubits  long and 20,000 cubits  wide. The entire area
        of this land will be sacred. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:1
        content: "    constitutes panel A\u2014the final one in the chiastic structure
          of the book. These chapters contain the visionary description of the division
          of the land and the renewal of the historical boundaries, implying renewed
          conquest (note especially  , a description of the sacred city, the dwelling
          place of      (panel A) that open the book of Ezekiel, focusing on the
          desecration of the land and temple (note the vision of the heavenly throne
          room).      About 8.29 miles (13.25 kilometers). Also vv.  ,  ,  .     
          About 6.63 miles (10.6 kilometers), as translated from the Septuagint.
          The Hebrew is \u201Cten thousand cubits wide.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'And inside this area, a square plot of land 500 cubits by 500 cubits
        [[COMMENT(0)]] must be set apart for the temple compound. All around the
        temple compound there will be a strip of open land that is 50 cubits  wide
        on each side. '
      comments:
      - number: 45:2
        content: '  About 875 feet long by 875 feet wide (265 meters long by 265
          meters wide).      About 87.5 feet (26.5 meters).    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Within this sacred portion you must mark off an area that is 25,000
        cubits long and 10,000 cubits [[COMMENT(0)]] wide. This is the area set apart
        for the temple, the Holy of Holies.
      comments:
      - number: 45:3
        content: '  About 3.31 miles (5.3 kilometers). Also v.  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CThis dedicated part of the land will be for the priests who
        minister before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> in his sanctuary. It will be
        for the priests\u2019 houses and for the holy precincts of the temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The other half of the area, a section 25,000 cubits long and 10,000
        cubits wide, will be owned by the Levites who minister at the temple, with
        towns for them to live in. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 45:5
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cas their
          possession, twenty chambers.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: The Portion for the Prince'
      title: The Portion for the Prince
      number: 6
      content: "You must assign an area 25,000 cubits long by 5,000 cubits [[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide, adjacent to the land belonging to my sanctuary. This will belong to
        all the people of Israel.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 45:6
        content: '  About 1.66 miles (2.65 kilometers).    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CThe prince [[COMMENT(0)]] will have land on both sides of the
        holy area and the city. West of the holy area and the city, his land will
        reach to the Mediterranean Sea. East of the holy area and the city, his land
        will reach to the eastern border of the country. It will correspond in length
        to the land given to each tribe. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:7
        content: '  See    and the first footnote there.    '
    - name: '8: Rules for the Rulers'
      title: Rules for the Rulers
      number: 8
      content: "This will be the prince\u2019s property in Israel. Then my leaders
        will no longer bully and oppress my people. They will permit the people of
        Israel to live peacefully and possess the rest of the country for its tribes.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 45:8
        content: "  Or \u201Coccupy the land in line with its tribal allocations.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says this: \u201CYou have overstepped
        your bounds, you leaders of Israel! Stop your violence and oppression and
        start practicing justice and righteousness. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        say to you: Do what is right and just, and stop forcing people from their
        homes so that you can take their property. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'You must have accurate scales and a true standard of measurement
        for grains (known as an ephah) [[COMMENT(0)]] and for liquids (known as a
        bath).   '
      comments:
      - number: 45:10
        content: '  The dry measurement of an ephah is a little over half a bushel
          or eighteen liters.      The liquid measurement of a bath is slightly over
          five gallons or nineteen liters.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The measurement of an ephah and bath must be equal, and each will
        be one-tenth of a homer, [[COMMENT(0)]] the bath and the ephah one-tenth
        of a homer. The standard for measuring will be based on the homer. '
      comments:
      - number: 45:11
        content: "  A homer (  literally means \u201Ca donkey load\u201D) is about
          50 gallons or 220 liters.    "
    - name: '12: Worship Offerings'
      title: Worship Offerings
      number: 12
      content: "A shekel is to consist of twenty gerahs. A mina is to consist of
        sixty shekels.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 45:12
        content: "  Or \u201Ctwenty shekels plus twenty-five shekels plus fifteen
          shekels.\u201D A mina was a little over a pound (a little over half a kilogram).
          The shekel, gerah, and mina were all weights used in Israel for measuring
          scales. These weights were usually stones of a specified weight. The shekel
          was about 20 gerahs in weight and roughly 0.4 ounces or 11.4 grams. A gerah
          was a bean, most likely from the carob tree, that amounted to one-twentieth
          of a shekel (see  ). God was telling Israel that the weights they use for
          measurements on their scales must be accurate.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CThese are the things you must bring as an offering to God:\u201COne-sixtieth
        of your wheat, [[COMMENT(0)]]One-sixtieth of your barley, "
      comments:
      - number: 45:13
        content: "  Or \u201Can ephah for every homer of wheat,\u201D which is one-sixtieth
          of their wheat harvest.      Or \u201Cand the sixth of an ephah for every
          homer of barley,\u201D which is equal to one-sixtieth of their barley harvest.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: One-hundredth of your olive oil, using the standard measurement known
        by all, [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 45:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cone bath of oil out of every ten baths or out of every
          kor [which is equal to ten baths or one homer, since ten baths equal one
          homer],\u201D which equals one-hundredth of the olive oil.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then, one sheep (or goat) is to be taken from every flock of two
        hundred livestock from the well-watered pastures of Israel.\u201CI, Lord
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, declare that these offerings will be for grain
        offerings, burnt offerings, and peace offerings, [[COMMENT(0)]] to make atonement 
        for the people."
      comments:
      - number: 45:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cfellowship offerings.\u201D      The word    is taken
          from an Anglo-Saxon word meaning \u201Cmaking at one,\u201D hence \u201Cat-one-ment.\u201D
          It is the act of loving reconciliation between God and fallen man. Atonement
          presupposes a separation from God that needs to be overcome if we are to
          know him and have fellowship with him. Making atonement is the act by which
          God and man are brought together in personal relationship. See v.  .    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CAll the people of the land will be required to give these offerings
        to the prince of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: The Feast of the Passover'
      title: The Feast of the Passover
      number: 17
      content: "The prince will be responsible to provide the burnt offerings, the
        grain offerings, and the drink offerings for feasts, new moons, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Sabbaths, and all the appointed feasts of the people of Israel.  The prince
        must provide the sacrifice for sin, the grain offering, the burnt offering,
        and the fellowship offerings to make atonement for the people of Israel.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 45:17
        content: '  See  .      These feasts were not secular celebrations, but the
          three major feasts of the Jewish calendar of Israel, which included Passover
          and the Feast of Unleavened Bread, the Feast of Weeks (also called Pentecost
          or Feast of Harvest), and the Feast of Tabernacles. These were called pilgrim
          festivals because every Israelite was expected to come together in Jerusalem
          for them. See  ;  ;  ;  .      Indeed, our Prince, the Lord Jesus, provided
          himself as the atoning sacrifice for sin. He is the fulfillment of all
          the offerings and sacrifices of the Old Testament.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201COn the first day of
        each new year, [[COMMENT(0)]] you must select a perfect young bull without
        blemish to sacrifice to purify the sanctuary. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:18
        content: "  This was not January 1 but the month of Nisan in the Jewish calendar
          (late March\u2013early April).    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The priest must take the blood of the sin offering and smear it on
        the doorposts of the temple, on the four corners of the ledge of the altar,
        and on the posts of the gate to the inner courtyard. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: You must do the same seven days later, on behalf of anyone who has
        sinned unintentionally or through ignorance. In this way you will purify
        [[COMMENT(0)]] the temple.
      comments:
      - number: 45:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cmake atonement for.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThen seven days later, on the fourteenth day of the first month,
        you will observe the Passover Feast [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        for seven days. During that time everyone must eat bread made without yeast. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cit will be Passover for you.\u201D Passover was a Hebrew
          festival to commemorate the night  \u201Cpassed over\u201D the Hebrew homes
          and rescued them from their slavery in Egypt. See  . Many years later,
          it was at the time of the Passover Feast that Jesus was crucified as the
          Passover Lamb. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'On the first day of the feast, the prince must offer a bull as a
        sacrifice for sin, for himself and all the sins of the people of the land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'And on each of the seven days of the festival the prince will offer
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> a burnt offering of seven young bulls and seven
        rams without blemish or defect. And every day he will also offer a male goat
        to take away the sins of the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: The Feast of Tabernacles'
      title: The Feast of Tabernacles
      number: 24
      content: "The prince must also offer one ephah of grain [[COMMENT(0)]] for
        each bull and each ram sacrificed. And he will also offer one hin  of oil
        for each ephah.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 45:24
        content: '  See v.    and first footnote there.      A hin is one-sixteenth
          of a bath (a bath is slightly over five gallons, or nineteen liters).    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201COn the fifteenth day of the seventh month [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        on each of the seven days of the Feast of Tabernacles, the prince must supply
        the provisions for the sin offerings, burnt offerings, grain offerings, and
        the oil.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 45:25
        content: '  This was late September or early October, the month of Tishri
          in the Jewish calendar.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Prince and the Feasts'
      title: The Prince and the Feasts
      number: 1
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CThe east gate of the
        inner courtyard must remain closed for the six working days. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        However, on the Sabbath day and the day of the new moon, it will be open. "
      comments:
      - number: 46:1
        content: '  That is, from Sunday to Friday.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The prince must enter through the porch of the outer gate and stand
        by the posts of the gateway as the priests offer his burnt offering and his
        fellowship offering on his behalf. He must bow down and worship at the threshold
        of the gate. Then the prince will go out the same gate he entered, but the
        gate will remain open until evening. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Each Sabbath and each new moon, all the people of the land will bow
        down and worship in the presence of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> at the
        entrance to the gate.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201COn the Sabbath, I want the prince to bring to me six lambs
        and one ram, all without flaws, and the priests will burn them as an offering
        to me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: Additionally, I want the prince to also give me one ephah of grain
        with the ram as an offering and as much grain offering as he wants to give
        for each lamb, plus a hin [[COMMENT(0)]] of olive oil for every ephah of
        flour.
      comments:
      - number: 46:5
        content: '  A hin is one-sixteenth of a bath (a bath is slightly over five
          gallons, or nineteen liters). Also vv.  ,  ,  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201COn the day of the new moon, I want the prince to offer to me
        a young unblemished bull, six unblemished lambs, and one unblemished ram. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: And with his offerings, I want him also to bring to me one ephah of
        grain for the bull and one ephah of grain for the ram, and as much flour
        and oil as he wants for the lambs, and a hin of oil for every ephah of grain.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CWhen the prince enters, he must enter and exit the outer courtyard
        by the porch of the gate."
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "\u201CWhen the people of Israel come into my presence for the solemn
        festivals, the prince will be with them, coming in with them and going out
        with them. When they enter the outer courtyard, they will all go in from
        either the north side or south side of the temple. Those who have come in
        by the north gate to bow in worship must go out by the south gate, and those
        who have come in by the south gate must go out by the north gate. No one
        will turn around and leave through the same gate by which he entered, but
        they must go out on the opposite side. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "46:9\u201310"
        content: "  That is, no one can be in God\u2019s presence and leave the same
          way as they came. God\u2019s presence changes us, transforms us, and touches
          our lives indelibly.    "
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "\u201CWhen the people of Israel come into my presence for the solemn
        festivals, the prince will be with them, coming in with them and going out
        with them. When they enter the outer courtyard, they will all go in from
        either the north side or south side of the temple. Those who have come in
        by the north gate to bow in worship must go out by the south gate, and those
        who have come in by the south gate must go out by the north gate. No one
        will turn around and leave through the same gate by which he entered, but
        they must go out on the opposite side. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "46:9\u201310"
        content: "  That is, no one can be in God\u2019s presence and leave the same
          way as they came. God\u2019s presence changes us, transforms us, and touches
          our lives indelibly.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201COn the feast days and solemn festivals the prince\u2019s grain
        offering must be one ephah for every bull, one ephah for every ram, and as
        much as he wants for the lambs, and a hin of oil for every ephah of grain. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: When the prince offers me a freewill burnt offering or a freewill
        fellowship sacrifice, the east gate must be opened for him, and he will make
        his offering as he does on the Sabbath day. When he leaves, the priests will
        shut the gate behind him.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CEvery day, he [[COMMENT(0)]] must provide a year-old flawless
        lamb as a burnt offering to me for the morning sacrifice. "
      comments:
      - number: 46:13
        content: "  As translated from a few Hebrew manuscripts, the Septuagint,
          and the Vulgate. Most Hebrew manuscripts have \u201Cyou.\u201D However,
          it is doubtful that \u201Cyou\u201D is referring to Ezekiel and more likely
          that it is referring to the \u201Cprince.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Additionally, every morning, he must provide a grain offering of
        one-sixth of an ephah and one-third hin of olive oil, to mix with the flour.
        This grain offering to me will be a lasting ordinance for all time. '
      comments: []
    - name: "15: The Prince\u2019s Land"
      title: "The Prince\u2019s Land"
      number: 15
      content: "Every single morning, the lamb, the grain, and the olive oil must
        be offered to me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CIf the prince gives
        a gift of his land to any of his sons, that land will belong to his descendants.
        It is their property by inheritance. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'If, however, he gives part of his inheritance to one of his servants,
        it will belong to him until the year of liberty, and then it must return
        to the prince. [[COMMENT(0)]] Only he and his sons will own it permanently. '
      comments:
      - number: 46:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cthen it will come to an end.\u201D The year of liberty
          is most likely the Year of Jubilee. See  . The purpose of this law was
          so that the prince\u2019s family would never permanently lose the property
          of their family line.    "
    - name: '18: The Sacred Kitchens'
      title: The Sacred Kitchens
      number: 18
      content: "The prince may not evict anyone from their land or seize any part
        of the family property of any Israelite. He must provide an inheritance for
        his sons out of his own property so that no member of my people is robbed
        of what is his!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 46:18
        content: "  Or \u201Cis scattered from his property.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then the shining man took me through the entrance at the side of
        the north gate that leads to the priests\u2019 holy chambers. And behold,
        there before us was a place at the western end of the rooms. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "He said to me, \u201CThis is the kitchen where the priests must boil
        the guilt offering and the sin offering, and where they must bake the grain
        offering without having to carry them into the outer court and inadvertently
        transmit holiness to the people.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Then he brought me out to the outer court and led me to each of its
        four corners. And in each corner of the outer court was an enclosure. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Each enclosure in the corners was the same size, forty cubits by
        thirty cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 46:22
        content: '  About 70 feet by 52.5 feet (21.3 meters by 16 meters).    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: All four enclosures had stone shelves on the walls [[COMMENT(0)]]
        with built-in fireplaces all around the walls under the ledge.
      comments:
      - number: 46:23
        content: "  Or \u201Ca ledge of stone all around the inside of each of the
          walls.\u201D These \u201Cledges\u201D were most likely courses of stone
          masonry designed to enclose the fireplaces.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then the shining man said to me, \u201CThese are the kitchens where
        the temple servants [[COMMENT(0)]] will cook the sacrifices the people offer.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 46:24
        content: '  That is, the Levites.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Life-Giving River Flows from the Temple'
      title: A Life-Giving River Flows from the Temple
      number: 1
      content: 'Then the shining man brought me back to the entrance of the temple,
        and I saw water flowing [[COMMENT(0)]] from underneath the temple threshold.
        It was flowing eastward (for the temple faced east).  Water was trickling
        out from the south side of the temple, south of the altar. '
      comments:
      - number: 47:1
        content: "  Today, the temple of God is the church, the Holy of Holies on
          the earth today (see  ;  ). This river can be a picture of the life-giving
          flow of the Holy Spirit, who becomes \u201Crivers\u201D pouring through
          us, his temple (see  ; see also  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ). This river heals
          as it flows; it brings life as it grows deeper.      There is a vast water
          table beneath the Temple Mount in Israel. In the Letter of Aristeas, dated
          circa 100 BC, there is mention of a spring on the Temple Mount inside the
          enclosure of the temple area. The many sacrifices and purification rites
          (involving  , immersion pools used for ceremonial cleansing of Jewish worshipers)
          required much water. It is also possible that past earthquakes have capped
          underground springs and reservoirs in Jerusalem. (See G. A. Cooke,  , The
          International Critical Commentary [Edinburgh: T &amp; T Clark, 1985], 517\u201318;
          see also L. Ritmeyer, \u201CLocating the Original Temple Mount,\u201D   
          18, no. 2 [1992]: 34\u201336, which includes various locations of cisterns
          [reservoirs] on the Temple Mount.)    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then he took me out by the north gate and led me around the outside
        to the gate that faces east. And there I saw water flowing out on the right-hand
        side, south of the gateway. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The man holding his measuring line walked east and measured off a
        thousand cubits. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then he made me wade across the shallow water,
        and it was ankle deep.   '
      comments:
      - number: 47:3
        content: "  About a third of a mile (1,750 feet; 530 meters). Three times
          Ezekiel uses this phrase in vv.  .      The river flowing \u201Cankle deep\u201D
          points to our walk in Christ. As we walk in the Spirit-River of life, our
          lives are changed. The first miracle of the apostles in the book of Acts
          helped a man lame in his ankles sitting at the temple\u2019s Beautiful
          Gate, the gate through which this river flowed. He was immediately healed
          and was able to walk and enter the temple for the first time in his life.
          Ezekiel\u2019s Temple began its process of being rebuilt as the lame beggar
          waded into the river of God pouring out from the apostles. See  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He measured off another thousand cubits and told me to wade across
        the stream again; the water was up to my knees. [[COMMENT(0)]] He measured
        off another thousand cubits and made me wade across the stream again, and
        the water was up to my waist.   '
      comments:
      - number: 47:4
        content: '  The knee-deep river of God points symbolically to a life of prayer.
          We bow our knees before the Father of Glory and enter into the flow of
          life through prayer (;  ;  ;  ).      The waist-deep river of God points
          symbolically to what we produce or give birth to, for the water soaks the
          reproductive organs. When the life-giving Spirit-River reaches our loins,
          we begin bearing the fruit of the Spirit, spiritual offspring, and enduring
          works that glorify God.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "He measured off another thousand; it was now a river over my head,
        which I was unable to swim across. It was a deep swollen river\u2014a river
        no one could cross."
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The shining man said to me, \u201CSon of man, do you see this?\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Then he brought me back to the riverbank. "
      comments:
      - number: 47:6
        content: "  No doubt Ezekiel was stunned by seeing a stream start as a trickle
          and end up becoming an impassable river. The rhetorical question that was
          posed to Ezekiel could be made into an emphatic statement, by saying, \u201CSon
          of man, pay close attention to the miracle you just witnessed! Get this
          revelation!\u201D A river over your head points to the revelation of the
          Holy Spirit that is deep and limitless, which cannot be humanly \u201Ccrossed
          over\u201D or understood without divine help. This deep river is flowing
          in us today and will cause us to go beyond the earthly realm into God\u2019s
          life in the Spirit (see  ). When the river is this deep, we will become
          totally dependent upon the Holy Spirit to teach, guide, and empower us.
          Human intellect will not be able to fathom the depth of this Spirit-River.     
          The implication of this sentence is that Ezekiel was in the river and had
          to return to the bank.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When I got there, I was astonished to see [[COMMENT(0)]] an enormous
        number of trees on each side of the river.   '
      comments:
      - number: 47:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cbehold, I saw.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "He said, \u201CThis water flows east, down to the Jordan Valley [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and to the Dead Sea. As it flows into the stagnant waters, that water becomes
        fresh water.   "
      comments:
      - number: 47:8
        content: "  Or \u201CArabah,\u201D which in the time of Ezekiel referred
          to the rift valley through which the Jordan River flows until it empties
          into the Dead Sea.      See  .    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Wherever the river [[COMMENT(0)]] flows, all living creatures will
        live and thrive. Schools of fish will be very plentiful, for wherever the
        river goes, it brings healing, and everything will come alive! '
      comments:
      - number: 47:9
        content: "  Or literally \u201Ctwo rivers.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Fishermen [[COMMENT(0)]] will crowd its banks and spread their nets
        from En-Gedi  to En-Eglaim.  They will catch as many species of fish as there
        are in the Great Sea.   '
      comments:
      - number: 47:10
        content: "  This healing river of God\u2019s Spirit brings life. It points
          us to the gospel being preached by the Lord\u2019s \u201Cfishermen,\u201D
          his kingdom evangelists (see    and footnote).        means \u201Cthe fountain
          of the kid.\u201D      En-Eglaim may possibly be Ain-el-Feshkah, a village
          on the northwest end of the Dead Sea.    means \u201Cfountains of two calves\u201D
          or \u201Cfountain of two pools.\u201D      That is, the Mediterranean Sea
          (see vv.  ,  ,  ).    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: However, its swamps and marshes will not become healed but will be
        left for salt. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 47:11
        content: "  This verse illustrates a significant interpretive feature of
          this vision, namely, that it is not a picture of ecological perfection.
          The statement that the swamps and marshes will not be purified by the remarkable
          river flowing down from the Jerusalem temple but will be left as stagnant
          pools, polluted by excessive salt, reflects a less than perfect renewal.
          Now, while this vision describes a truly remarkable transformation of the
          land of promise, and the ecological purification of the Dead Sea, it is
          incomplete. The language of this vision is couched in terms of revived
          natural vegetation, ecology, and wildlife\u2014marine creatures in particular\u2014but
          the full realization of this divine transformation will not come about
          until the return of the Lord Jesus. And that vision is given to us in the
          final two chapters of Holy Scripture\u2014. It is there\u2014and only there\u2014that
          the full and perfect consummation of God\u2019s redemptive plans and purposes
          for his people is revealed. And significantly, while explicit images of
          Ezekiel\u2019s vision are retained in  , the full import of John\u2019s
          vision is profoundly spiritual and transcends the physical realities of
          a fallen world that will one day be renewed and transformed forever.    "
    - name: '12: The Boundaries of the Holy Land'
      title: The Boundaries of the Holy Land
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CAlong both banks of the river, every kind of fruit tree will
        flourish. And their leaves will never wither, and abundant fruit will always
        be on their branches. Each month they will bear a fresh crop of fruit because
        this life-giving water comes from inside the sanctuary. And their fruit will
        be good to eat, and the leaves will bring healing.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 47:12
        content: '  See    for the fulfillment of this phenomenon.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> says: \u201CBehold, here are the
        territorial boundaries for your distribution of land among the twelve tribes
        of Israel. Joseph shall receive a double portion. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 47:13
        content: "  Joseph\u2019s two portions would remind Israel\u2019s tribes
          that Joseph\u2019s family line divided into two tribes, Manasseh and Ephraim.
          There was no \u201Ctribe of Joseph\u201D but of his two sons.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: You will each have a fair share of it since I swore to your ancestors
        that I would give it to them. So now, this land will belong to you as family
        property.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CThese will be the borders of the land. [[COMMENT(0)]] The northern
        border starts at the Mediterranean Sea and stretches east along the road
        to the town of Hethlon,  through Hamath Pass, to the town of Zedad,   "
      comments:
      - number: 47:15
        content: "  Verses    are similar to the division of the land under Moses
          in  . It will help to compare these two passages, especially in light of
          the textual difficulty in understanding exact locations found here in Ezekiel\u2019s
          account (see the footnotes for  ).      Possibly modern Haitela.      As
          translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cthe entrance of Zedad,
          Hamath.\u201D Zedad is possibly modern Sadad, southeast of Homs.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'and then on to the towns of Berothah [[COMMENT(0)]] and Sibraim. 
        These two towns are on the border between Damascus and Hamath. It will extend
        as far as Hazer-ha-Tikon, which is on the border of the region of Hauran.   '
      comments:
      - number: 47:16
        content: '  Berothah is possibly the same as Berothai (see  ), modern Bereitan.     
          Sibraim may possibly be modern Ziphron (see  ).      Hauran is sometimes
          equated with Bashan, the mountainous region east of Lake Galilee.    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'So, your northern frontier will extend from the sea to Hazer-Enon,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] which is north of Damascus and the border of Hamath on the
        north. '
      comments:
      - number: 47:17
        content: '  Most scholars identify Hazar-Enon with modern Qaryatein.     
          The Hebrew of v.    is uncertain.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CThe Jordan River will serve as your eastern border between
        Hauran and Damascus, between Gilead and Israel, down to the Dead Sea as far
        south as Tamar. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 47:18
        content: '  The Hebrew of this last clause is uncertain.  '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CYour southern border stretches west from Tamar southward to
        the waters of Meribah-Kadesh, following the dry riverbed to the Mediterranean
        Sea; that will be your southern border. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: And your western boundary will follow the coast of the Mediterranean
        Sea from the southern border north to the point opposite Hamath Pass; that
        will be the western frontier.
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CDivide this land among the tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'You must distribute it as an inheritance for yourselves and the resident
        aliens who live among you, who have their children among you, since you must
        treat them as citizens of Israel. They must receive a share of the land for
        their inheritance with you among the tribes of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "In whatever tribe the resident alien resides, that is where you will
        assign his share. I, Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, have spoken.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1-7: Distribution of the LandSpecial Land at the Center of the Country'
      title: Distribution of the LandSpecial Land at the Center of the Country
      number: 1-7
      content: "\u201CThis is the list of the tribes and the land they are to receive.
        The border follows the Hethlon road to the boundary between Damascus and
        Hamath. The territory for each tribe will extend all the way across the country
        from east to west. Starting from the north, the tribes are:DanAsherNaphtaliManassehEphraimReubenJudah.\u201D"
      comments: []
